module.exports={"fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba-vs-hacienda-tres-rios":{"keyDifferences":"Both are luxury family all-inclusives in the Playa del Carmen area at the same price tier, but their ratings and amenity depth diverge sharply. Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba leads on nearly every metric: overall (9.8 vs 8.5), food (9.0 vs 6.4, a striking 2.6-point gap), pool (8.6 vs 6.3), atmosphere (8.8 vs 6.8), and sleep quality (9.4 vs 8.1). Rooms are comparable but Fairmont edges ahead (9.7 vs 8.7). Beach scores are low at both properties, reflecting the area's rocky coastline rather than resort shortcomings, though Fairmont rates noticeably higher even there (6.5 vs 3.8). Fairmont's amenity list is vastly broader — kids club, spa, golf, tennis, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, yoga, hiking, babysitting, and bicycles versus Hacienda Tres Rios's beach-only listing. Hacienda Tres Rios leans on its natural river and cenote setting as its identity, while Fairmont delivers polished, full-service resort luxury with consistently exceptional ratings across the board.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples who want the highest-rated luxury all-inclusive experience near Playa del Carmen, with exceptional food, spacious rooms accommodating five or more guests, a full activity roster including golf, tennis, archery, and watersports, and service and cleanliness ratings that sit at the very top of the category.","whoShouldChooseB":"Eco-minded families drawn to a nature-reserve setting with cenotes, rivers, and jungle surroundings who are willing to trade a lower food score and fewer amenities for a quieter, more naturalistic atmosphere and a resort identity built around its unique Tres Rios river ecosystem.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Riviera Maya's dry season, November through April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity is manageable. December through March is peak season with the best weather but highest rates at both properties. May through October brings heat, humidity, and hurricane risk, with the quietest crowds and lower pricing — a reasonable trade-off at either resort for budget-conscious travelers.","activities":"Both resorts sit within reach of the Riviera Maya's standout attractions: Tulum ruins, Cobá, and multiple cenotes are within an hour's drive. Fairmont's on-site options include golf, tennis, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, yoga, hiking, and bicycles. Hacienda Tres Rios centers its activity offering on its natural reserve — river kayaking, cenote swimming, and nature trails — making the resort itself the destination for guests drawn to the surrounding ecosystem."},"fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba-vs-sunset-royal-beach-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a luxury villa-style family resort set within the Mayakoba ecological reserve near Playa del Carmen, with an exceptional overall rating of 9.8 versus Sunset Royal Beach Resort's 8.3. The gaps are sharpest in food (9.0 vs 6.2), atmosphere (8.8 vs 6.3), pool (8.6 vs 6.0), and room quality (9.7 vs 8.1). Fairmont's location score of 9.8 reflects its unique lagoon-and-jungle setting, while Sunset Royal's 8.7 speaks to a more conventional Cancun Hotel Zone position with a notably better beach score (7.8 vs 6.5). Fairmont carries an extensive amenity list including a kids club, spa, golf, tennis, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, yoga, and babysitting, while Sunset Royal's amenity set is not comparably documented. At the same price tier, Fairmont delivers meaningfully higher guest satisfaction across almost every dimension. Sunset Royal competes on beach access and a recognizable Cancun strip location, but trails badly on food, atmosphere, and pool experience.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who want an ultra-premium, nature-immersed Mexican resort experience with villa-style accommodation, an exceptional service record, and a full suite of activities including golf, spa, watersports, and a kids club, and who prioritize refined atmosphere over a wide open beach.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a large-format Cancun Hotel Zone all-inclusive with direct beach access and a familiar resort-strip setting at the luxury price point, and who are less focused on food quality, pool experience, or distinctive atmosphere.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in the Yucatán Peninsula's peak season window of December through April, when rainfall is minimal and temperatures are comfortable. July and August bring heat and humidity to both Playa del Carmen and Cancun. Hurricane season runs June through November, with September and October carrying the highest risk. Shoulder months of May and late November offer lower rates with manageable weather at both properties.","activities":"Fairmont Mayakoba guests can snorkel, windsurf, do yoga, play tennis, golf, archery, and explore the surrounding Mayakoba ecological reserve by bicycle or on foot through jungle trails. The broader Playa del Carmen area offers cenote diving, Coba ruins, and the Quinta Avenida strip. Sunset Royal guests have the Cancun Hotel Zone on their doorstep, with easy access to Isla Mujeres ferry, Xcaret and Xel-Há eco-parks, and Chichén Itzá day trips."},"fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba-vs-occidental-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a luxury fractional-ownership resort on the Riviera Maya near Playa del Carmen, set within the eco-reserve canal system of Mayakoba, with an extraordinary overall rating of 9.8, rooms rated 9.7, and service at 9.7. It offers a sprawling amenity list: kids club, golf, tennis, spa, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, yoga, babysitting, and hiking trails through mangroves. Occidental Cozumel is a mid-market family all-inclusive on Cozumel island, rated 8.0 overall, with food scoring just 6.3 and pool at 6.0, well below Fairmont's marks. Occidental's location rating of 8.3 reflects its proximity to world-class diving reefs, which is its primary draw, but its amenity list is nearly bare beyond a beach. Fairmont costs significantly more but delivers across every rated category, while Occidental trades on Cozumel's famous reef diving at a more accessible price point. If you want elevated luxury with extensive amenities in a unique eco-resort setting near Playa del Carmen, choose Fairmont. If you want an affordable, no-frills island base for reef diving on Cozumel, choose Occidental.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples seeking a top-rated luxury all-inclusive experience within the Mayakoba eco-reserve, where exceptional service scores of 9.7, spacious rooms that sleep five or more, a golf course, spa, and activities from archery to yoga justify the premium price tag.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families and divers who want an affordable, straightforward island base on Cozumel with easy access to some of the Caribbean's best reef diving, and who are willing to accept modest food, pool, and atmosphere scores in exchange for a lower nightly rate.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in Mexico's Yucatan region, sharing the same dry, sunny high season from December through April. Summer months bring heat, humidity, and occasional tropical storms, with hurricane risk peaking September through October. Cozumel's diving visibility is exceptional year-round but is at its clearest November through May. Mayakoba's lush canal ecosystem is beautiful in any season, though the eco-reserve feels especially vibrant in the drier winter months.","activities":"Fairmont Mayakoba guests can golf the El Camaleón PGA Tour course, kayak and bike through mangrove canals, take yoga classes, try archery, and snorkel the property's lagoon system, with Playa del Carmen's shops and cenotes nearby. Occidental Cozumel guests are best positioned for scuba diving and snorkelling the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, with dive shops and the town of San Miguel a short taxi ride away."},"fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba-vs-park-royal-beach-cancun":{"keyDifferences":"Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a luxury fractional-ownership villa resort set within the Mayakoba ecological reserve near Playa del Carmen, delivering exceptional across-the-board ratings: overall 9.8, rooms 9.7, service 9.7, cleanliness 9.8, and food 9.0. Park Royal Beach Cancun sits on Cancun's Hotel Zone with a stronger beach score (7.8 vs 6.5) but trails Fairmont in every other meaningful category — food scores 6.1 vs 9.0, pool 6.0 vs 8.6, atmosphere 6.2 vs 8.8, and rooms 7.8 vs 9.7. Fairmont's amenity list is extensive: golf, tennis, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, spa, kids club, babysitting, hiking, yoga, and pet-friendly rooms for five or more guests. Park Royal offers a conventional Cancun Hotel Zone all-inclusive experience at a lower effective cost. If you want a near-flawless luxury resort in the Mayakoba reserve with outstanding rooms and service, choose Fairmont. If you want a straightforward beachfront Cancun all-inclusive with a solid beach rating at a more modest price, choose Park Royal.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples seeking a premium, villa-style all-inclusive in the serene Mayakoba reserve, where exceptional service, spacious rooms that sleep five or more, a full activity roster including golf and archery, and pet-friendly policies justify the top-tier price point.","whoShouldChooseB":"Budget-conscious families who prioritise a genuine Cancun Hotel Zone beachfront location and a simple, familiar all-inclusive format over elevated food, atmosphere, or room quality, and who don't require the deep amenity list of a luxury property.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Mexican Caribbean's dry season, December through April, when rainfall is lowest and humidity manageable. Mayakoba's lagoon and jungle setting can feel humid in summer but remains lush and green. Cancun's peak is December to March; hurricane season runs June through November for both areas, with September the highest-risk month. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates with generally acceptable weather at either property.","activities":"Fairmont Mayakoba guests can explore the resort's jungle waterways by kayak or bicycle, play golf on the El Camaleón PGA Tour course, practice archery, snorkel, windsurf, hike reserve trails, and take yoga classes on-site. Park Royal guests are minutes from Cancun's Hotel Zone water parks, jet-ski rentals, deep-sea fishing charters, and the Nichupté Lagoon, with downtown Cancun nightlife and ferry connections to Isla Mujeres easily accessible."},"fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba-vs-the-reef-coco-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a luxury family resort set within the Mayakoba ecological reserve near Playa del Carmen, commanding a $$$$ price point and earning exceptional ratings across nearly every category: overall 9.8, rooms 9.7, service 9.7, and cleanliness 9.8. The Reef Coco Beach is a mid-market $$$ family all-inclusive near Cancun with noticeably weaker scores across the board: overall 8.1, food 6.2, pool 5.8, beach 5.3, and atmosphere 6.2. The ratings gap is stark and consistent. Fairmont's amenity list is extensive, covering golf, tennis, spa, snorkelling, windsurfing, archery, yoga, babysitting, a kids club, and even pet-friendly rooms, while Reef Coco Beach's standout feature is essentially its waterpark for older kids. Fairmont's beach scores just 6.5, suggesting the lagoon-reserve setting limits direct beach access, but everything else outperforms Reef Coco Beach by a wide margin. Reef Coco Beach offers a cheaper entry point near Cancun with a waterpark, but guests pay for that savings in nearly every measurable quality metric.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or multi-generational groups willing to pay a premium for an exceptional resort experience within a protected ecological reserve, who want a full suite of amenities including golf, spa, kids club, babysitting, and watersports, and place high value on room quality, service, and overall polish.","whoShouldChooseB":"Budget-conscious families with older kids who prioritize a waterpark over refined dining or atmosphere, want a straightforward Cancun-area all-inclusive at a lower price point, and are comfortable trading lower food, pool, and atmosphere scores for a more accessible nightly rate.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula dry season, roughly December through April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity is lower. Peak weeks around Christmas, New Year, and spring break drive up prices sharply at both properties. Shoulder months of May and November offer better availability and rates, though the Atlantic hurricane season runs June through November and warrants travel insurance.","activities":"Mayakoba guests have access to golf, tennis, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, bicycles, hiking, and yoga within the reserve, plus the broader Playa del Carmen strip for cenote tours, diving, and the Quinta Avenida shopping corridor. Reef Coco Beach's on-site activity list is thin beyond its waterpark, but its Cancun-area location gives families easy access to Xcaret, Xel-Há, cenotes, Isla Mujeres ferry trips, and Chichen Itza day tours."},"cozumel-hotel-and-resort-vs-fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba":{"keyDifferences":"Cozumel Hotel & Resort is a budget-friendly family property on Cozumel island with a beach and solid fundamentals: overall 8.0, cleanliness 8.1, service 8.1, and strong value at 8.0, but notably weak food (5.8), pool (5.7), and beach (3.3) ratings that point to a no-frills operation. Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a premium family resort in the Playa del Carmen corridor scoring near-perfect across almost every category: overall 9.8, rooms 9.7, service 9.7, cleanliness 9.8, and atmosphere 8.8, with an extensive amenity list including kids club, spa, golf, tennis, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, yoga, babysitting, and evening entertainment. The gap between them is stark: Mayakoba outscores Cozumel by 2.0 points overall, 3.2 on food, 3.0 on pool, and 2.9 on atmosphere. Cozumel offers island access and decent value at a low price point; Mayakoba delivers a genuinely comprehensive luxury family resort at a significantly higher one. If you want an affordable Cozumel base with beach access and good service fundamentals, choose Cozumel Hotel & Resort. If you want a near-flawless luxury family all-inclusive with exceptional rooms, service, and activities, choose Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba.","whoShouldChooseA":"Budget-conscious families or couples using Cozumel as a base for island exploration and diving who prioritise location, value, and clean, well-serviced rooms over resort amenities and dining quality. Best suited to guests who plan to spend most of their time off-property.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families and couples willing to pay premium rates for an exceptional all-inclusive experience with top-rated rooms, service, and a wide activity roster including golf, spa, snorkelling, yoga, and kids club. Guests who want to stay on-property and have every need met at the highest level.","whenToVisit":"Both properties sit along Mexico's Caribbean coast and share similar weather patterns. December through April offers dry, sunny conditions ideal for either resort. Avoid late August through October when hurricane season peaks. Mayakoba's lush lagoon setting can feel humid in summer; Cozumel benefits from sea breezes year-round. The island ferry schedule to Cozumel is worth checking around major Mexican holidays.","activities":"Cozumel is world-renowned for diving and snorkelling on its protected reef system, with numerous dive operators accessible from the resort. Fairmont Mayakoba sits within the larger Mayakoba complex, giving guests access to an El Camaleón golf course, cycling through mangrove trails, watersports on the lagoon and beach, archery, yoga, and easy access to Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue shopping and nearby Mayan ruins at Tulum and Cobá."},"fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba-vs-the-sens-cancun":{"keyDifferences":"Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a luxury family resort in the Mayakoba eco-reserve near Playa del Carmen, built around jungle lagoons with an extraordinary overall rating of 9.8 versus The Sens Cancun's 8.1. The gaps are significant across nearly every category: rooms (9.7 vs 8.1), food (9.0 vs 6.4), atmosphere (8.8 vs 6.2), pool (8.6 vs 6.0), and sleep quality (9.4 vs 7.9). Fairmont's amenity list is vastly deeper — golf, spa, tennis, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, hiking, yoga, babysitting, and bicycles — while The Sens Cancun offers a kids club, pool slide, and a small waterpark for little ones. The Sens does edge Fairmont on beach rating (7.3 vs 6.5), reflecting its direct Cancun Hotel Zone beachfront. Fairmont commands a premium for good reason: it is a genuine luxury eco-resort experience. The Sens is a more modest Cancun family property where the beach and kids' water features are the main draws but service and food ratings suggest a more inconsistent guest experience.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a genuinely exceptional luxury experience in a natural lagoon setting near Playa del Carmen, with top-tier service, expansive amenities including golf, spa, archery, and watersports, and some of the highest room and food ratings available at a Mexican all-inclusive.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with young children primarily motivated by a solid Cancun Hotel Zone beachfront and fun water features like a pool slide and toddler waterpark, who are comfortable trading atmosphere, food quality, and room refinement for a lower entry point into the premium Cancun market.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's Caribbean coast dry season, roughly December through April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity manageable. Mayakoba's jungle-lagoon setting can feel more intense during humid summer months. Cancun's Hotel Zone draws large spring break crowds in March and April. For either property, January through early March offers the best balance of weather and fewer peak-season crowds.","activities":"At Fairmont Mayakoba, guests can explore jungle lagoon trails by bicycle or on foot, snorkel, windsurf, practice archery, play golf on the adjacent El Camaleón course, and join yoga classes. Both resorts are within range of Xcaret and Xel-Há eco-parks, Tulum ruins, and cenote swimming. The Sens guests are well-placed for Cancun Hotel Zone water activities, nearby Isla Mujeres day trips, and the Cancun Underwater Museum snorkel experience."},"fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba-vs-royalton-riviera-cancun":{"keyDifferences":"Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a luxury fractional-ownership villa resort set within the Mayakoba eco-complex near Playa del Carmen, with private residences sleeping 5 or more, a kids club, golf, tennis, archery, hiking, yoga, snorkelling, windsurfing, babysitting, and bicycles on a lagoon-laced mangrove property. Royalton Riviera Cancun is a conventional large-scale family all-inclusive on the Cancun hotel strip with a waterpark for small children, casino, spa, buffet, and watersports. The rating gap is stark: Fairmont leads on overall score (9.8 vs 8.2), food (9 vs 7), pool (8.6 vs 7.1), atmosphere (8.8 vs 6.8), room quality (9.7 vs 8.4), service (9.7 vs 8.3), and cleanliness (9.8 vs 8.6). Beach scores are low at both, but Fairmont's lagoon setting is by design while Royalton's weak beach score (4) reflects a genuinely poor shoreline. Fairmont is a quieter, villa-style retreat with exceptional service and space; Royalton is a bustling, more affordable conventional all-inclusive with a casino and a small waterpark.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or groups who want a high-end, villa-style Mexican retreat with expansive private residences, outstanding service, golf, nature-based activities, and the refined atmosphere of the Mayakoba eco-complex rather than a conventional all-inclusive hotel experience.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with young children who want a traditional large-scale Cancun all-inclusive with a casino, buffet dining, and a small waterpark, and who prioritise convenience and price point over atmosphere, beach quality, or elevated service.","whenToVisit":"Both properties benefit from the Riviera Maya's dry season, running November through April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity is lower. July and August bring school-holiday crowds and higher prices at both. Hurricane season peaks September and October, when rates drop but weather risk increases. Fairmont's lagoon setting makes it more sheltered from wind than Royalton's exposed beachfront position.","activities":"Fairmont guests can explore Mayakoba's lagoon network by bicycle or kayak, play golf on the El Camaleon PGA Tour course, take yoga classes, snorkel, try archery, or hike mangrove trails. Both resorts offer watersports rentals and snorkelling. Royalton guests have the casino on-site and the Cancun hotel zone's bars, shops, and excursion infrastructure nearby. Cenote tours, Tulum ruins, and Xcaret parks are accessible from both locations."},"fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba-vs-krystal-grand-cancun":{"keyDifferences":"Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a luxury villa-style family all-inclusive set within the Mayakoba ecological reserve near Playa del Carmen, with an extraordinary overall rating of 9.8 versus Krystal Grand Cancún's 8.2. The gap is most pronounced in food (9.0 vs 6.4), atmosphere (8.8 vs 6.2), pool (8.6 vs 6.0), room quality (9.7 vs 8.0), and service (9.7 vs 8.3). Fairmont scores slightly lower on beach (6.5 vs 7.8), reflecting its lagoon-reserve setting rather than a direct beachfront. Krystal Grand sits on Cancún's Hotel Zone with better beach access and a strong location score of 8.7, but falls short across nearly every experiential metric. Fairmont brings a resort-within-a-resort feel with golf, archery, hiking, yoga, snorkelling, windsurfing, and bicycles through mangrove-lined waterways, while Krystal Grand offers a more conventional Cancún all-inclusive. If you want near-perfect service, food, and rooms in a nature-rich Riviera Maya setting, choose Fairmont. If you want solid beachfront Cancún access at a more predictable all-inclusive experience, choose Krystal Grand.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples willing to pay a premium for an exceptional villa-style experience inside a nature reserve, where outstanding service, spacious rooms accommodating five or more guests, and a curated activity program from archery to yoga matter more than a wide open beachfront.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a familiar, full-service all-inclusive directly on Cancún's Hotel Zone beach, with straightforward access to Cancún's nightlife, shopping, and attractions, and are comfortable trading top-tier food and atmosphere for a lower entry price and a classic beach-facing setup.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Yucatán Peninsula's dry season, roughly December through April, when humidity is lower and rainfall minimal. Avoid hurricane season's peak, August through October. Fairmont Mayakoba's jungle-lagoon setting can feel especially lush just after the rainy season in November, while Cancún's Hotel Zone is busiest and most expensive over US spring break in March.","activities":"Fairmont Mayakoba guests can explore mangrove canals by bicycle or kayak, play the acclaimed El Camaleón PGA golf course, take yoga and archery sessions, and snorkel offshore reefs, with Playa del Carmen's boutiques and the Mayan ruins of Tulum nearby. Krystal Grand guests enjoy Cancún's Hotel Zone beach, close proximity to Isla Mujeres day trips, Xcaret and Xel-Há eco-parks, and the Cancún city nightlife corridor."},"crown-paradise-club-cancun-vs-fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba":{"keyDifferences":"Crown Paradise Club Cancun is a family-focused all-inclusive on the Cancun hotel strip with a kids club for under-4s, solid cleanliness (8.2) and service (8.2) scores, but notably weak food (6.1), pool (6.5), and atmosphere (6.2) ratings that drag its overall to 8.0. Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a villa-style family all-inclusive in the Riviera Maya's Mayakoba complex near Playa del Carmen, with near-perfect scores across almost every category: overall 9.8, rooms 9.7, service 9.7, cleanliness 9.8, and a vastly superior food rating of 9.0. The amenity gap is equally stark — Fairmont offers golf, tennis, spa, snorkelling, windsurfing, archery, yoga, hiking, babysitting, and bicycles, while Crown Paradise lists only a kids club for toddlers. Crown Paradise trades on Cancun's lively hotel zone location (8.1) and relative accessibility; Fairmont delivers a serene, resort-within-a-resort experience at a premium. Both share the same price tier, making Fairmont the objectively stronger value proposition despite identical pricing.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with toddlers or very young children who want a straightforward Cancun hotel-zone all-inclusive with decent beach access, good service, and the convenience of Cancun's central location — and who don't need an extensive activity program or exceptional dining.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families, couples, or multi-generational groups who want a near-flawless villa-style all-inclusive experience in the Riviera Maya, with exceptional rooms, top-rated service, a full activity roster including golf, spa, and watersports, and a serene Mayakoba setting far removed from the Cancun strip.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Yucatan Peninsula's dry season, December through April, when humidity is lower and rain is rare. Peak weeks around Christmas, New Year, and spring break push prices up and crowds higher at Cancun particularly. Shoulder months of May and November offer better availability; hurricane season runs June through October, with September the riskiest month for either destination.","activities":"Crown Paradise guests are well-placed for Cancun's hotel zone beaches, nearby water parks, and day trips to Isla Mujeres or Chichen Itza. Fairmont Mayakoba guests can snorkel, windsurf, kayak, hike, cycle through mangrove lagoons, practice archery, play golf, and take yoga classes on site, with Tulum, Coba ruins, and cenote swimming all accessible as day excursions from the Playa del Carmen area."},"fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba-vs-planet-hollywood-cancun":{"keyDifferences":"Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a luxury private-residence-style family resort in the Mayakoba ecosystem near Playa del Carmen, rated 9.8 overall against Planet Hollywood Cancun's 8.3, with standout scores in room quality (9.7 vs 8.6), service (9.7 vs 8.7), and atmosphere (8.8 vs 7.2). Mayakoba's beach rating is notably lower at 6.5 versus Planet Hollywood's 7.5, reflecting its lagoon-laced jungle setting rather than a traditional beachfront. Planet Hollywood sits in Costa Mujeres with a waterpark, flowrider, and lazy river that Mayakoba entirely lacks, making it the more conventional splash-and-play all-inclusive. Fairmont compensates with an extraordinary amenity breadth: golf, tennis, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, yoga, hiking, babysitting, and pet-friendly rooms. Planet Hollywood's food scores lag at 7.2 versus Mayakoba's 9.0, a meaningful gap at the same price tier. Mayakoba is about refined, nature-immersed luxury; Planet Hollywood is about branded entertainment and water attractions in a busy Cancun-corridor setting.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who want elite service, a jungle-lagoon ecosystem, and a wide activity range including golf, archery, and watersports, and who prioritise room quality, cuisine, and a serene atmosphere over big waterpark features.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with kids who want a recognisable branded all-inclusive with a flowrider, lazy river, and waterpark, and are happy to trade some service polish and food quality for high-energy water attractions on a proper beach in Costa Mujeres.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in the Yucatán corridor where the dry season runs November through April, offering the most reliable sunshine and lowest humidity. July and August are popular for families despite heat and humidity. Hurricane season peaks September through October; Planet Hollywood's exposed Costa Mujeres beach may feel that more acutely than Mayakoba's sheltered lagoon setting.","activities":"At Mayakoba, guests can golf the El Camaleón PGA Tour course, kayak and snorkel jungle lagoons, practice archery, take yoga classes, cycle the resort's trail network, and access the Riviera Maya's cenotes nearby. At Planet Hollywood, the flowrider, lazy river, and waterpark dominate on-site entertainment, while Costa Mujeres offers proximity to Isla Mujeres snorkelling trips and Cancun's nightlife corridor."},"azulik-tulum-vs-fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba":{"keyDifferences":"AZULIK Tulum is an adults-only eco-luxury retreat in Tulum built into the jungle canopy with no conventional beach or pool to speak of — its beach rating of 4.8 and pool rating of 5.0 reflect that deliberately — but it compensates with a near-perfect atmosphere score of 9.5, the highest single rating either property posts. Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a full-service family all-inclusive in the Mayakoba resort corridor near Playa del Carmen with a 9.8 overall rating, 9.7 service score, 9.7 room score, and a broad amenity list covering kids club, golf, tennis, snorkelling, windsurfing, archery, babysitting, and hiking. Fairmont wins on almost every operational metric — value (8.9 vs 7.2), cleanliness (9.8 vs 8.5), sleep quality (9.4 vs 8.3) — while AZULIK leads only in atmosphere and location feel. These are fundamentally different properties: AZULIK is a design-forward adults-only jungle experience; Fairmont is a polished, amenity-rich family resort.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults and couples who prioritise immersive design, jungle atmosphere, and an unconventional Tulum experience over beach access, pools, or operational polish. Best for those who want a distinctive, Instagram-worthy retreat and are comfortable paying a premium for aesthetics over amenities.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families and couples who want a high-performing, full-service Mexican all-inclusive with exceptional service, spacious rooms, a kids club, babysitting, golf, and watersports. The 9.8 overall and value scores make it one of the most broadly satisfying options in the Riviera Maya.","whenToVisit":"Both properties sit in Mexico's Yucatán coast climate zone. Peak season runs December through April with dry, sunny weather and lower humidity — ideal for outdoor activities at Fairmont and jungle walks at AZULIK. May through October brings heat, humidity, and hurricane-season risk, with September being the least advisable month. Tulum can feel oppressively humid in summer; Mayakoba's air-conditioned facilities buffer that more effectively.","activities":"Fairmont Mayakoba offers golf, tennis, snorkelling, windsurfing, archery, hiking, yoga, and bicycles within its lagoon-and-canal eco-resort setting, with Playa del Carmen shopping and cenotes nearby. AZULIK Tulum is centred on its jungle setting, with access to Tulum's archaeological ruins, cenote swimming, and the Sian Ka'an Biosphere Reserve — activities are nature- and culture-driven rather than resort-facility-driven."},"fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba-vs-hotel-krystal-cancun":{"keyDifferences":"Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a luxury family all-inclusive in Playa del Carmen's Mayakoba estate, scoring 9.8 overall versus Hotel Krystal Cancun's 8.0, with a 1.8-point gap that reflects a fundamentally different tier of experience. Mayakoba's room rating of 9.7 against Krystal's 7.6 and service rating of 9.7 against Krystal's 7.9 underscore the difference in quality. Mayakoba offers an extraordinary amenity roster including golf, tennis, spa, kids club, babysitting, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, yoga, hiking, and bicycles within a lush ecological reserve, while Krystal Cancun lists only beach access. Atmosphere scores tell the same story: 8.8 versus 6.2. Krystal Cancun's beach rating of 7.8 edges Mayakoba's 6.5, and its $$ price advantage is real, sitting at $$$ versus $$$$. Krystal is a serviceable budget-conscious Cancun hotel zone option; Mayakoba is a premium sanctuary for families who want exceptional rooms, broad programming, and an immersive ecological setting near Playa del Carmen.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples willing to pay a premium for near-perfect service, stunning rooms, and an extensive activity program inside a protected natural reserve. Those who want golf, spa, archery, watersports, yoga, and a kids club all in one meticulously maintained, high-rated property near Playa del Carmen.","whoShouldChooseB":"Budget-conscious families who prioritize Cancun's hotel zone location and direct beach access over amenities and atmosphere. Guests who want a straightforward, recognizable Mexican all-inclusive in central Cancun at a lower price point and are comfortable with more modest food, pool, and atmosphere scores.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Yucatan Peninsula's dry season from December through April, with the lowest humidity and minimal rain. Avoid hurricane season peak from August through October. Mayakoba's jungle lagoon setting can feel humid in summer months, while Cancun's coastal breeze makes Krystal slightly more comfortable in shoulder-season heat. December through March offers the best overall conditions at both properties.","activities":"Mayakoba guests can explore the resort's lagoon ecosystem by bicycle or kayak, take archery and yoga classes, snorkel, windsurf, and play golf or tennis without leaving the estate, with Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue shopping and Tulum's ruins nearby. Krystal Cancun guests have direct beach access and the full Cancun hotel zone on their doorstep, with proximity to Isla Mujeres ferry, Chichen Itza day trips, and the Cancun nightlife strip."},"fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba-vs-kore-tulum-retreat-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a family-oriented luxury all-inclusive in the Mayakoba resort complex near Playa del Carmen, set within a lagoon-and-jungle environment with an extraordinary 9.8 overall rating, 9.7 for rooms, and 9.7 for service. Kore Tulum Retreat and Spa Resort is an adults-only property in Tulum rated 7.9 overall, with notably weaker scores across food (6.8 vs 9.0), pool (6.0 vs 8.6), atmosphere (7.0 vs 8.8), and a beach rating of just 1.5 compared to Fairmont's 6.5. The gap in room quality is narrower (8.4 vs 9.7) but still significant. Fairmont offers a vastly broader amenity set including a kids club, golf, archery, windsurfing, babysitting, and pets, while Kore Tulum has no listed amenities beyond its retreat positioning. Fairmont is the clear premium choice on nearly every measurable dimension; Kore Tulum's main differentiator is its Tulum address and adults-only focus, but its ratings do not support a luxury price point the way Fairmont's do.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples seeking ultra-luxury in a well-maintained, lagoon-side Mayakoba setting who want exceptional service, spacious rooms accommodating five or more guests, a full activity roster including golf and watersports, and ratings that consistently justify the top-tier price.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults without children drawn specifically to Tulum's bohemian aesthetic and cenote-rich surroundings who prioritize location over resort amenities, and who are willing to accept middling food, pool, and beach scores in exchange for a quieter, retreat-style atmosphere.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in Mexico's Yucatán Caribbean coast, sharing the same optimal window of December through April when humidity is lower, rainfall minimal, and seas calm. Avoid late August through October for hurricane risk. Tulum can feel more humid and buggy year-round given its jungle proximity, while Mayakoba's lagoon setting provides some natural buffer from coastal weather extremes.","activities":"Fairmont Mayakoba guests access golf, tennis, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, hiking, yoga, and bicycle rentals on-site, plus the wider Mayakoba complex and nearby Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue. Kore Tulum's retreat positioning points guests outward to Tulum's cenotes, Mayan ruins at Tulum Archaeological Zone, jungle biking, and the Sian Ka'an Biosphere Reserve, with most active pursuits requiring off-property excursions."},"fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba-vs-senses-riviera-maya-by-artisan":{"keyDifferences":"Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a luxury family-oriented resort in the Mayakoba estate near Playa del Carmen, carrying a near-perfect overall rating of 9.8 against Senses Riviera Maya's 7.9. The gap is consistent across nearly every category: food scores 9.0 vs 6.8, pool 8.6 vs 6.0, atmosphere 8.8 vs 6.8, and room quality 9.7 vs 8.4. Fairmont's beach rating of 6.5 still edges out Senses' 5.3. Fairmont is a four-dollar-sign property offering an expansive amenity list — kids club, golf, tennis, spa, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, hiking, yoga, babysitting, and pet-friendly rooms — set within the renowned Mayakoba lagoon ecosystem. Senses is a budget adults-only option in Playa Paraiso with a two-dollar-sign price point and more modest infrastructure. If you want a premium family resort inside a world-class ecological development with exceptional service and rooms, choose Fairmont. If you want an affordable adults-only escape on the Riviera Maya without premium expectations, choose Senses.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples willing to pay a premium for one of the Riviera Maya's highest-rated resorts, where outstanding service scores of 9.7, spacious rooms accommodating five or more guests, a golf course, spa, and a full activity roster justify the four-dollar-sign price.","whoShouldChooseB":"Budget-conscious adult travelers who want a quiet, no-kids environment on the Riviera Maya at an accessible price point and are comfortable with more modest food, pool, and atmosphere ratings in exchange for solid cleanliness and sleep quality scores.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Riviera Maya's dry season running roughly December through April, when humidity drops and rainfall is minimal. Peak weeks around Christmas, New Year, and spring break push prices up sharply at Fairmont given its luxury positioning. Senses, at a lower price tier, sees less dramatic rate swings. May through October brings heat, humidity, and hurricane-season risk, though shoulder months like May and November offer reasonable value at both properties.","activities":"The Mayakoba estate surrounding Fairmont gives guests access to lagoon kayaking, cycling through mangrove paths, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, yoga, and a Greg Norman-designed golf course. Senses offers a simpler on-site program suited to relaxation rather than adventure. Both resorts sit within easy reach of Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue for shopping and dining, Xcaret and Xel-Ha eco-parks, and cenote diving across the Yucatan Peninsula."},"fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba-vs-hotel-dos-playas-faranda-cancun":{"keyDifferences":"Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a luxury family resort in the Riviera Maya's Mayakoba estate, rated 9.8 overall with standout scores for rooms (9.7), service (9.7), and cleanliness (9.8), offering a vast amenity list including a kids club, spa, golf course, tennis, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, yoga, babysitting, and pet-friendly accommodation. Hotel Dos Playas Faranda Cancun is a budget-friendly family property in Cancun rated 8.3 overall, with notably weaker scores for food (5.6 vs 9.0), pool (4.9 vs 8.6), and atmosphere (5.6 vs 8.8), and a bare-bones amenity set that amounts to little beyond a beach. The price gap is extreme—four price tiers separate them—and the experiential gap matches it. Mayakoba delivers a polished, resort-within-a-resort luxury experience in an eco-estate setting; Dos Playas delivers an affordable Cancun beachfront base with few extras. If you want a luxury Riviera Maya family resort with exceptional service, rooms, and activities at a premium price, go to Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba. If you want a low-cost Cancun beach base with minimal frills, go to Dos Playas Faranda.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples willing to pay a premium for an outstanding all-round resort experience—exceptional rooms, service, and cleanliness scores back that up—with a full activity roster including golf, spa, archery, watersports, and a kids club inside a managed eco-estate in the Riviera Maya.","whoShouldChooseB":"Budget-conscious families who primarily want a Cancun beach base at a low price point and don't need an extensive amenity set, entertainment program, or strong food offering—just affordable access to a Mexican beach with decent location scores.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Yucatán Peninsula's dry season, roughly December through April, when rainfall is minimal and temperatures are warm without being oppressive. Peak weeks around Christmas, New Year, and spring break push prices up significantly at Mayakoba given its luxury positioning. Shoulder months like May or November offer better value at both properties while still delivering reliable weather.","activities":"Mayakoba guests can tap into golf, tennis, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, yoga, hiking, and bicycles on the estate's lagoon and mangrove network, plus easy access to Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue and nearby Tulum ruins. Dos Playas guests are limited to the beach on-property but benefit from Cancun's Hotel Zone location, placing them close to water parks, Mayan ruins at Chichén Itzá, Isla Mujeres ferry trips, and the city's broad restaurant and nightlife scene."},"dreams-puerto-morelos-resort-and-spa-vs-fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Puerto Morelos and Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba are both family-oriented Mexican all-inclusives at the same price tier, but their ratings tell sharply different stories. Fairmont Mayakoba outscores Dreams across every single category: overall 9.8 vs 7.8, rooms 9.7 vs 8.5, service 9.7 vs 8.5, pool 8.6 vs 6.7, atmosphere 8.8 vs 6.9, and cleanliness 9.8 vs 8.6. Dreams' strongest suit is its waterparks for both young and older kids, making it a straightforward large-resort family play in Puerto Morelos. Fairmont Mayakoba is a villa-style resort set within the Mayakoba ecosystem near Playa del Carmen, with golf, tennis, archery, yoga, snorkelling, windsurfing, babysitting, and rooms that accommodate five or more guests — a dramatically broader activity roster and a far higher-rated overall experience. Dreams leans on its waterpark infrastructure for families with young children; Fairmont Mayakoba offers that breadth plus refinement for families who want top-tier rooms, service, and activities in a distinctive natural setting.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who prioritize waterparks and no-reservation dining in a straightforward large-resort all-inclusive format. Dreams Puerto Morelos suits those who want splash-pad and waterslide infrastructure as the centerpiece of their stay without paying a premium for elevated service or atmosphere.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families, multigenerational groups, and couples who want an exceptional overall experience with top-rated rooms, service, and a wide activity range including golf, tennis, archery, yoga, and watersports. Fairmont Mayakoba's villa-style setting and near-perfect ratings justify the same price tier for guests who want more than waterpark amenities.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Yucatan Peninsula's dry season, roughly December through April, when humidity drops and rainfall is minimal. Peak weeks around Christmas, New Year, and spring break push prices up and occupancy high at both properties. May through November brings heat, humidity, and hurricane-season risk, though shoulder months like May and November often offer better availability and value.","activities":"At Dreams Puerto Morelos, the waterparks for both young and older kids are the headline draw, supplemented by beach access. Fairmont Mayakoba offers a substantially richer menu: golf, tennis, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, yoga, hiking, bicycles, and watersports rentals within the Mayakoba ecological reserve. Both properties sit close to Puerto Morelos and Playa del Carmen, giving guests access to the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef for diving and the ruins at Tulum and Chichen Itza."},"fairmont-heritage-place-mayakoba-vs-maya-tulum-by-g-hotels":{"keyDifferences":"Fairmont Heritage Place Mayakoba is a luxury family all-inclusive in Playa del Carmen's upscale Mayakoba estate, rated 9.8 overall with standout scores for rooms (9.7), service (9.7), cleanliness (9.8), and location (9.8), backed by a deep amenity list including kids club, spa, golf, tennis, archery, snorkelling, windsurfing, yoga, and babysitting. Maya Tulum by G Hotels is a budget-friendly family property in Tulum rated 7.8 overall, with notably weaker scores across food (7.0 vs 9.0), pool (4.5 vs 8.6), and atmosphere (7.6 vs 8.8), though it holds a respectable location score of 8.5. The gap between these two is substantial: Fairmont delivers near-perfect execution at a premium price, while Maya Tulum offers a lower-cost entry point into the Tulum area with trade-offs in nearly every measurable category. If you want a polished, luxury Mexican all-inclusive with exceptional service and a full activity program, go Fairmont Mayakoba. If you want affordable family accommodation in Tulum and can accept more modest facilities, go Maya Tulum.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and discerning travelers who want a top-rated luxury Mexican all-inclusive with exceptional service, spacious rooms that accommodate five or more, a full activity roster including golf, spa, and watersports, and are willing to pay premium prices for near-flawless execution.","whoShouldChooseB":"Budget-conscious families who want a low-cost base in Tulum to explore the area's cenotes, ruins, and beaches without expecting resort-level amenities, and who prioritize location and value over pool quality, dining, or atmosphere.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's Yucatan dry season, roughly December through April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity is lower. Mayakoba and Tulum share similar weather patterns, so peak season runs concurrently. Visiting outside peak school holidays reduces crowds and rates at both properties, with shoulder months like May and November offering the best balance of decent weather and lower pricing.","activities":"Fairmont Mayakoba guests can snorkel, windsurf, play tennis and golf, take yoga classes, explore the Mayakoba lagoon system by bicycle or kayak, and book archery on-site. Maya Tulum's location gives guests easy access to Tulum's archaeological ruins, nearby cenotes, Sian Ka'an Biosphere Reserve, and the town's growing restaurant and wellness scene, compensating somewhat for the resort's thinner on-site activity offering."},"hyatt-zilara-cap-cana-vs-hyatt-ziva-puerto-vallarta":{"keyDifferences":"Hyatt Zilara Cap Cana is an adults-only all-inclusive on the Dominican Republic's upscale Cap Cana coast, earning a standout overall rating of 9.7 versus Hyatt Ziva Puerto Vallarta's solid 8.9. Zilara leads across nearly every scored category: rooms (9.5 vs 8.6), atmosphere (8.5 vs 7.5), pool (8.5 vs 7.3), food (8.5 vs 7.8), value (9.3 vs 8.7), and cleanliness (9.7 vs 9.0). Both properties share the same beach score (7.5) and sit at the same price tier. Ziva Puerto Vallarta is a family resort on Mexico's Pacific coast with a kids club, babysitting, diving, fishing, tennis, and rooms accommodating five or more guests — amenities Zilara simply doesn't offer. Zilara counters with a lazy river, yoga, nightclub, and a quieter adults-only atmosphere in a newer, purpose-built marina enclave. Service scores are close (9.6 vs 9.1), but Zilara's ratings reflect a more consistently polished experience. The gap is less about price and more about who is traveling.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults-only couples or groups who want a highly rated, polished Dominican Republic all-inclusive in the upscale Cap Cana enclave, with a lazy river, nightclub, yoga, and some of the strongest room and service scores in the Caribbean at this price tier.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families traveling with children who want a Pacific Mexico all-inclusive with a kids club, babysitting, diving, fishing, and tennis, plus large rooms for groups of five or more, in a well-connected Puerto Vallarta setting.","whenToVisit":"Cap Cana's dry season runs December through April, making winter the safest bet for Zilara; the shoulder months of May and November offer value with mostly stable weather. Puerto Vallarta's dry season also peaks November through April, with the summer rainy season bringing brief but heavy Pacific showers. Both destinations see peak pricing over the Christmas and spring break windows.","activities":"Zilara guests can explore Cap Cana's marina, championship golf courses, and nearby Scape Park with cenotes and zip lines. Ziva Puerto Vallarta guests can arrange diving and fishing excursions directly through the resort, then venture into Puerto Vallarta's Malecón boardwalk, Zona Romántica, and surrounding Sierra Madre jungle tours. Both resorts offer on-property spa, swim-up bar, and evening entertainment programs."},"excellence-riviera-cancun-vs-finest-punta-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Excellence Riviera Cancun is an adults-only luxury all-inclusive on Mexico's Riviera Maya near Puerto Morelos, with a lazy river, heated pool, nightclub, diving, and snorkelling, earning a standout overall rating of 9.6 versus Finest Punta Cana's 9.2. Excellence leads meaningfully in atmosphere (8.3 vs 7.8), pool (8.8 vs 8.2), sleep quality (9.2 vs 8.6), and service (9.5 vs 9.1), reflecting the quieter, more polished environment of an adult-only property. Finest Punta Cana is a large family all-inclusive in the Dominican Republic with a waterpark, kids club for under-4s, babysitting, pool slides, yoga, a dedicated adult pool, and rooms that sleep five or more. Both sit at the same price level and score closely on rooms (9.3 vs 9.2) and cleanliness (9.5 vs 9.3), but the beach ratings are modest at both properties (6.8 vs 6.5). Excellence is the choice for couples and adults wanting a refined, higher-rated Mexican retreat; Finest Punta Cana is the choice for families needing serious kids infrastructure in the Dominican Republic.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and adults who want a high-rated, adults-only Mexican all-inclusive with a lazy river, nightclub, heated pool, and exceptional service scores in a quieter Riviera Maya setting away from the crowds of Cancun's hotel zone.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of all ages, including toddlers, who want a well-equipped Dominican Republic all-inclusive with a waterpark, under-4s kids club, babysitting, pool slides, yoga, and large rooms that accommodate groups of five or more.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April when rainfall is lowest and conditions are driest. Puerto Morelos and Punta Cana share a similar hurricane-season risk from August through October, so travel insurance is advisable then. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates at both resorts with generally acceptable weather, though brief tropical showers are possible.","activities":"At Excellence Riviera Cancun, guests can dive, snorkel, fish, play tennis, use the lazy river, or catch evening entertainment and the nightclub on-site, with the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef and Puerto Morelos town nearby. At Finest Punta Cana, families can use the waterpark, rent watersports equipment, dive, snorkel, do yoga, play tennis, or explore Punta Cana's wider resort strip, with Bavaro Beach and local excursions to Indigenous Eyes Ecological Park close by."},"grand-velas-los-cabos-vs-velas-vallarta":{"keyDifferences":"Grand Velas Los Cabos and Velas Vallarta are both luxury family all-inclusives in Mexico under the same brand, but their ratings tell very different stories. Grand Velas Los Cabos dominates on almost every metric: food (9.9 vs 7.3), pool (9.8 vs 6.7), atmosphere (9.4 vs 6.8), room (9.9 vs 8.8), and service (9.9 vs 9.3). The overall gap of 9.8 vs 9.3 understates how pronounced these differences are category by category. Both resorts score modestly on beach (5.9 vs 5.3), which is typical for the Pacific coast. Velas Vallarta adds activities Grand Velas lacks — diving, tennis, fishing, and a lazy river — and comes in at better perceived value (8.9 vs 9.3) despite a lower price differential. Velas Vallarta also offers paid Wi-Fi where Grand Velas includes it free. If you want a near-flawless luxury experience with exceptional food, rooms, and service in Los Cabos and budget is secondary, go to Grand Velas Los Cabos. If you want a solid family all-inclusive in Puerto Vallarta with more active programming at a slightly more accessible price, go to Velas Vallarta.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who prioritize exceptional food, impeccable rooms, and five-star service above all else and are willing to pay a premium for one of the highest-rated all-inclusive experiences in Los Cabos, where atmosphere and cuisine consistently outperform nearly every competitor.","whoShouldChooseB":"Active families who want a broader activity menu — diving, tennis, fishing, and a lazy river — in the lush, tropical setting of Puerto Vallarta, and who are comfortable trading some polish in food and atmosphere for a slightly better value proposition and more varied on-site programming.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations enjoy excellent weather from November through May. Los Cabos is drier and sunnier year-round, making Grand Velas a strong choice even outside peak season. Puerto Vallarta's lush landscape comes courtesy of a wetter summer, so Velas Vallarta is best visited during the dry winter months. Both resorts reach peak pricing and occupancy between December and March.","activities":"Grand Velas Los Cabos guests can explore Cabo San Lucas's famous arch, whale watching from January to March, sport fishing, and ATV desert excursions. Velas Vallarta guests have on-site diving, tennis, and fishing alongside Puerto Vallarta's lively Malecón boardwalk, jungle zip-lining, whale watching, and sailing tours through Banderas Bay."},"casa-velas-vs-velas-vallarta":{"keyDifferences":"Casa Velas and Velas Vallarta are sister properties in Puerto Vallarta at the same price tier, but they serve fundamentally different guests. Casa Velas is adults-only and scores notably higher on overall experience (9.6 vs 9.3), service (9.6 vs 9.3), cleanliness (9.5 vs 9.1), atmosphere (8.0 vs 6.8), and sleep quality (9.1 vs 8.3), reflecting a quieter, more refined boutique environment. Velas Vallarta is a full family resort with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, babysitting, diving, tennis, fishing, and rooms for five or more guests, but its pool rating (6.7 vs 7.3), food rating (7.3 vs 8.3), and atmosphere score lag behind its adults-only sibling. Beach scores are modest at both properties (5.3 vs 3.0), though Velas Vallarta edges ahead there. Casa Velas adds a golf course and includes Wi-Fi, while Velas Vallarta charges for Wi-Fi. The tradeoff is clear: Casa Velas delivers a more polished, serene experience for couples, while Velas Vallarta trades some refinement for the infrastructure families need.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and adult travelers who want a quieter, more polished Puerto Vallarta all-inclusive with exceptional service, a golf course, and a boutique atmosphere. Those who prioritize sleep quality, cleanliness, and a refined environment over family amenities will find Casa Velas consistently delivers on those metrics.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of all ages who need a kids club, teen club, babysitting, lazy river, diving, and large rooms accommodating five or more guests. Parents willing to accept slightly lower food and atmosphere scores in exchange for comprehensive family programming and infrastructure will find Velas Vallarta well-suited to a busy family holiday.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Puerto Vallarta's dry season, running November through April, when rainfall is minimal and temperatures sit in the mid-to-upper 20s Celsius. December through March is peak season with higher prices and full programming at both properties. May through October brings humidity, occasional rain, and lower rates, with September and October carrying the highest storm risk.","activities":"Both resorts share access to Puerto Vallarta's marina district, downtown Malecon, and whale-watching excursions from December through March. Casa Velas guests can use an affiliated beach club and on-site golf course. Velas Vallarta adds diving, tennis, and fishing directly through the resort. Old Town Puerto Vallarta, the Romantic Zone, and nearby jungle zip-lining are accessible from either property within a short taxi or rideshare ride."},"hyatt-zilara-cap-cana-vs-hyatt-ziva-cancun":{"keyDifferences":"Hyatt Zilara Cap Cana is an adults-only luxury all-inclusive in the Dominican Republic's gated Cap Cana enclave, earning a 9.7 overall versus Hyatt Ziva Cancun's 9.3. Zilara scores notably higher on rooms (9.5 vs 9.3), service (9.6 vs 9.3), cleanliness (9.7 vs 9.5), atmosphere (8.5 vs 8.2), and value (9.3 vs 8.9), reflecting the premium of an adults-only environment where every detail is tuned to couples and solo travelers. Ziva Cancun is a full-family resort on the Cancun Hotel Zone peninsula with a kids club, teen club, waterpark, pool slides, babysitting, and rooms that sleep five or more — amenities Zilara does not offer. Ziva's beach rates slightly higher (8.0 vs 7.5), and its Cancun peninsula location delivers ocean views on two sides. Zilara counters with a lazy river, stronger service scores, and a quieter, more polished Cap Cana setting. Both are premium Hyatt properties at the same price tier, but one is engineered for adults and the other for families.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and adult travelers who want an immaculately run, adults-only Dominican Republic all-inclusive in the exclusive Cap Cana enclave, where top-tier service scores (9.6), high cleanliness (9.7), a lazy river, spa, and heated pool combine without children in the mix.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of any age who want a full-service Cancun all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, waterpark, pool slides, babysitting, and large rooms that sleep five or more, all on a peninsula with ocean views from multiple sides.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April. Cap Cana sits slightly outside the main Dominican hurricane corridor but late summer still brings risk; book Zilara for winter escapes or spring honeymoons. Cancun's Hotel Zone is busiest over U.S. spring break (March–April) and Christmas week; shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates with mostly good weather at both properties.","activities":"At Zilara Cap Cana, guests can use the marina and yacht facilities of the broader Cap Cana development, access nearby Scape Park caves and zip lines, or arrange deep-sea fishing charters. At Ziva Cancun, the Hotel Zone puts guests within reach of Isla Mujeres day trips, snorkeling at MUSA underwater museum, ancient Mayan ruins at Chichen Itza and Tulum, and ATV excursions through the Yucatan jungle."},"hyatt-vivid-grand-island-vs-hyatt-zilara-cap-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only Hyatt all-inclusives at the same price tier, but their ratings tell sharply different stories. Hyatt Zilara Cap Cana outscores Vivid Grand Island in nearly every measurable category: overall 9.7 vs 9.1, food 8.5 vs 7.2, beach 7.5 vs 3.5, pool 8.5 vs 7.6, atmosphere 8.5 vs 7.4, and service 9.6 vs 9.1. Vivid Grand Island's strongest suit is its room score (9.3) and cleanliness (9.4), and its Cancun location (8.2) puts guests close to the Hotel Zone's nightlife and airport. Zilara Cap Cana dominates on location (9.5) within the exclusive Cap Cana marina enclave and adds amenities Vivid lacks entirely: a lazy river, yoga classes, nightclub, heated pool, and room service. Vivid's beach rating of 3.5 is a significant liability versus Zilara's 7.5. At the same price point, Zilara Cap Cana delivers a measurably superior all-inclusive experience across food, beach, and service, while Vivid Grand Island trades on its Cancun proximity and strong room quality.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who prioritize Cancun's Hotel Zone convenience, want strong room quality and cleanliness, and plan to spend meaningful time outside the resort exploring Cancun's nightlife, cenotes, and nearby Isla Mujeres. Best for those who treat the resort primarily as a well-appointed home base.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults seeking a self-contained, high-performing all-inclusive where every category from food to beach to service scores exceptionally. Ideal for couples who want a polished Dominican retreat in the exclusive Cap Cana enclave with a lazy river, yoga, nightclub, and heated pool without needing to leave the property.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April when rainfall is minimal and humidity drops. Cancun's hurricane season runs June through November, with September the riskiest month. Cap Cana in the Dominican Republic follows a similar pattern but can see drier conditions on its eastern coast even in shoulder months. Both properties command premium rates over Christmas and Easter weeks.","activities":"Hyatt Vivid guests can access Cancun's Hotel Zone strip, cenote tours, Isla Mujeres day trips, and Chichen Itza excursions. Hyatt Zilara Cap Cana sits within the exclusive Cap Cana marina complex, giving guests access to deep-sea fishing, golf at Punta Espada, cave diving in nearby cenotes, and boat charters, while the resort itself covers yoga, lazy river, and nightclub entertainment on property."},"grand-velas-boutique-los-cabos-vs-velas-vallarta":{"keyDifferences":"Grand Velas Boutique Hotel Los Cabos is a small adults-only Mexican all-inclusive in Los Cabos with near-perfect ratings across the board: overall 9.9, food 9.7, room 9.9, service 9.9, and cleanliness 9.9. Velas Vallarta is a family-oriented Puerto Vallarta all-inclusive with solid service (9.3) and location (8.7) but noticeably weaker scores in food (7.3 vs 9.7), pool (6.7 vs 8.9), beach (5.3 vs 7.1), and atmosphere (6.8 vs 9.3). Both sit at the same premium price tier, but Grand Velas delivers a markedly superior culinary and experiential product in a boutique adults-only setting, while Velas Vallarta offers far more family infrastructure including a kids club, teen club, lazy river, babysitting, diving, and rooms for five or more guests. The 1.4-point overall gap is driven largely by Grand Velas's exceptional food and atmosphere scores. Grand Velas is the clear choice for adults prioritising quality and intimacy; Velas Vallarta is the practical choice for families needing space and programming.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults-only couples or pairs seeking a boutique Los Cabos experience where dining, service, and room quality are paramount. With food rated 9.7 and rooms and service both at 9.9, this is the pick for guests who want a refined, indulgent Mexican Pacific Coast escape without children.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of all ages who need dedicated kids and teen programming, babysitting, a lazy river, diving, tennis, and rooms that accommodate five or more guests, all in a well-located Puerto Vallarta property with strong service despite food and beach ratings that trail Grand Velas considerably.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's Pacific Coast dry season, roughly November through April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity drops. Los Cabos at Grand Velas tends to be sunnier and drier year-round due to its desert climate, making shoulder months like May and October viable. Puerto Vallarta at Velas Vallarta sees a pronounced rainy season June through October, so families should aim for December through March for the most reliable weather.","activities":"At Grand Velas Los Cabos guests can snorkel, fish, practise yoga, and use a heated pool and swim-up bar, with a spa, nightclub, and evening entertainment rounding out the program. Velas Vallarta adds diving, tennis, a lazy river, a kids club, and a teen club to a similar beach-and-pool framework. Offsite, both areas offer whale watching seasonally, sport fishing, ATV tours, and access to vibrant local dining and cultural scenes in Los Cabos and Puerto Vallarta respectively."},"hyatt-vivid-playa-del-carmen-vs-hyatt-zilara-cap-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only Hyatt all-inclusives at the same price level, but Hyatt Zilara Cap Cana outscores Hyatt Vivid Playa Del Carmen across nearly every category. Zilara's overall rating is 9.7 versus Vivid's 9.2, with the sharpest gaps in beach (7.5 vs 4.5), pool (8.5 vs 7.3), atmosphere (8.5 vs 7.4), food (8.5 vs 7.7), room (9.5 vs 9.1), and service (9.6 vs 9.2). Vivid's beach rating of 4.5 is a notable weakness, while Zilara's 7.5 reflects a proper Caribbean beach in Cap Cana's protected marina enclave. Zilara also adds a lazy river that Vivid lacks. Vivid's strengths are its Playa del Carmen location score (8.9) and walkable access to the 5th Avenue dining and nightlife strip, which partially compensates for weaker on-property scores. Zilara sits in a more secluded, purpose-built resort zone where the property itself carries the experience. If on-property quality and beach are your benchmarks, Zilara wins decisively. If proximity to a lively town matters, Vivid holds an edge.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a high-rated Hyatt all-inclusive base in Playa del Carmen where the location lets them walk to 5th Avenue restaurants, shops, and nightlife. Best for couples or solo travelers who want urban energy alongside resort amenities and rate location access as a priority.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who want the stronger overall all-inclusive experience and are willing to stay within a resort enclave to get it. The right choice for couples prioritizing a proper Caribbean beach, superior food scores, a lazy river, immaculate cleanliness, and consistently excellent service in a polished Cap Cana setting.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April when rainfall is low and humidity manageable. Playa del Carmen can feel busier and more crowded during spring break and holiday weeks given its urban setting. Cap Cana's more secluded location buffers it from that seasonal crowd pressure. Hurricane season runs June through November for both, with the Dominican Republic carrying slightly higher storm risk in September and October.","activities":"At Vivid Playa del Carmen, guests can walk to 5th Avenue for independent dining, cenote day trips, ferry access to Cozumel, and Mayan ruins at Tulum or Chichen Itza. On-property: tennis, yoga, spa, nightclub, and evening entertainment. At Zilara Cap Cana, guests have the lazy river, swim-up bar, yoga, spa, nightclub, and evening entertainment on-site, plus nearby deep-sea fishing, golf at Cap Cana's courses, and cave diving at Hoyo Azul."},"hyatt-zilara-cap-cana-vs-hyatt-ziva-rose-hall":{"keyDifferences":"Hyatt Zilara Cap Cana is an adults-only all-inclusive on the Dominican Republic's upscale Cap Cana coast, earning a 9.7 overall with standout scores for cleanliness (9.7), service (9.6), and location (9.5). Hyatt Ziva Rose Hall is a family all-inclusive on Jamaica's Rose Hall strip, scoring a solid but lower 8.9 overall, with notably weaker marks for beach (5.8 vs 7.5), pool (7.4 vs 8.5), and atmosphere (7.4 vs 8.5). Zilara Cap Cana offers a lazy river, heated pool, yoga, spa, and nightclub in a polished, serene adults-only setting where virtually every metric outperforms its Jamaican counterpart. Ziva Rose Hall compensates with a kids club, babysitting, tennis, and family-oriented programming that Zilara cannot offer by design. Food scores also favor Cap Cana meaningfully at 8.5 versus 7.7. If you want a premium Dominican adults-only retreat with exceptional service and a lazy river at near-perfect satisfaction scores, choose Zilara Cap Cana. If you want a family-friendly Jamaican all-inclusive with kids programming and babysitting near Montego Bay, choose Ziva Rose Hall.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and adult travelers who want a polished, high-scoring Dominican adults-only all-inclusive with a lazy river, heated pool, yoga, spa, and nightclub in the exclusive Cap Cana area, and who are willing to pay a premium for near-perfect service and cleanliness ratings.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of all ages who want a full-service Jamaican all-inclusive with a kids club, babysitting, tennis, and evening entertainment near Rose Hall, and who prioritize family programming over top-tier beach and pool ratings.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in the Caribbean's peak dry season from December through April, when rainfall is lowest and conditions are most reliable. Cap Cana's sheltered marina-adjacent coast can be favorable outside peak season too. Rose Hall, on Jamaica's north coast, sees more year-round rain variability. Both carry hurricane risk from June through November, with September and October the most active months to avoid.","activities":"At Cap Cana, guests can explore the marina, championship golf at Punta Espada, deep-sea fishing, and cave snorkeling nearby, while the resort itself offers yoga, spa treatments, and lazy river relaxation. At Rose Hall, guests can visit the historic Rose Hall Great House, try horseback riding on the beach, play tennis, snorkel offshore, and enjoy proximity to Montego Bay's shops and restaurants, with the resort offering evening entertainment and watersports."},"hyatt-zilara-cap-cana-vs-turquoize-at-hyatt-ziva-cancun":{"keyDifferences":"Hyatt Zilara Cap Cana and Turquoize at Hyatt Ziva Cancun are both adults-only, upper-luxury all-inclusives at the same price tier, but they diverge meaningfully across several ratings. Zilara Cap Cana leads in overall score (9.7 vs 8.4), atmosphere (8.5 vs 8.2), service (9.6 vs 9.3), and value (9.3 vs 8.9), and brings a significantly broader amenity set: heated pool, gym, yoga, swim-up bar, nightclub, evening entertainment, lazy river, and buffet. Turquoize counters with a noticeably better beach score (9.0 vs 7.5) and the highest room rating of the two (9.8 vs 9.5), suggesting superior accommodation quality and a stronger oceanfront position in Cancun's Hotel Zone. Food scores are close, with Turquoize edging ahead slightly (8.6 vs 8.5). Zilara Cap Cana is the fuller-featured resort with a livelier amenity program in a newer Dominican enclave, while Turquoize is a more pared-back, room- and beach-forward adults retreat where the setting and accommodation do most of the heavy lifting.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a high-scoring, amenity-rich Dominican all-inclusive with a swim-up bar, lazy river, nightclub, yoga, and evening entertainment in the upscale Cap Cana enclave. Strong across nearly every rating category, it suits couples and solo travelers who want a full resort experience at excellent perceived value.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who prioritize an exceptional room and a standout beach over a broad activity roster. Turquoize's 9.8 room score and 9.0 beach rating make it ideal for couples seeking a refined, relaxed Cancun retreat where the accommodation quality and oceanfront position are the primary draws.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak from December through April when rainfall is lowest and humidity manageable. Cancun's Hotel Zone can feel busier year-round given its proximity to Cancun's international airport and urban energy. Cap Cana is quieter and more secluded regardless of season. Both carry hurricane risk from August through October, though Cancun is statistically more exposed.","activities":"Cap Cana guests can access nearby Scape Park, deep-sea fishing, world-class golf at Cap Cana's courses, and cave snorkeling at Hoyo Azul. Turquoize guests are steps from Cancun's Hotel Zone, with easy access to Isla Mujeres day trips, cenote excursions, Chichen Itza tours, and the Mesoamerican Reef for snorkeling and diving. Both resorts offer on-site spa services."},"hyatt-zilara-cap-cana-vs-hyatt-zilara-rose-hall":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only Hyatt Zilara properties at the same price tier, but the ratings tell a clear story: Cap Cana outscores Rose Hall across nearly every category. The overall gap is significant — 9.7 vs. 8.9 — and the differences in pool (8.5 vs. 7.4), atmosphere (8.5 vs. 7.5), and food (8.5 vs. 7.8) are consistent. The beach rating divergence is the starkest: Cap Cana scores 7.5 against Rose Hall's 5.8, reflecting Cap Cana's superior Caribbean coastline versus Montego Bay's more modest beach offering. Cap Cana also adds a lazy river, heated pool, yoga classes, and room service that Rose Hall lacks, while Rose Hall counters with tennis courts. Location scores are close (9.5 vs. 8.7), but Cap Cana's setting in the exclusive, purpose-built Cap Cana marina enclave gives it a more polished, resort-within-a-resort feel. Value scores also favor Cap Cana (9.3 vs. 8.5), suggesting guests feel Cap Cana justifies its premium more convincingly despite identical pricing.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults and couples who want the highest-rated all-inclusive experience in the Dominican Republic, with a superior beach, lazy river, heated pool, yoga, and room service in the exclusive Cap Cana enclave. Ideal for those who prioritize atmosphere, food quality, and overall resort polish at a luxury price point.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who specifically want a Jamaica all-inclusive in the Montego Bay corridor and value the Hyatt Zilara brand, convenient airport proximity, and tennis facilities. Best suited to those whose primary draw is Jamaica itself rather than beach or pool quality, and who are comfortable with a more modest overall experience.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in the Caribbean's dry season sweet spot of December through April, when rainfall is lowest and trade winds keep temperatures comfortable. Cap Cana's hurricane exposure is comparable to Jamaica's, with peak risk from August through October for both. Rose Hall's Montego Bay location makes it particularly convenient for short stays given its proximity to Sangster International Airport.","activities":"Cap Cana guests can explore the broader Cap Cana marina complex, deep-sea fishing, and nearby Scape Park for adventure excursions, alongside on-site yoga, spa, and lazy river. Rose Hall guests have access to on-site tennis, the spa, and easy excursions to Dunn's River Falls, ATV tours, and Montego Bay's Hip Strip for dining and nightlife beyond the resort gates."},"hyatt-zilara-cap-cana-vs-hyatt-zilara-riviera-maya":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only Hyatt Zilara properties at the same price tier, but their ratings diverge sharply in several categories. Cap Cana in the Dominican Republic outscores Riviera Maya in Mexico on nearly every metric: overall (9.7 vs 8.6), food (8.5 vs 7.9), pool (8.5 vs 7.1), atmosphere (8.5 vs 7.5), room (9.5 vs 9.1), value (9.3 vs 8.4), and service (9.6 vs 9.0). The beach gap is the starkest differentiator: Cap Cana scores 7.5 versus a weak 5.5 at Riviera Maya, which sits on a more typical Mexican Caribbean stretch. Cap Cana also offers meaningfully more amenities, including a heated pool, lazy river, swim-up bar, yoga classes, nightclub, and room service, none of which appear at Riviera Maya. For guests paying the same premium rate, Cap Cana delivers a demonstrably stronger all-around experience. Riviera Maya's main advantages are proximity to the Yucatan Peninsula's cenotes, ruins, and broader destination appeal, plus slightly better sleep quality scores (8.9 vs 9.2).","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want the stronger-rated Hyatt Zilara experience, prioritizing a better beach, swim-up bar, lazy river, nightclub, and higher-scoring food and service in a polished Cap Cana setting. Ideal for couples seeking a luxurious, amenity-rich Dominican adults-only retreat with little reason to leave the resort.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who want to base themselves in Mexico's Riviera Maya to access cenotes, Tulum, Chichen Itza, and Playa del Carmen day trips, and are willing to accept lower ratings across most categories in exchange for the Yucatan Peninsula's exceptional off-resort destination appeal.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April for dry, sunny weather. Cap Cana and Riviera Maya share a similar hurricane season risk from June through November, with September being the most active month for both. Riviera Maya can see more seaweed on its beaches in summer months. Cap Cana's shoulder months of May and November offer strong value with fewer crowds at both properties.","activities":"Cap Cana guests have yoga, the spa, lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, and evening entertainment on property, with deep-sea fishing, golf, and the marina district nearby. Riviera Maya guests have the spa and evening entertainment on site, but the location shines off-resort with cenote swimming, snorkeling at Cozumel, the Tulum ruins, and the shops and restaurants of Playa del Carmen within easy reach."},"hyatt-zilara-cap-cana-vs-hyatt-ziva-los-cabos":{"keyDifferences":"Hyatt Zilara Cap Cana is an adults-only all-inclusive on the Dominican Republic's exclusive Cap Cana strip, earning a 9.7 overall against Hyatt Ziva Los Cabos's 8.7. Zilara dominates on atmosphere (8.5 vs 7.4), pool (8.5 vs 7.4), and location (9.5 vs 8.5), and its beach score of 7.5 still comfortably clears Los Cabos's 3.5, reflecting the Pacific's notoriously rough surf and non-swimmable shoreline. Ziva Los Cabos counters with a family-first amenity stack — kids club, teen club, waterpark, pool slide, tennis, and babysitting — that Zilara simply doesn't offer. Room quality is comparable (9.5 vs 8.8), but Zilara's service (9.6 vs 9.0) and cleanliness (9.7 vs 9.1) ratings are measurably sharper. If you want a serene, high-performing adults-only Dominican retreat with a swimmable beach and near-flawless guest satisfaction scores, choose Zilara Cap Cana. If you need a family-capable Mexican Pacific resort with kids infrastructure despite a beach too rough to swim, choose Ziva Los Cabos.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples and groups who want one of the Caribbean's highest-rated all-inclusive experiences — swimmable beach, lazy river, spa, and polished service — in the upscale Cap Cana enclave without children in the mix.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of all ages who want a full-service Los Cabos all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, waterpark, babysitting, and tennis, and are comfortable trading a swimmable beach for pool-focused days in a Baja desert setting.","whenToVisit":"Zilara Cap Cana sits in the Dominican Republic's hurricane belt; January through March delivers the most reliable dry weather. Ziva Los Cabos enjoys a desert climate with sunshine year-round, though September and October bring occasional tropical storms to Baja. Both resorts charge peak rates over US holidays and spring break, so shoulder months like May or November offer the same sun with softer pricing.","activities":"Zilara Cap Cana guests can explore Cap Cana's world-class golf courses, deep-sea fishing, and nearby Scape Park adventure attractions, alongside on-site yoga, spa, and evening entertainment. Ziva Los Cabos guests have access to whale watching (December–April), sport fishing, ATV desert tours, and the art galleries and restaurants of downtown San Jose del Cabo, complementing on-site tennis, waterpark, and nightclub programming."},"hyatt-zilara-cap-cana-vs-hyatt-ziva-barbados":{"keyDifferences":"Hyatt Zilara Cap Cana is an adults-only luxury all-inclusive in the Dominican Republic's upscale Cap Cana enclave, rated an exceptional 9.7 overall, with standout scores in cleanliness (9.7), service (9.6), location (9.5), and rooms (9.5). Hyatt Ziva Barbados is a family all-inclusive on the island of Barbados with solid room (9.2) and cleanliness (9.4) scores but meaningfully lower ratings across food (6.0 vs 8.5), pool (7.4 vs 8.5), atmosphere (7.5 vs 8.5), and value (7.6 vs 9.3). Zilara Cap Cana commands a premium price tier and delivers on it across almost every measurable dimension, while Ziva Barbados trails notably on food and atmosphere despite charging a comparable rate. Cap Cana's beach scores slightly lower (7.5 vs 7.7), but Zilara compensates with a lazy river, heated pool, swim-up bar, spa, nightclub, and evening entertainment. Ziva Barbados benefits from Barbados's natural charm and marginally better beach score but struggles to match Zilara's overall execution.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and adults who want a polished, high-performing Dominican Republic all-inclusive in the exclusive Cap Cana area, where exceptional service, immaculate facilities, a lazy river, spa, and nightclub combine at a price point that still earns near-perfect value scores.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who prioritize the authentic Caribbean appeal of Barbados and clean, comfortable rooms over a broad amenity set, and who are willing to accept middling food and atmosphere scores in exchange for the island's distinct culture and slightly better beach access.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations enjoy warm weather year-round. The Dominican Republic's peak season runs December through April, when Cap Cana is at its driest and most popular — book Zilara well in advance. Barbados sits south of the hurricane belt, making it a reliable year-round destination, but its dry season (December to June) offers the most predictable sunshine. Both resorts carry peak-season pricing from late December through March.","activities":"At Zilara Cap Cana, guests can enjoy on-site yoga, a heated pool, lazy river, swim-up bar, spa treatments, nightclub, and evening entertainment, with Cap Cana's marina, Punta Espada golf course, and Blue Mall shopping nearby. Ziva Barbados guests can explore the island's world-class surf at Soup Bowl, Harrison's Cave, rum distillery tours, and sailing catamaran excursions, with snorkelling and water sports accessible from the property's beach."},"hyatt-zilara-cap-cana-vs-hyatt-ziva-punta-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Hyatt Zilara Cap Cana is an adults-only all-inclusive in the upscale Cap Cana enclave, rated 9.7 overall with a lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, heated pool, spa, and evening entertainment. Hyatt Ziva Punta Cana is a family all-inclusive rated lower on atmosphere (7.6 vs 8.5) and pool (7.4 vs 8.5), but adds a kids club, teen club, tennis, and mini golf for families. Zilara edges Ziva on location (9.5 vs 9.1), value (9.3 vs 8.7), and atmosphere, reflecting Cap Cana's more exclusive, polished setting versus Punta Cana's broader resort corridor. Beach scores flip slightly in Ziva's favor (8.2 vs 7.5). Zilara's amenity list is deeper for couples—spa, nightclub, lazy river, swim-up bar—while Ziva trades those for family-specific programming. If you want a refined, amenity-rich adults-only experience in exclusive Cap Cana, choose Zilara. If you need kids club infrastructure and teen programming in a family-friendly Punta Cana property, choose Ziva.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and adult travelers who want a highly rated, adults-only Dominican Republic all-inclusive in the exclusive Cap Cana area, with a spa, lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, and an atmosphere score and overall rating that lead this comparison.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of all ages who need a structured all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, tennis, and mini golf in Punta Cana, and are willing to trade some atmosphere and pool quality for solid family programming at a slightly lower value rating.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Dominican Republic's dry season, roughly December through April, when rainfall is lowest and trade winds keep temperatures comfortable. Zilara's adults-only atmosphere makes it especially appealing over the holiday shoulder periods when families descend on Punta Cana. Budget-conscious travelers should consider May or early June before hurricane season peaks in August and September.","activities":"At Zilara Cap Cana, guests can explore the upscale Marina Cap Cana, deep-sea fish, or arrange excursions to Scape Park's cenotes and zip lines minutes away. Ziva Punta Cana guests are well-positioned for Bavaro's busy excursion market, including catamaran snorkeling trips, dune buggy tours, and the Punta Cana Ecological Reserve. Both properties offer yoga and gym facilities on-site."},"hyatt-vivid-punta-cana-vs-hyatt-zilara-cap-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only Dominican Republic all-inclusives at the same price tier under the Hyatt brand, but their ratings tell meaningfully different stories. Hyatt Zilara Cap Cana outscores Vivid Punta Cana in nearly every experiential category: food by a significant 1.1 points (8.5 vs 7.4), beach by 1.0 (7.5 vs 6.5), pool by 1.6 (8.5 vs 6.9), atmosphere by 1.3 (8.5 vs 7.2), value by 0.6 (9.3 vs 8.7), service by 0.2 (9.6 vs 9.4), and sleep quality by 0.3 (9.2 vs 8.9). Vivid Punta Cana counters with a marginally higher overall score (9.8 vs 9.7) and cleanliness edge (9.5 vs 9.7 goes to Zilara). Zilara sits in the upscale Cap Cana marina district with a lazy river, heated pool, and nightclub, while Vivid's ratings suggest a property still finding its footing despite strong room and service scores. For two resorts at the same price point, Zilara delivers consistently better across food, beach, pool, and atmosphere.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who prioritize immaculate rooms and flawless service above all else, and who have found a strong rate at Hyatt Vivid Punta Cana. Best for World of Hyatt loyalists maximizing points stays where the room experience matters more than dining or beach quality.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults and couples who want the complete package at the same price point: superior food, a better beach, a lazy river, heated pool, nightclub, and the polished Cap Cana setting. Strong across every measurable category, making it the more defensible choice at this price tier.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in the Dominican Republic's dry season corridor from December through April, when rainfall is lowest and trade winds keep temperatures comfortable. Cap Cana's sheltered marina location at Zilara provides slightly calmer water conditions than open Punta Cana beaches. July and August bring heat and higher humidity to both but remain popular. Hurricane season peaks September through October; both carry risk during that window.","activities":"Hyatt Zilara Cap Cana guests have the amenity-rich Cap Cana marina complex nearby, offering deep-sea fishing, golf at Punta Espada, and the Scape Park adventure attraction. On property: lazy river, heated pool, swim-up bar, yoga, spa, and nightclub. Vivid Punta Cana guests access the broader Bavaro-Punta Cana corridor with water parks, zip-lining, and ATV excursions. Both properties offer watersports and evening entertainment programs standard to Dominican all-inclusives at this tier."},"grand-velas-riviera-nayarit-vs-velas-vallarta":{"keyDifferences":"Grand Velas Riviera Nayarit and Velas Vallarta are sister properties from the same Mexican resort group, both family-focused all-inclusives at the same price tier on Mexico's Pacific coast, but their ratings tell meaningfully different stories. Grand Velas scores a 9.5 overall versus Velas Vallarta's 9.3, with sharper gaps in food (9.7 vs 7.3), pool (8.7 vs 6.7), atmosphere (8.7 vs 6.8), room (9.6 vs 8.8), and sleep quality (9.7 vs 8.3). Both carry weak beach scores, but Grand Velas edges it at 6.5 versus Velas Vallarta's 5.3. Grand Velas adds a nightclub, bicycles, and room service that Velas Vallarta lacks, while Velas Vallarta counters with a lazy river, fishing, and rooms accommodating five or more guests. Grand Velas is the clear premium performer within the same brand and price bracket, while Velas Vallarta suits larger family groups who need the extra room capacity and a lazy river, and who can accept a notable step down in dining and atmosphere quality.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who want the best the Velas brand offers — outstanding food, impeccably rated service and cleanliness, a nightclub, spa, and a polished all-inclusive experience in Nuevo Vallarta where the ratings across nearly every category outperform its sister property at the same price.","whoShouldChooseB":"Larger families of five or more who need the room capacity Velas Vallarta uniquely offers, and who value a lazy river and fishing access in a Puerto Vallarta location, while being comfortable trading down significantly on dining quality and atmosphere relative to Grand Velas.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit on Mexico's Pacific coast and share the same seasonal rhythms. The dry season runs November through April, with the clearest skies and calmest seas. December through March is peak demand, so book well in advance. May through October brings humidity and occasional tropical storms, but shoulder months like May and November offer thinner crowds and lower rates without the full brunt of rainy-season weather.","activities":"At both properties guests can dive, play tennis, swim in heated pools, and enjoy kids and teen clubs with evening entertainment programs. Grand Velas adds bicycles and a nightclub for after-dark options. Velas Vallarta adds fishing and a lazy river. The surrounding area of Nuevo Vallarta and Puerto Vallarta offers whale watching from December to March, zip-lining in the Sierra Madre foothills, boat trips to Los Arcos marine sanctuary, and the cobblestone streets and restaurants of downtown Puerto Vallarta."},"iberostar-selection-praia-do-forte-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Praia do Forte is a large Brazilian family all-inclusive on the Coconut Coast north of Salvador, with a kids club, babysitting, nightclub, yoga, snorkelling, and rooms sleeping five or more. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is an adults-only all-inclusive on Mexico's Riviera Maya with a golf course, swim-up bar, and noticeably stronger ratings across nearly every metric. JOIA leads on overall score by a wide 0.6 points (9.5 vs 8.9), with food up 0.7 (8.1 vs 7.4), pool up 0.8 (8.2 vs 7.4), rooms up 0.5 (9.3 vs 8.8), cleanliness up 0.5 (9.4 vs 8.9), service up 0.8 (9.4 vs 8.6), and value up 0.8 (9.0 vs 8.2). Praia do Forte holds its own on location (8.6 vs 8.8) and offers the only kids programming, nightclub, and yoga classes of the two. JOIA's beach rating is actually marginally lower (7.0 vs 7.3). The choice is essentially between a well-rounded Brazilian family resort with broader activity programming and an adults-only Mexican retreat that scores meaningfully higher on polish, comfort, and food.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who want a full-service Brazilian all-inclusive with a kids club, babysitting, nightclub, yoga, and snorkelling on Brazil's Coconut Coast. The larger rooms sleeping five or more and evening entertainment program make it especially practical for families travelling with multiple children.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travellers who want a high-performing, polished adults-only all-inclusive on the Riviera Maya with standout service (9.4), immaculate rooms (9.3), and a golf course on-site. The consistently elevated ratings across food, cleanliness, and value make it a strong choice for those prioritising quality and quiet.","whenToVisit":"Praia do Forte is best visited April through September, Brazil's drier season, when wind and surf conditions also attract kitesurfers to the area. JOIA Paraíso on the Riviera Maya is most reliably pleasant December through April, ahead of the June–November hurricane season. Both resorts carry a $$$$  price tag, so shoulder-season travel to either can yield better rates without major trade-offs in weather.","activities":"At Praia do Forte, guests can explore the historic Tamar sea turtle project nearby, snorkel the natural reef pools, dive, play tennis, or take yoga classes on-site. JOIA Paraíso guests can access diving along the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, play golf, use the tennis courts, or arrange excursions to Tulum ruins and cenotes. Both resorts offer evening entertainment and spa facilities."},"grand-velas-riviera-maya-vs-velas-vallarta":{"keyDifferences":"Grand Velas Riviera Maya and Velas Vallarta are both premium Mexican family all-inclusives from the same brand, but their ratings diverge sharply across nearly every category. Grand Velas Riviera Maya scores a 9.7 overall versus Velas Vallarta's 9.3, but the food gap is the most striking: Grand Velas earns a 9.9 versus Velas Vallarta's 7.3, a 2.6-point difference that is enormous for siblings under the same brand. Pool scores tell a similar story — 9.7 versus 6.7. Atmosphere (9.3 vs. 6.8) and room ratings (9.6 vs. 8.8) also favor Grand Velas meaningfully. Beach scores are poor at both properties — 6.3 and 5.3 respectively — so neither should be chosen primarily for beach quality. Velas Vallarta adds a lazy river and tennis courts that Grand Velas lacks, and its location rating of 8.7 reflects Puerto Vallarta's accessible, vibrant setting. Grand Velas includes a free Wi-Fi policy where Velas Vallarta charges for it, a notable distinction at the same price tier. Grand Velas is the clearer choice for families who prioritize dining and overall resort quality.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples willing to pay top dollar for a near-flawless resort experience anchored by exceptional dining — a 9.9 food score — and outstanding pool and service quality in the Riviera Maya. A strong pick if culinary experience and overall polish matter most and beach quality is secondary.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a well-run Puerto Vallarta all-inclusive with the bonus of a lazy river and tennis courts, and who value the energy and accessibility of the Puerto Vallarta destination itself. A reasonable choice if resort amenity variety and location convenience outweigh the gaps in food and atmosphere quality.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in Mexico's dry season window of December through April, when rainfall is minimal and conditions are most reliable. Riviera Maya's peak runs November through March with strong hurricane exposure June through October. Puerto Vallarta's rainy season runs June through October as well, though storms are typically shorter and less severe than the Caribbean. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates with manageable weather at both properties.","activities":"At Grand Velas Riviera Maya guests can dive, fish, and access a full spa and arcade, with Playa del Carmen's cenotes, Tulum ruins, and Cozumel day trips nearby. At Velas Vallarta guests can dive, fish, play tennis, and float the lazy river, with Puerto Vallarta's Malecón boardwalk, Marietas Islands snorkeling, whale watching seasonally, and Sierra Madre zip-line tours all within easy reach."},"iberostar-selection-hacienda-dominicus-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Hacienda Dominicus is a large family all-inclusive on Bayahibe's quieter Dominican coastline with a kids club, teen club, babysitting, nightclub, yoga, diving, and snorkelling. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is an adults-only all-inclusive on Mexico's Riviera Maya near Playa Paraiso, with a golf course, diving, spa, and swim-up bar in a more intimate, elevated setting. The ratings tell a clear story: JOIA leads on overall score (9.5 vs 9.0), food (8.1 vs 7.4), pool (8.2 vs 7.3), room quality (9.3 vs 8.6), cleanliness (9.4 vs 9.1), and service (9.4 vs 9.0). Hacienda Dominicus counters with a stronger beach score (8.3 vs 7.0) and a full family programming suite that JOIA simply does not offer. Both sit at the same price tier, making the choice less about budget and more about who is travelling. If you want a family-friendly Dominican all-inclusive with a strong beach and dedicated kids infrastructure, go to Hacienda Dominicus. If you want a polished, adults-only Mexican all-inclusive with superior rooms, food, and service, go to JOIA Paraíso.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a well-rated Dominican all-inclusive with a strong beach, kids club, teen club, babysitting, nightclub, and a broad range of water activities including diving and snorkelling in the relatively uncrowded Bayahibe area.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples and solo travellers who prioritise exceptional room quality, food, and service in a refined, adults-only Mexican setting with golf, spa, and diving, and who are willing to trade a weaker beach score for a significantly higher overall resort experience.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations share a broadly similar Caribbean climate. The Dominican Republic's Bayahibe coast is driest and calmest from December through April, with humidity and brief rain possible from June to October. Mexico's Riviera Maya peaks from December to April as well, with hurricane season running June through November. Either resort is best booked for a winter or early spring visit to maximise settled weather and beach conditions.","activities":"At Hacienda Dominicus, the reef-sheltered waters of Bayahibe make it one of the Dominican Republic's top spots for diving and snorkelling, and the resort adds yoga, tennis, and a nightclub for evenings. JOIA Paraíso guests can access golf, spa treatments, diving, and tennis, with the broader Riviera Maya offering Mayan ruins at Tulum and Cobá, cenote swimming, and the Sian Ka'an biosphere reserve within easy reach of the resort."},"iberostar-waves-bahia-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Waves Bahia is a large family all-inclusive on Brazil's Praia do Forte coast with a kids club, babysitting, archery, hiking, mini golf, bicycles, nightclub, and rooms for five or more guests. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is an adults-only all-inclusive on Mexico's Riviera Maya at Playa Paraíso, with a spa, diving, swim-up bar, and a level of polish reflected in notably higher ratings across nearly every category. JOIA outscores Waves Bahia on food by 1.2 points (8.1 vs 6.9), pool by 1.3 points (8.2 vs 6.9), rooms by 0.7 points (9.3 vs 8.6), cleanliness by 0.7 points (9.4 vs 8.7), service by 0.8 points (9.4 vs 8.6), and overall by 0.5 points (9.5 vs 9.0). Waves Bahia wins on breadth of family amenities and its distinctive Brazilian setting, while JOIA wins on refined execution, quieter atmosphere, and room quality. If you want a Brazilian family all-inclusive with kids programming and active pursuits at Praia do Forte, choose Waves Bahia. If you want a high-performing adults-only Mexican all-inclusive with superior food, rooms, and service on the Riviera Maya, choose JOIA Paraíso.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a sprawling Brazilian all-inclusive with a kids club, babysitting, archery, hiking, mini golf, and a nightclub in the distinctive ecological setting of Praia do Forte, and are willing to accept more modest food and pool ratings in exchange for that breadth of programming.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples and solo travelers who want a high-quality, tranquil Riviera Maya all-inclusive where food (8.1), rooms (9.3), service (9.4), and cleanliness (9.4) are genuine strengths, and where a spa, diving, and swim-up bar round out a polished, adults-only experience.","whenToVisit":"Praia do Forte enjoys warm weather year-round, but Brazil's dry season from September through March offers calmer seas and less rainfall, making it the prime window for Iberostar Waves Bahia. JOIA Paraíso benefits from the Riviera Maya's dry season running December through April, when humidity drops and skies are reliably clear. Both properties carry premium-season pricing over the Christmas and New Year period.","activities":"At Iberostar Waves Bahia, guests can explore the Tamar sea turtle sanctuary at Praia do Forte village, hike through Atlantic Forest trails, and take guided reef snorkelling tours along Brazil's coral coast. At JOIA Paraíso, the Riviera Maya delivers world-class cenote diving, Tulum ruins day trips, zip-lining at nearby eco-parks like Xcaret, and snorkelling along the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, the second largest in the world."},"iberostar-waves-quetzal-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Waves Quetzal and JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar are both four-dollar-sign Iberostar properties on Mexico's Riviera Maya, but they serve fundamentally different guests. Quetzal is a family resort in Playa del Carmen with a kids club, teen club, babysitting, a waterpark for little kids, and rooms that sleep five or more, making it purpose-built for multigenerational travel. JOIA Paraíso is adults-only near Playa Paraiso, and its ratings tell the story clearly: overall 9.5 versus Quetzal's 8.9, rooms 9.3 versus 8.2, cleanliness 9.4 versus 8.9, and service 9.4 versus 8.8. The most striking gap is food: JOIA scores 8.1 against Quetzal's 6.9, a difference that will be felt at every meal. JOIA also adds a golf course not found at Quetzal. Beach ratings are close, 7.5 for Quetzal and 7.0 for JOIA. Quetzal's edge is its family infrastructure and Playa del Carmen location; JOIA's edge is a consistently more refined, quieter experience across nearly every rated category.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a Playa del Carmen base with a full kids and teen club, babysitting, a waterpark, and rooms large enough for five or more. The strong value rating of 8.8 and location score of 8.8 make it a practical choice for families who want amenities without compromise.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults and couples who prioritize room quality, service, and dining above all else. With a 9.3 room rating, 9.4 service score, and food at 8.1, JOIA Paraíso delivers a noticeably more polished all-inclusive experience, and the addition of golf makes it particularly appealing to guests who want leisure options beyond the beach.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Riviera Maya's dry season, roughly December through April, when rainfall is lowest and humidity most manageable. January through March offers the most reliable weather but commands peak pricing. May and June bring good value before the summer crowds arrive. Hurricane season runs June through November, with September and October carrying the highest storm risk for both properties.","activities":"Both resorts offer diving, tennis, spa, swim-up bar, and evening entertainment. Quetzal's Playa del Carmen location puts guests within reach of the 5th Avenue shopping and dining strip, Xcaret and Xel-Há eco-parks, and easy ferry access to Cozumel for reef diving. JOIA's Playa Paraiso setting is quieter and more secluded, with the added draw of onsite golf. Cenote tours, zip-lining, and Tulum ruins are accessible from either resort."},"iberostar-selection-paraiso-lindo-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Both resorts sit in the same Playa Paraíso corridor on Mexico's Riviera Maya and share the same $$$$price tier, but they serve fundamentally different guests. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is adults-only and outperforms Iberostar Selection Paraíso Lindo across nearly every rated category: overall 9.5 vs 8.9, food 8.1 vs 7.0, pool 8.2 vs 7.4, rooms 9.3 vs 8.3, cleanliness 9.4 vs 9.0, and service 9.4 vs 8.9. Paraíso Lindo counters with a vastly broader family amenity set: kids club, teen club, babysitting, a waterpark for both age groups, a lazy river, and rooms accommodating five or more guests. Its value rating of 8.5 matches JOIA's 9.0 reasonably closely given the extra infrastructure it provides. JOIA trades the family programming for a quieter, more polished atmosphere where the higher food and room scores genuinely matter to couples. If you want a high-amenity Mexican family all-inclusive with waterparks, a lazy river, and youth programming at Playa Paraíso, go to Iberostar Selection Paraíso Lindo. If you want a refined, adults-only Riviera Maya resort with superior food, rooms, and service scores, go to JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of any age who need a waterpark, lazy river, kids club, teen club, and babysitting under one roof, and who are willing to accept lower food and room scores in exchange for comprehensive youth programming and large-group accommodations.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travelers who want the best food, room quality, and service ratings available in the Playa Paraíso area, in a quieter adults-only environment with tennis, a spa, and a swim-up bar without the backdrop of a waterpark.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Riviera Maya's dry season, roughly November through April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity is lower. December and January bring peak crowds and prices. May through October is hurricane season, with September the riskiest month, though shoulder months like May or November offer meaningful savings at both properties without significant weather trade-offs.","activities":"Both properties offer beach access, diving, a swim-up bar, spa, gym, golf, and evening entertainment within the shared Playa Paraíso zone. Paraíso Lindo adds its waterpark and lazy river on-site. Nearby, guests at either resort can access Tulum ruins, Cobá, cenote swimming, and snorkeling at the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, all reachable within an hour by car or organized excursion."},"iberostar-waves-tucan-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Waves Tucán is a large family all-inclusive in Playa del Carmen with a kids club, teen club, waterpark for little kids, babysitting, rooms for 5+ guests, and evening entertainment across a broad amenity set. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is an adults-only all-inclusive in Playa Paraíso with a golf course, spa, swim-up bar, and a noticeably more refined experience reflected in its ratings. JOIA outscores Tucán in nearly every category: overall 9.5 vs 9.0, food 8.1 vs 6.9, pool 8.2 vs 6.9, rooms 9.3 vs 8.2, cleanliness 9.4 vs 8.9, service 9.4 vs 8.9, and sleep quality 8.5 vs 8.2. Tucán holds its own on location and value, both rated 8.8, matching JOIA on location while offering a full family infrastructure at the same price tier. Tucán wins on beach at 7.5 vs JOIA's 7.0. For families, Tucán's programming depth is unmatched; for adults prioritizing food quality, room comfort, and quieter surroundings, JOIA is the clear upgrade within the same brand and price band.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who need kids club, teen club, babysitting, a waterpark for little ones, and rooms that sleep five or more. Those who want full family infrastructure in Playa del Carmen and don't mind trading some food and room quality for broad programming and strong value.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a quieter, more polished Riviera Maya experience with markedly better food, room quality, and service than a typical family resort. Golfers, spa enthusiasts, and anyone who values cleanliness and sleep quality and is willing to forego kids-focused amenities entirely.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Riviera Maya's dry season, December through April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity is lower. Peak weeks around Christmas, New Year, and spring break bring higher prices and heavier crowds at both properties. For JOIA, shoulder months like May or November offer quieter adult-oriented stays; for Tucán, those same months mean kids clubs are less crowded outside school holidays.","activities":"Both properties sit on the Riviera Maya coast and offer diving, tennis, spa treatments, evening entertainment, and swim-up bar access. Guests at either resort can arrange excursions to the Tulum ruins, Cobá, cenote swims, and snorkeling at the Mesoamerican Reef. Tucán adds a waterpark and teen programming on-site. JOIA guests have access to a golf course. Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue shopping and dining strip is accessible from Tucán, while JOIA's Playa Paraíso location is slightly more removed but still reachable."},"iberostar-selection-playa-mita-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Playa Mita is a large family all-inclusive on Mexico's Pacific coast in Punta de Mita, with a kids club, teen club, waterpark for little kids, babysitting, nightclub, and rooms for five or more guests. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is an adults-only all-inclusive on the Riviera Maya in Playa Paraiso, with a quieter, more refined atmosphere and ratings that consistently outperform Playa Mita across nearly every category. JOIA leads on overall score (9.5 vs 8.8), food (8.1 vs 7.1), pool (8.2 vs 7.3), atmosphere (8.0 vs 6.9), room (9.3 vs 8.8), and service (9.4 vs 9.0). Playa Mita's strength is its family infrastructure and Pacific coast location near Punta de Mita's surf breaks and Marieta Islands. If you want a premium Pacific-coast family resort with a waterpark, kids club, and nightclub despite weaker food and beach scores, go to Iberostar Playa Mita. If you want the higher-rated, adults-only Riviera Maya experience with superior food, rooms, and atmosphere, go to JOIA Paraíso.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a full-service Pacific-coast Mexican all-inclusive with a waterpark, kids club, teen club, babysitting, nightclub, and large rooms, and who value proximity to Punta de Mita's surf and natural attractions.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples and solo travelers who want a high-performing, adults-only Riviera Maya all-inclusive with top-rated rooms, food, and service, and who prioritize a peaceful, polished atmosphere over family-oriented programming.","whenToVisit":"Playa Mita's dry season runs November through April, avoiding the Pacific hurricane season and summer humidity. JOIA Paraíso on the Riviera Maya is best visited November through April as well, sidestepping Atlantic hurricane season and peak summer heat. Both resorts see higher prices over the Christmas and spring break periods, so shoulder months like November or early December offer good value at either property.","activities":"Playa Mita guests can surf nearby breaks, take boats to the Marieta Islands for snorkeling, and explore the charming town of Sayulita. JOIA Paraíso guests have access to Tulum's ruins, cenotes, and the Sian Ka'an biosphere reserve within driving distance. Both resorts offer on-site diving, tennis, spa, golf, and watersports, with the Riviera Maya giving JOIA guests a broader range of nearby cultural and natural excursions."},"iberostar-selection-coral-bavaro-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Coral Bávaro is a large Dominican Republic family all-inclusive in Bavaro with a kids club, waterpark, babysitting, casino, nightclub, snorkelling, and rooms sleeping five or more, at a strong value rating of 8.6. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive in Playa Paraiso with a swim-up bar, diving, golf, and a significantly higher overall score of 9.5 versus Coral Bávaro's 9.0. JOIA outperforms on food (8.1 vs 7.6), pool (8.2 vs 7.4), room quality (9.3 vs 8.8), cleanliness (9.4 vs 9.1), and service (9.4 vs 8.8), reflecting its adults-only focus and more refined execution. Coral Bávaro edges ahead on beach (8.0 vs 7.0), which is a meaningful gap for beach-priority guests. If you want a large Dominican family all-inclusive with kids programming, a casino, nightclub, and rooms for bigger groups at a competitive price, go to Coral Bávaro. If you want a polished, quieter adults-only Riviera Maya experience with superior service, rooms, and food, go to JOIA Paraíso.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a full-featured Dominican Republic all-inclusive with a kids club, waterpark, babysitting, casino, nightclub, and large-group rooms on one of Bavaro's better-rated beaches.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a quieter, more refined Riviera Maya all-inclusive with standout service (9.4), excellent room quality (9.3), a swim-up bar, golf access, and diving, without the energy of a family resort.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Caribbean and Mexican Riviera's dry season, roughly December through April, when rainfall is lowest and conditions are most reliable. Bavaro can see hurricane-season humidity and storms from August through October. Playa Paraiso follows a similar pattern, with the shoulder months of May and November offering lower prices and still-reasonable weather at both properties.","activities":"Coral Bávaro guests can snorkel, play tennis, use the casino, or visit the waterpark, with Bavaro's broader resort strip and excursion options nearby. JOIA Paraíso guests can dive, golf, use the swim-up bar, or take excursions to Tulum, Cobá, and Xcaret from its Playa Paraiso location. Both properties offer spas, evening entertainment, tennis, and gym facilities on-site."},"iberostar-selection-holguin-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Holguin is a large Cuban family all-inclusive on Holguin's beach strip with a waterpark for little kids, kids club, babysitting, archery, yoga, snorkelling, and a nightclub, priced accessibly and earning strong marks for rooms (9), cleanliness (9), and value (8.7), but dragged down by notably weak food (6.1) and pool ratings (6.7). JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is a premium adults-only all-inclusive in Mexico's Playa Paraiso with diving, golf, a spa, and swim-up bar, commanding a top-tier price and posting significantly better scores across food (8.1 vs 6.1), pool (8.2 vs 6.7), atmosphere (8 vs 6.4), service (9.4 vs 8.7), and overall (9.5 vs 9). The food gap of two full points is the starkest differentiator. Holguin delivers Cuba's unique character at strong value for families; JOIA delivers a refined, polished adults experience in the Riviera Maya where cuisine and service are the headline. If you want a family-friendly Cuban all-inclusive with kids programming and good value, choose Holguin. If you want a premium adults-only Riviera Maya resort where food and service quality justify the higher price, choose JOIA Paraíso.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want an affordable Cuban all-inclusive with a waterpark, kids club, babysitting, archery, and snorkelling, and who prioritise value and room quality over dining sophistication or polished poolside experiences.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travellers willing to pay a premium for a high-performing adults-only Riviera Maya resort where food (8.1), service (9.4), and cleanliness (9.4) all genuinely deliver, complemented by diving, golf, and a spa in a tranquil, upscale atmosphere.","whenToVisit":"Cuba's Holguin coast runs best November through April when rainfall and hurricane risk drop sharply; summer visits carry humidity and storm exposure. JOIA Paraíso in Mexico's Riviera Maya also peaks November through April, avoiding the June-to-October hurricane season. Both destinations share the same ideal winter travel window, making direct comparisons on timing straightforward for travellers choosing between the two.","activities":"At Iberostar Holguin, guests can snorkel offshore reefs, take archery and yoga classes, use the tennis courts, and explore Holguin province's colonial towns and nearby Guadalavaca beach area. At JOIA Paraíso, guests can dive the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, play golf, use the spa and tennis courts, and access Tulum's ruins and cenotes, plus the broader Riviera Maya's water parks and ecological reserves within easy reach."},"iberostar-selection-rose-hall-suites-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Rose Hall Suites is a large family all-inclusive in Montego Bay, Jamaica, with a waterpark, lazy river, kids club, babysitting, casino, and nightclub, while JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is an adults-only luxury property on Mexico's Riviera Maya in Playa Paraiso with golf, diving, and a markedly more refined atmosphere. The rating gap tells the real story: JOIA outscores Rose Hall Suites on overall satisfaction (9.5 vs 8.8), food (8.1 vs 7.1), pool (8.2 vs 7.3), rooms (9.3 vs 8.8), value (9.0 vs 8.5), service (9.4 vs 8.9), and cleanliness (9.4 vs 9.1). Rose Hall Suites holds its own on location (8.6 vs 8.8) and beach (6 vs 7), but neither property earns strong beach marks. If you want a full-service Jamaican family all-inclusive with a kids club, waterpark, casino, and nightclub in Montego Bay, go to Rose Hall Suites. If you want a high-performing adults-only Mexican resort with superior food, rooms, and service on the Riviera Maya, go to JOIA Paraíso.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children who want a feature-rich Jamaican all-inclusive with a waterpark, lazy river, kids club, babysitting, casino, and nightclub in Montego Bay. The large suites accommodating five or more guests make it especially practical for bigger family groups.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travelers seeking a high-quality, peaceful Riviera Maya retreat where the ratings consistently back up the premium price. Golfers, divers, and anyone who prioritizes exceptional food, spotless rooms, and attentive service over family-oriented programming will find JOIA hard to beat.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in peak Caribbean and Mexican sunshine between December and April, when rainfall is lowest and demand is highest. Jamaica's summer months bring rain and lower rates at Rose Hall Suites. JOIA Paraíso enjoys gentler summer humidity than much of the Yucatán coast, though September and October mark peak hurricane season for both destinations and are best avoided.","activities":"Rose Hall Suites guests can dive, fish, play tennis, hit the casino, or visit the historic Rose Hall Great House nearby, with Montego Bay's Hip Strip and airport both close. JOIA Paraíso offers diving on the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, golf, tennis, and evening entertainment on-site, with the Tulum ruins, Xcaret eco-parks, and cenote swimming all reachable within an hour or two by car."},"iberostar-waves-cozumel-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Waves Cozumel is a family all-inclusive on Cozumel island with a kids club, babysitting, snorkelling, and rooms for larger families, while JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is an adults-only luxury all-inclusive on the Riviera Maya mainland at Playa Paraiso with a golf course and significantly stronger performance across nearly every rating category. JOIA Paraíso outscores Cozumel on overall rating by 0.7 points (9.5 vs 8.8), food by 1.5 points (8.1 vs 6.6), pool by 1.9 points (8.2 vs 6.3), rooms by 1.5 points (9.3 vs 7.8), cleanliness by 0.7 points (9.4 vs 8.7), and service by 0.6 points (9.4 vs 8.8). Cozumel's beach rating is notably low at 5.3 versus JOIA's 7.0, though Cozumel compensates with world-class diving access off the island. If you want a family-friendly Mexican all-inclusive on Cozumel with diving and snorkelling in one of the Caribbean's premier reef destinations, go to Iberostar Waves Cozumel. If you want a high-performing adults-only Riviera Maya all-inclusive with superior food, rooms, and a golf course, go to JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children who want to base themselves on Cozumel for access to world-class diving and snorkelling on the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, and who need a kids club, babysitting, and rooms that sleep five or more people.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples and groups who want a premium adults-only Riviera Maya all-inclusive with outstanding rooms, food, service, and cleanliness scores, plus a golf course and a beach that significantly outperforms the typical Cozumel shoreline.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season between December and April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity is lower. Cozumel's diving is excellent year-round, with peak visibility from April through August. Both properties sit in the Caribbean hurricane belt, making June through November higher-risk months, with September and October the most active. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates with generally acceptable weather at both locations.","activities":"At Iberostar Waves Cozumel, the island itself is the activity draw: world-renowned reef diving and snorkelling, plus water taxis to the mainland for Tulum ruins and cenotes. At JOIA Paraíso, guests have on-site golf, diving, and spa access, with the Riviera Maya's cenote network, Tulum, Cobá ruins, and Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue easily reachable by car or tour from the mainland location."},"iberostar-selection-paraiso-maya-suites-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Both resorts sit in the same Playa Paraíso corridor on Mexico's Riviera Maya and share the same $$$$ price tier, but they serve fundamentally different guests. Iberostar Selection Paraíso Maya Suites is a large family all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, waterparks, lazy river, babysitting, and rooms that sleep five or more. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is adults-only and posts markedly stronger ratings across almost every category: overall 9.5 vs. 8.8, food 8.1 vs. 7.5, pool 8.2 vs. 7.4, rooms 9.3 vs. 8.6, service 9.4 vs. 8.8, and cleanliness 9.4 vs. 9.0. The beach scores are close (7.0 vs. 6.5), suggesting neither property has a standout shoreline. JOIA also adds tennis to the activity roster. In short, Paraíso Maya Suites trades some polish for the infrastructure needed to run a full family operation, while JOIA channels the same price point into a quieter, noticeably higher-quality experience for adults.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a self-contained Mexican all-inclusive with waterparks, a lazy river, a kids club, teen programming, babysitting, and large-format rooms that fit five or more. The strong cleanliness and service scores mean parents can relax while the resort keeps the kids entertained.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups of friends who want a refined, high-performing Riviera Maya all-inclusive without the noise and infrastructure of a family property. JOIA's 9.3 room rating and 9.4 service score make it one of the stronger executions in the area at this price level, with tennis, diving, and a spa rounding out the offering.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the same Riviera Maya climate. December through April delivers dry, sunny weather with low humidity and is peak season. May and June are warm and less crowded. Hurricane season runs July through November, with September and October carrying the highest risk, though rates are lowest then. Easter and Christmas weeks see heavy family bookings at Paraíso Maya Suites in particular.","activities":"Both resorts share access to the same stretch of the Riviera Maya coastline, with diving into the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, the world's second largest, available at each property. Guests can reach Tulum's ruins, Cobá, and cenote networks within an hour. Nearby Playa del Carmen offers shopping and nightlife. Golf is accessible at both resorts, and JOIA adds tennis on site. Iberostar's waterpark facilities give families additional on-property entertainment without leaving the grounds."},"iberostar-waves-paraiso-del-mar-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Both resorts sit in Playa Paraíso on Mexico's Riviera Maya and share the same Iberostar price tier, but they serve fundamentally different guests. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is adults-only and outperforms Iberostar Waves Paraíso del Mar across nearly every rated category: overall satisfaction 9.5 versus 8.8, food 8.1 versus 6.8, rooms 9.3 versus 8.2, pool 8.2 versus 6.5, service 9.4 versus 8.6, and cleanliness 9.4 versus 8.7. The food gap of 1.3 points and the pool gap of 1.7 points are particularly significant. Iberostar Waves counters with family-specific infrastructure absent at JOIA: a kids club, teen club, babysitting, archery, mini golf, bicycles, nightclub, and rooms accommodating five or more guests. Waves also scores slightly better on value at 8.5 versus 9.0 at JOIA, though JOIA's higher overall ratings suggest guests there feel the premium is well justified. If you want a family-oriented Mexican all-inclusive with broad programming for all ages, choose Waves. If you want a quieter, higher-performing adults-only experience at the same destination, choose JOIA.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a full-service Mexican all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, babysitting, mini golf, archery, and rooms large enough for five or more guests, accepting slightly lower food and pool scores in exchange for comprehensive family programming.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups of friends who want the highest-rated experience in Playa Paraíso, with standout room quality, food, cleanliness, and service scores in a quieter adults-only setting, and no need for family-focused amenities.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Riviera Maya's dry season from December through April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity is lower. The shoulder months of May and November offer reduced crowds and slightly lower rates before and after peak season. July and August draw families during school holidays, making Iberostar Waves particularly busy. Hurricane season runs June through November, with September the highest-risk month.","activities":"Both resorts offer diving, snorkelling, golf, spa facilities, and swim-up bars. Iberostar Waves adds archery, mini golf, bicycles, and a nightclub. The broader Playa Paraíso area provides access to cenote tours, Tulum ruins, the Sian Ka'an Biosphere Reserve, kite surfing, and Cobá archaeological sites. Playa del Carmen's dining and nightlife scene is a short drive north, and Cozumel is reachable by ferry for world-class reef diving."},"iberostar-waves-paraiso-beach-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Both resorts sit in Playa Paraíso on Mexico's Riviera Maya and share the same Iberostar campus and price tier, but they serve fundamentally different guests. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is adults-only and outperforms Iberostar Waves Paraíso Beach across every measurable category: overall rating 9.5 vs 8.9, food 8.1 vs 6.8, pool 8.2 vs 6.5, room 9.3 vs 8.2, cleanliness 9.4 vs 8.7, and service 9.4 vs 8.6. That food gap of 1.3 points and the room gap of 1.1 points are the most telling differences. Iberostar Waves compensates with a broader amenity list aimed at families: kids club, babysitting, lazy river, archery, bicycles, nightclub, and rooms accommodating five or more guests. JOIA strips back the programming in favor of a quieter, higher-quality experience. If you are traveling with children or want lively entertainment infrastructure, Waves is the practical choice. If you are traveling as a couple or a group of adults and food, room quality, and atmosphere matter most, JOIA's numbers make it the clear winner on the same stretch of beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of any age who need a kids club, babysitting, a lazy river, and large-format rooms on the Riviera Maya. Also suits groups who want evening entertainment, a nightclub, archery, and cycling as part of a broad activity program at a competitive value rating of 8.5.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a quieter, premium experience on the same Playa Paraíso beach without children present. The 9.3 room rating, 8.1 food score, and 9.4 service rating make it the right choice for anyone prioritizing quality over activity volume.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the same Riviera Maya climate. December through April brings dry, sunny weather with low humidity and the most reliable beach conditions, making it peak season. May through November is the wet and hurricane season, with July and August seeing family crowds at Waves in particular. Shoulder months of late November and early May offer a balance of good weather and lower rates at both properties.","activities":"Guests at both resorts can dive, play tennis and golf, and use the spa and swim-up bar on a shared stretch of Playa Paraíso beach. Iberostar Waves adds archery, bicycles, a lazy river, and a nightclub for more active or entertainment-focused stays. Off-site, the Riviera Maya delivers cenote swimming, Tulum ruins, Cobá climbing, snorkelling at Akumal, and day trips to Chichén Itzá within a short drive of both properties."},"iberostar-waves-dominicana-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Waves Dominicana is a large family all-inclusive in Bavaro, Dominican Republic, with a kids club, teen club, waterpark for little kids, casino, nightclub, and babysitting across a property built to handle multigenerational groups including rooms for five or more guests. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is an adults-only all-inclusive in Playa Paraiso, Mexico, with diving, a swim-up bar, spa, and evening entertainment in a dramatically more refined setting. The rating gaps tell the story clearly: JOIA outscores Waves Dominicana across nearly every category, with particularly sharp leads in overall satisfaction (9.5 vs 8.6), food (8.1 vs 6.8), rooms (9.3 vs 8.2), cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.7), service (9.4 vs 8.6), and pool (8.2 vs 6.4). Waves Dominicana trades on breadth of family amenities and solid value, while JOIA trades on quality, calm, and a noticeably higher standard of execution across the board. Same parent brand, meaningfully different experience.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a feature-packed Dominican all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, waterpark, casino, nightclub, and rooms large enough for five or more guests. A strong value rating makes it a sensible choice for families prioritizing coverage of amenities over premium quality.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or solo travelers who want a high-quality, tranquil Mexican all-inclusive where the ratings back up the premium price: exceptional service, spotless rooms, strong food, and a swim-up bar and diving program without the noise and logistics of a family resort.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in the Caribbean basin where the dry season runs December through April, making that window the safest bet for sun and low humidity. Bavaro and the Riviera Maya share similar hurricane exposure from June through November, though shoulder months like May and November often offer reduced rates with acceptable weather. JOIA's Riviera Maya location tends to get slightly more reliable dry-season conditions than Bavaro.","activities":"At Iberostar Waves Dominicana, guests can use the waterpark, casino, nightclub, tennis courts, and golf course, with Bavaro's reef-lined beach and nearby Punta Cana excursions close at hand. At JOIA Paraíso, guests can dive the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, play golf, use the spa and swim-up bar, and access the Riviera Maya's cenotes, ruins at Tulum, and Playa del Carmen from a well-positioned Playa Paraiso base."},"iberostar-selection-riviera-cancun-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Riviera Cancun is a large family all-inclusive in Puerto Morelos with a kids club, waterpark, babysitting, archery, yoga, and rooms for five or more guests, built around a full family activity program. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is an adults-only all-inclusive in Playa Paraíso with access to a golf course, swim-up bar, spa, and diving, designed for a quieter, more refined experience. The rating gaps are significant: JOIA leads on overall score (9.5 vs 8.7), food (8.1 vs 7.1), beach (7.0 vs 5.5), pool (8.2 vs 6.9), room (9.3 vs 8.8), and service (9.4 vs 9.0). Riviera Cancun's strongest relative advantage is its family infrastructure — kids club, babysitting, waterpark, and large-group rooms that JOIA simply does not offer. If you want a family-focused Mexican Caribbean all-inclusive with kids programming and a full activity roster, go to Iberostar Riviera Cancun. If you want a higher-rated adults-only escape with stronger food, beach, and room scores plus golf access, go to JOIA Paraíso.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who need a kids club, babysitting, waterpark, and rooms large enough for five or more guests. Those willing to accept lower food and beach scores in exchange for comprehensive family programming at a well-run Riviera Maya resort.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a noticeably higher-rated experience across food, beach, pool, and rooms, with golf on-site and an atmosphere free of children. Guests prioritizing quality and comfort over family amenities at the same price tier.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit on Mexico's Riviera Maya, where the dry season runs from December through April — the clearest skies, calmest seas, and peak prices. May through October brings humidity and hurricane-season risk, with September being the most vulnerable month. Shoulder months of November and late April offer a reasonable balance of good weather and lower rates at both properties.","activities":"Both resorts offer diving, spa treatments, tennis, and evening entertainment on the Riviera Maya. Nearby, guests can explore the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef by snorkelling or diving, visit the ruins at Tulum or Cobá, swim in the region's famous cenotes, or take day trips to Akumal to snorkel with sea turtles. JOIA guests also have access to an on-site golf course, while Riviera Cancun guests can add archery, yoga classes, and fishing excursions."},"iberostar-selection-cancun-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Cancun and JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar are both four-dollar-sign Mexican all-inclusives on the Yucatán coast, but they serve fundamentally different guests. Iberostar Cancun is a large family resort on Cancun's Hotel Zone with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, waterpark for little ones, babysitting, and rooms that sleep five or more — a full-service family machine. JOIA Paraíso is an adults-only boutique property in quieter Playa Paraíso, south of Cancun, built around elevated service and room quality rather than family programming. The ratings tell the story clearly: JOIA outscores Iberostar Cancun on overall rating (9.5 vs 8.8), food (8.1 vs 7.5), room quality (9.3 vs 8.4), cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.9), and service (9.4 vs 8.9). Iberostar Cancun holds its own on beach (8.3 vs 7.0) and pool (7.3 vs 8.2 in reverse), suggesting a stronger beach setup but a less polished overall experience. If refined rooms and top-tier service matter most and children are not in the picture, JOIA wins on nearly every metric.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a large, well-equipped Cancun all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, waterpark, babysitting, and rooms that fit five or more guests — all on one of Mexico's most recognized resort beaches.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups seeking a quieter, more polished all-inclusive experience away from Cancun's busiest strip, where standout room quality (9.3), exceptional service (9.4), and strong food scores (8.1) matter more than family amenities or a buzzy beach scene.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the same regional seasonality. December through April brings dry, sunny weather and peak pricing across the Yucatán coast. May and June offer a shoulder window with lower rates before the July–October hurricane season raises risk. November is often an underrated sweet spot — weather stabilizes, crowds thin, and pricing at both properties tends to soften.","activities":"Both resorts offer diving, tennis, golf access, spa, swim-up bars, and evening entertainment. Iberostar Cancun adds a lazy river and waterpark for younger guests. The broader Cancun and Riviera Maya corridor offers Chichen Itza, Tulum ruins, Xcaret and Xel-Há eco-parks, cenote swimming, and snorkelling along the Mesoamerican Reef. JOIA's Playa Paraíso location places guests closer to Tulum and the quieter southern stretch of the Riviera Maya."},"iberostar-origin-daiquiri-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Daiquiri is a family-oriented Cuban all-inclusive on Cayo Guillermo, a remote island accessed by causeway, with a strong beach score of 8.5 but notably weak food and pool ratings of 5.6 each and a modest atmosphere score of 6. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is a premium adults-only all-inclusive on Mexico's Riviera Maya, rated 9.5 overall, with food at 8.1, pool at 8.2, rooms at 9.3, cleanliness at 9.4, and service at 9.4, gaps of 2.5 or more rating points over Daiquiri in nearly every quality metric. Daiquiri's strengths are its beach, a broad family amenity set including kids club, babysitting, horseback riding, and snorkelling, and a value score of 8.1 in a destination where resort options are limited. JOIA trades the family programming for a refined, quiet adults-only experience with golf access, superior rooms, and consistently top-tier service in a more accessible Riviera Maya location. The gap in food alone — 5.6 versus 8.1 — is a telling indicator of the overall quality difference between the two properties.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and travellers drawn specifically to Cuba who want a strong beach on Cayo Guillermo's protected waters with horseback riding, diving, snorkelling, and kids programming, and who accept that food and pool quality will be noticeably below what comparable Mexican resorts deliver.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples and solo travellers who want a premium Riviera Maya all-inclusive with exceptional rooms, service rated 9.4, golf access, and top-tier cleanliness, and who are willing to pay a higher price for a quality level that Daiquiri's ratings simply do not match.","whenToVisit":"Cayo Guillermo is best November through April when Cuba's dry season delivers calm seas and minimal rainfall, though hurricane risk runs June through October. JOIA Paraíso on the Riviera Maya is also best December through April; summer brings heat, humidity, and hurricane season from June onward. Both destinations share a similar peak and shoulder season rhythm, making late winter the safest window for either.","activities":"At Daiquiri guests can dive, snorkel, ride horses on the beach, rent watersports equipment, and use the tennis courts, with evening entertainment and a nightclub on-site. JOIA offers diving, tennis, a swim-up bar, evening entertainment, and access to a golf course, making it better suited to guests who want a quieter activity menu with higher-end execution. Neither property is near significant off-site attractions, though the Riviera Maya offers Tulum and cenote excursions within easy reach of JOIA."},"iberostar-waves-punta-cana-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Waves Punta Cana is a large Dominican Republic family all-inclusive on the Punta Cana strip with a kids club, teen club, waterpark, casino, nightclub, and babysitting across rooms that sleep five or more. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on the Riviera Maya in Playa Paraíso with a swim-up bar, diving, golf, and dramatically stronger ratings across nearly every category. The overall gap is stark: JOIA scores 9.5 overall versus Waves Punta Cana's 8.7, but the real separation is in food (8.1 vs 6.8), pool (8.2 vs 6.4), atmosphere (8.0 vs 6.7), rooms (9.3 vs 8.2), value (9.0 vs 8.5), cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.7), and service (9.4 vs 8.6). Waves Punta Cana wins on family infrastructure and breadth of entertainment. JOIA wins on almost every quality metric and suits guests who want a quieter, more polished experience without children present.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who need a large Dominican all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, waterpark, babysitting, casino, and rooms that accommodate five or more people, and who prioritize activity variety over ratings.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a high-quality, adults-only Mexican Riviera Maya resort where food, rooms, service, and cleanliness all score well above average, and a calmer poolside and beach atmosphere is the priority.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak from December through April when Caribbean and Riviera Maya weather is at its driest and most reliable. Punta Cana's hurricane season runs June through November, with September the riskiest month. Playa Paraíso shares similar risk but tends to see slightly less direct hurricane exposure. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower prices at both with generally acceptable conditions.","activities":"Iberostar Waves Punta Cana guests can dive, play golf and tennis, use the casino, and access evening entertainment and a nightclub on a busy resort strip near Punta Cana's shopping and excursion hubs. JOIA Paraíso guests can dive, golf, play tennis, and use a swim-up bar, with easy access to Riviera Maya cenotes, Tulum ruins, and Cobá nearby for day trips."},"iberostar-origin-tainos-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Tainos is a family all-inclusive on Cuba's Varadero peninsula with a kids club, babysitting, windsurfing, fishing, yoga, tennis, and a nightclub, built around one of the Caribbean's best beaches (9.0) at a budget-friendly price point. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is a premium adults-only all-inclusive on Mexico's Riviera Maya with a spa, dive center, swim-up bar, and golf course, posting dramatically stronger scores across food (8.1 vs 5.8), rooms (9.3 vs 7.5), pool (8.2 vs 5.6), cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.1), and service (9.4 vs 8.2). Tainos trades on its exceptional Varadero beach and Cuba's inherent novelty while keeping costs low; JOIA Paraíso trades on near-flawless execution at every touchpoint at a luxury price. The overall rating gap—9.5 versus 8.5—reflects that difference in polish. If you want a family-friendly Cuban beach holiday with classic all-inclusive programming at a competitive price, choose Tainos. If you want a refined, adults-only Riviera Maya experience with superior food, rooms, and service, choose JOIA Paraíso.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and Cuba-curious travelers who prioritize an outstanding beach, a full activity roster including windsurfing, fishing, and a kids club, and are comfortable trading some polish in food and pool quality for the novelty and value of a Varadero all-inclusive.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travelers who want a premium, meticulously run Riviera Maya all-inclusive with exceptional rooms, strong food, spa access, diving, and golf, and are willing to pay top-tier prices for consistently high scores across every category.","whenToVisit":"Varadero is best from November through April when Cuba's dry season delivers reliable sunshine; hurricane season runs June through November with higher humidity and rain risk. Playa Paraiso shares the Riviera Maya's peak season of December through April. Both destinations are busiest and priciest over Christmas and spring break, so shoulder months like November or early December offer better value without significant weather compromise.","activities":"At Tainos, guests can windsurf, fish, play tennis, join yoga classes, and explore Varadero's 20-kilometer beach strip, with Havana day trips and Cuban cultural excursions a short drive or flight away. At JOIA Paraíso, guests can dive the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, play golf, use the spa, snorkel, and access nearby Tulum ruins, cenotes, and the boutique town of Playa del Carmen for off-property exploration."},"iberostar-selection-bavaro-suites-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Bávaro Suites is a large family all-inclusive in the Dominican Republic's Bavaro area with a kids club, babysitting, waterpark for little kids, nightclub, yoga, tennis, diving, and rooms for five or more guests on one of the Caribbean's most active resort strips. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is an adults-only all-inclusive on Mexico's Riviera Maya near Playa Paraiso with a golf course, swim-up bar, diving, spa, and tennis in a more intimate, refined setting. The ratings tell the story clearly: JOIA leads on overall score (9.5 vs 8.6), room quality (9.3 vs 8.5), cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.9), service (9.4 vs 8.8), and food (8.1 vs 7.5), while Iberostar Bavaro edges ahead on beach (8.0 vs 7.0). If you want a large Dominican family all-inclusive with kids programming, a nightclub, and a waterpark at a competitive price, go to Iberostar Bavaro Suites. If you want a high-performing adults-only Mexican all-inclusive with superior rooms, service, and food in a quieter Riviera Maya setting, go to JOIA Paraíso.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a full-service Dominican Republic all-inclusive with a kids club, babysitting, waterpark, nightclub, and large-group rooms on a well-established Bavaro beach strip.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travelers who want a premium, quiet adults-only experience on the Riviera Maya with standout rooms, top-tier service, a golf course, and consistently high ratings across every category.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in peak Caribbean and Riviera Maya season from December through April, when dry weather and lower humidity make beach conditions ideal. Bavaro's hurricane exposure peaks August through October, while Playa Paraiso on Mexico's east coast shares similar risk. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates with generally acceptable weather at both properties.","activities":"At Iberostar Bavaro Suites, guests can dive, play tennis, take yoga classes, use the waterpark, and explore Punta Cana's busy excursion market including cenotes and whale-watching seasonally. At JOIA Paraíso, guests can dive, golf, play tennis, and access the Riviera Maya's rich excursion network including Tulum ruins, Chichen Itza, and some of the world's best cenote swimming within easy driving distance."},"iberostar-origin-playa-alameda-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Playa Alameda is an adults-only Cuban all-inclusive in Varadero with a strong beach rating of 8.8 but conspicuously low food and pool scores of 5.6, and an atmosphere rating of just 6.1, reflecting the realities of the Cuban all-inclusive market. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is a premium adults-only all-inclusive on Mexico's Riviera Maya, rated 9.5 overall with food at 8.1, rooms at 9.3, service at 9.4, and cleanliness at 9.4, making it one of the stronger performers across the board. The gap is significant: JOIA outscores Playa Alameda on every single metric, most starkly in food (8.1 vs 5.6), atmosphere (8.0 vs 6.1), pool (8.2 vs 5.6), and sleep quality (8.5 vs 7.4). Playa Alameda's value proposition rests almost entirely on its excellent beach and Cuba's novelty as a destination. JOIA adds a swim-up bar, diving, and golf, and justifies its premium price tier with across-the-board excellence. Choose Playa Alameda if Cuba itself is the draw; choose JOIA if you want a genuinely high-performing luxury adults-only resort.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults specifically drawn to Cuba as a destination who prioritize a strong beach experience and can accept limited food quality and atmosphere in exchange for the novelty and relative value of a Varadero all-inclusive. Best suited to travelers for whom the Cuban experience outweighs resort polish.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults seeking a premium, high-performing all-inclusive on the Riviera Maya where rooms, service, food, and cleanliness all rate exceptionally. Ideal for couples or travelers who want refined comfort, a swim-up bar, diving access, and golf without compromise on quality.","whenToVisit":"Varadero is best visited November through April when Cuba's dry season delivers reliable sunshine and lower humidity; the summer hurricane season carries real risk. The Riviera Maya at Playa Paraiso is also strongest November through May, avoiding the June to October hurricane window. Both destinations share broadly similar Caribbean seasonal patterns, making winter the safe choice for either resort.","activities":"At Playa Alameda, guests have watersports rentals, tennis, yoga, a gym, spa, and evening entertainment on one of Cuba's finest beaches, with Varadero's town and peninsula accessible nearby. At JOIA Paraíso, the offering expands to include diving, a swim-up bar, golf, spa, tennis, and gym, with the broader Riviera Maya providing cenotes, Tulum ruins, and Playa del Carmen within easy reach."},"iberostar-waves-rose-hall-beach-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Waves Rose Hall Beach is a family-oriented Jamaican all-inclusive in Montego Bay with a kids club, babysitting, nightclub, and a full activity roster including diving, tennis, and evening entertainment. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on the Riviera Maya with access to a golf course, elevated rooms, and significantly stronger performance across nearly every rated category. The rating gaps are stark: JOIA outscores Rose Hall Beach on overall satisfaction by a full point (9.5 vs 8.5), food by 1.6 points (8.1 vs 6.5), pool by 1.8 points (8.2 vs 6.4), rooms by 1.3 points (9.3 vs 8.0), and cleanliness and service both by nearly a full point. Rose Hall Beach holds its own on location for Montego Bay access (8.3) and offers the family infrastructure JOIA deliberately excludes. If you want a family Jamaican all-inclusive with a kids club, nightclub, and babysitting in Montego Bay, choose Rose Hall Beach. If you want a high-performing adults-only Mexican resort with superior food, rooms, and service, choose JOIA Paraíso.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a Jamaican all-inclusive with a kids club, babysitting, nightclub, and evening entertainment near Montego Bay. Those prioritizing family infrastructure over polished food and pool ratings will find Rose Hall Beach a solid, well-located choice.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or friends seeking a premium, peaceful Mexican all-inclusive with outstanding rooms, service, and food ratings, plus access to golf and diving on the Riviera Maya. Guests who prioritize quality over family amenities and want one of the stronger-rated all-inclusives at this price level.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts share a similar Caribbean-basin climate. Jamaica's Montego Bay is best November through mid-December and January through April, avoiding the September hurricane peak. Mexico's Riviera Maya runs slightly drier, with December through April offering the most reliable weather. Both destinations see elevated pricing and occupancy over US and European holiday periods, so early booking is advisable for either.","activities":"Both resorts offer diving, tennis, swim-up bars, gym facilities, evening entertainment, and beach access. Rose Hall Beach adds a nightclub, kids club, and babysitting, making it more activity-dense for families. JOIA Paraíso adds a golf course and sits on the Riviera Maya, giving guests access to nearby Tulum ruins, cenote diving, and Playa del Carmen. Rose Hall Beach guests can explore Montego Bay's hip strip, Dunn's River Falls, and local excursions."},"iberostar-origin-playa-pilar-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Playa Pilar is a family all-inclusive on Cuba's Cayo Guillermo, built around one of the Caribbean's most spectacular beaches, rated 9.8 for sand and water but dragged down by a food score of just 6.1, a pool score of 5.9, and an atmosphere rating of 6.5. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is a premium adults-only all-inclusive on Mexico's Riviera Maya, rated 9.5 overall with food at 8.1, rooms at 9.3, cleanliness at 9.4, and service at 9.4, though its beach scores a more modest 7.0. The gap in overall ratings is 1.0 points in JOIA's favour, and the service and cleanliness scores are consistently stronger across the board at the Mexican property. Playa Pilar's defining advantage is its extraordinary beach, one of the highest-rated in the Caribbean; JOIA wins on nearly every other metric. If you want an elite Cuban beach experience and can tolerate inconsistent food and limited amenities, choose Playa Pilar. If you want a polished, high-scoring adults-only resort in Mexico with strong dining, immaculate rooms, and top-tier service, choose JOIA Paraíso.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and beach purists who prioritise extraordinary natural surroundings above all else and are willing to accept uneven food quality and a quieter atmosphere in exchange for one of the Caribbean's highest-rated beaches in an off-the-beaten-path Cuban setting.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples and solo travellers who want a premium, consistently high-performing all-inclusive on the Riviera Maya with exceptional rooms, immaculate service, strong dining, a swim-up bar, spa, and golf, and are less focused on beach quality than overall comfort and refinement.","whenToVisit":"Cayo Guillermo is best visited November through April when Cuba's dry season delivers calm seas and reliable sunshine; hurricane season runs June through November. JOIA Paraíso on the Riviera Maya also peaks December through April, with the driest and least humid conditions. Both destinations share a similar risk window for tropical storms mid-year, so either property rewards an early winter or spring booking.","activities":"At Playa Pilar, the beach itself is the main event, with watersports on the stunning flats of Cayo Guillermo supplemented by snorkelling on nearby reefs. JOIA Paraíso offers a fuller amenity lineup: diving, a golf course, spa, tennis, gym, swim-up bar, and evening entertainment, all within reach of the Riviera Maya's cenotes, Tulum ruins, and Xcaret eco-parks, giving guests far more structured activity options on and off the property."},"iberostar-origin-laguna-azul-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Laguna Azul is a family-oriented all-inclusive with a standout beach score of 9 and a solid location rating of 8, but it struggles across the board on food (5.6), pool (5.8), and atmosphere (6.1), suggesting a property that leans on its natural coastal setting rather than its facilities or programming. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is a premium adults-only all-inclusive in Playa Paraíso, Mexico, with ratings that are consistently strong: overall 9.5, food 8.1, rooms 9.3, cleanliness 9.4, service 9.4, and value 9.0. The gap in food alone is 2.5 points, and the atmosphere differential of nearly 2 points underscores how differently these properties deliver the all-inclusive experience. Laguna Azul's beach outscores JOIA's by 2 points, which may matter to beach-focused families, but JOIA wins on virtually every other measurable dimension. If you want a beach-first family resort at a more accessible price, go to Laguna Azul. If you want a polished, adults-only Mexican all-inclusive with exceptional rooms, service, and food, go to JOIA Paraíso.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who prioritize beach quality above all else and can accept weaker food, pool, and atmosphere scores in exchange for a more affordable, beach-centric family all-inclusive experience. Best suited to guests who spend most of their day in the water rather than relying on resort amenities.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travelers who want a high-end, adults-only Mexican all-inclusive where food, service, cleanliness, and room quality are all genuinely strong. Ideal for those willing to pay a premium for a property that earns its ratings across nearly every category rather than just one or two.","whenToVisit":"JOIA Paraíso sits on Mexico's Riviera Maya, where the dry season runs November through April, making winter and early spring the most reliable window. Laguna Azul's location data is incomplete, but if it follows a similar Caribbean or coastal pattern, the same shoulder months of November through March tend to offer the best weather and value before peak holiday pricing kicks in.","activities":"JOIA Paraíso offers diving, a spa, tennis, golf, swim-up bar, gym, and evening entertainment within a well-equipped adults-only setting, with Playa Paraíso's broader Riviera Maya corridor adding cenote tours, archaeological sites like Tulum, and snorkeling at Mesoamerican reef access points nearby. Laguna Azul's activity profile is less defined in the data, but its high beach score points to water-based recreation as the primary draw for families."},"iberostar-waves-costa-dorada-vs-joia-paraiso-iberostar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Waves Costa Dorada is a family-oriented all-inclusive on Puerto Plata's Atlantic coast in the Dominican Republic, rated overall 8.5, with strong value (8.6) and service (8.7) scores but notably lower food (6.3), beach (6.3), and pool (6.0) ratings. JOIA Paraíso by Iberostar is a premium adults-only all-inclusive on Mexico's Riviera Maya, rated overall 9.5, with exceptional room (9.3), cleanliness (9.4), and service (9.4) scores and a meaningfully better food rating of 8.1. The gap in overall rating is a full point, and virtually every subcategory favors JOIA — food alone differs by 1.8 points. Costa Dorada commands a lower price tier and welcomes families, while JOIA sits a price tier higher and excludes children entirely. Costa Dorada's amenity list is sparse, while JOIA adds a spa, gym, diving, swim-up bar, golf course, and tennis. If you want an affordable Dominican family beach holiday, choose Costa Dorada. If you want a polished, amenity-rich adults-only Mexican escape with top-tier rooms and service, choose JOIA Paraíso.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families seeking a solid, well-priced Dominican Republic all-inclusive in Puerto Plata where service and cleanliness consistently deliver above their cost. Guests who prioritize value and strong service scores over premium amenities, and who don't mind more modest food and pool offerings.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and solo adult travelers who want a premium, adults-only Riviera Maya experience with standout rooms, spa access, diving, golf, and food quality that genuinely justifies the higher price tier. Those for whom atmosphere, comfort, and refined service are non-negotiable.","whenToVisit":"Puerto Plata's north coast sees more rain and wind than the Dominican Republic's south, making December through April the safest window for Costa Dorada. Playa Paraíso on Mexico's Riviera Maya is best visited November through April, avoiding the June–October hurricane season and peak summer humidity. Both resorts share a broadly similar dry-season sweet spot, with Christmas and Easter commanding peak pricing at both.","activities":"Costa Dorada guests are close to Puerto Plata's cable car, the Ocean World marine park, and the historic Fortaleza San Felipe. JOIA Paraíso sits near Tulum's ruins, cenote diving, and the Sian Ka'an Biosphere Reserve, with on-site diving, tennis, golf, and a spa adding considerable on-property depth. Both resorts offer beach access, but JOIA's broader amenity list means far less reason to leave the property."},"impression-moxche-by-secrets-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Impression Moxché by Secrets and Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun are both adults-only luxury all-inclusives on Mexico's Riviera Maya, but they diverge sharply on beach versus pool experience and atmosphere. Moxché scores a near-perfect 10 on pool but only 5.5 on beach, while Maroma flips that dynamic with an 8.2 beach and 8.4 pool — Maroma sits on one of the Caribbean's most celebrated stretches of white sand, and that location score of 9.6 versus Moxché's 9.4 reflects it. Moxché counters with superior room quality (9.8 vs 9.5), service (9.7 vs 9.5), atmosphere (9.3 vs 8.7), and a notably higher food rating (9.4 vs 8.4), suggesting a more intimate, boutique-feeling property where the culinary and in-resort experience is the draw. Maroma's overall score edges ahead at 9.6 versus 9.4, driven largely by its beach. Moxché skips the swim-up bar, diving, snorkelling, and tennis that Maroma offers, trading watersports breadth for a more design-forward, pool-centric luxury experience.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who prioritize exceptional food, immaculate rooms, and a world-class pool experience over beach access. Couples or solo travelers who want a boutique, atmosphere-driven all-inclusive near Playa del Carmen where the on-resort experience — dining, service, design — matters more than watersports or a postcard beach.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults for whom a stunning natural beach is non-negotiable. Guests who want a broader activity menu including diving, snorkelling, tennis, and a swim-up bar alongside strong room quality, all on one of the Riviera Maya's finest stretches of white sand near Playa Maroma.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the same Riviera Maya climate. December through April delivers dry, sunny weather with low humidity — peak season and peak pricing. May through October brings warmer water and lower rates but increased humidity and hurricane risk, particularly August through October. Shoulder months of May and November offer a balance of good conditions and softer pricing at both properties.","activities":"Both resorts offer spa treatments, evening entertainment, nightclub access, gym facilities, and buffet dining. Maroma adds scuba diving, snorkelling, tennis, and a swim-up bar for guests who want watersports and active beach days. Off-resort, both are well positioned for cenote tours, Tulum ruins, Xcaret and Xel-Há eco-parks, and day trips to Coba or Chichen Itza, all accessible via the Riviera Maya highway corridor."},"secrets-maroma-beach-vs-zoetry-agua-punta-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on one of the Riviera Maya's most celebrated stretches of sand, with a nightclub, tennis, snorkelling, diving, and evening entertainment, earning standout scores for location (9.6), cleanliness (9.7), and room quality (9.5). Zoëtry Agua Punta Cana is a family-friendly Dominican all-inclusive in the quieter Uvero Alto area, with a lazy river, adult pool, fishing, and diving, rated notably lower on beach (6.5 vs 8.2) and pool (7.8 vs 8.4). The overall rating gap—9.6 vs 9.2—reflects Secrets Maroma's edge in atmosphere (8.7 vs 8.4), location, and value (9.1 vs 8.7). Zoëtry closes some ground on service (9.4 vs 9.5) and sleep quality (8.9 vs 9.0) but cannot match the Mexican resort's beach or setting. If you want an adults-only luxury escape on a world-class Mexican beach with nightlife and watersports, choose Secrets Maroma. If you want a quieter, family-inclusive Dominican retreat with a lazy river and fishing in a more secluded location, choose Zoëtry Agua.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and adult travelers who want an adults-only luxury all-inclusive on one of Mexico's finest beaches, with strong scores across rooms, location, and cleanliness, plus nightlife, snorkelling, tennis, and a lively but refined Riviera Maya atmosphere.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families or couples seeking a quieter, boutique-style Dominican all-inclusive in the secluded Uvero Alto area, with a lazy river, fishing, adult pool, and excellent service, and who prioritize tranquility over a standout beach or lively entertainment scene.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Caribbean's dry season, roughly December through April, when rain is minimal and humidity manageable. Secrets Maroma's Mexican Caribbean coast can see Atlantic swells in summer affecting beach conditions. Zoëtry Uvero Alto faces the Atlantic directly and is more susceptible to choppier seas and occasional seaweed, making the November-to-April window particularly important to target there.","activities":"At Secrets Maroma, guests can dive, snorkel, play tennis, and explore the nearby Mesoamerican Reef, with Playa del Carmen and Tulum within easy reach. At Zoëtry Agua, fishing, diving, and the on-site lazy river are the main draws, with Punta Cana's wider resort strip and excursions to indigenous Taino sites or catamaran day trips available from Uvero Alto with a short transfer."},"secrets-maroma-beach-vs-zoetry-villa-rolandi-isla-mujeres":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun and Zoëtry Villa Rolandi Isla Mujeres are both adults-only, luxury Mexican all-inclusives at the same price tier, but they differ sharply in scale, setting, and ratings profile. Secrets Maroma scores significantly higher on beach (8.2 vs 6.0) and pool (8.4 vs 7.3), reflecting its position on one of the Riviera Maya's premier stretches of white sand with a full swim-up bar and nightclub. Zoëtry edges ahead on food (8.8 vs 8.4) and delivers a more intimate, boutique experience on Isla Mujeres, a small car-free island reached by yacht transfer from Cancun. Secrets Maroma's overall rating is higher (9.6 vs 9.3), with stronger scores for location, rooms, and value. Zoëtry has no nightclub or evening entertainment, signaling a quieter, more contemplative atmosphere (8.1 vs 8.7). Secrets Maroma suits guests who want a landmark beach, lively amenities, and high energy; Zoëtry suits those who want refined seclusion, superior dining, and an island-retreat pace with yoga and fishing replacing the party infrastructure.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples or groups who want a premier Riviera Maya beach experience with outstanding rooms, a swim-up bar, nightclub, evening entertainment, and a full activity roster on one of Mexico's most celebrated stretches of Caribbean coastline at strong value for the luxury tier.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples seeking a quiet, intimate boutique escape on a car-free island, where superior food ratings, yoga, fishing, and a private yacht transfer from Cancun matter more than a headline beach or lively nightlife scene.","whenToVisit":"Both properties sit in the same climate zone. December through April offers dry, sunny weather with low humidity — peak season and peak pricing. May and June are warm with manageable crowds. July through October brings hurricane-season risk, though Isla Mujeres' orientation can differ from the mainland coast in storm exposure. Shoulder months of May and November offer good weather with lower rates at both resorts.","activities":"At Secrets Maroma, guests can dive, snorkel, and use the swim-up bar along the Playa Maroma coastline, with tennis and evening entertainment on-site. Zoëtry Villa Rolandi adds yoga and fishing to diving and snorkelling, with the island of Isla Mujeres itself offering golf-cart exploration, the Punta Sur sculpture park, and excellent reef snorkelling at Manchones reef just offshore."},"impression-isla-mujeres-by-secrets-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Impression Isla Mujeres by Secrets and Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun are both adults-only Mexican all-inclusives at the same price tier, but they differ sharply in setting, atmosphere, and what they deliver on the ratings sheet. Impression sits on Isla Mujeres, a small car-free island requiring a ferry crossing from Cancun, and its isolation shows in its scores: atmosphere 9.3, room 9.7, service 9.7, and cleanliness 9.8 are all exceptional, while its beach rating of 7.8 trails Maroma's 8.2. Maroma sits on one of the Riviera Maya's most celebrated stretches of Caribbean sand, which anchors its beach and pool scores but its food rating of 8.4 falls noticeably behind Impression's 9.4. Impression edges out on food, service, rooms, atmosphere, and cleanliness; Maroma leads on beach, pool, overall score (9.6 vs 9.3), and value (9.1 vs 8.8), and adds tennis and a nightclub. Impression suits guests who prioritize intimate, boutique luxury; Maroma suits those who want a world-class beach with broader amenities and slightly better headline value.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples seeking an intimate, island-escape adults-only experience who prioritize outstanding food, impeccable service, and beautifully appointed rooms over a wide beach or nightlife, and who don't mind a ferry crossing to reach a quieter, more exclusive setting.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults-only couples who want one of the Riviera Maya's finest beaches as their centerpiece, combined with tennis, a nightclub, and a large resort atmosphere, and who value a strong overall rating and better perceived value without sacrificing room quality.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts peak from December through April when dry season brings calm seas, low humidity, and minimal rain. Isla Mujeres can see stronger wind chop affecting its beach and ferry crossings in winter months. Maroma's beach remains more sheltered year-round. Both offer significant savings in the May–November shoulder and hurricane seasons, with September and October carrying the highest storm risk.","activities":"At Impression, guests snorkel, dive, and explore the reefs surrounding Isla Mujeres, join yoga classes, and take short trips into Isla Mujeres town for its colorful streets and seafood. At Maroma, guests dive, snorkel, play tennis, and access the broader Riviera Maya — Tulum ruins, Xcaret eco-parks, cenote swimming, and playa del Carmen shopping are all within a comfortable drive."},"secrets-la-romana-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only Secrets properties at the same price tier, but their ratings tell meaningfully different stories. Secrets Maroma outscores La Romana in nearly every category: overall (9.6 vs 9.1), food (8.4 vs 7.8), pool (8.4 vs 7.6), atmosphere (8.7 vs 7.7), room (9.5 vs 8.6), cleanliness (9.7 vs 9.1), service (9.5 vs 9.1), and sleep quality (9.0 vs 8.5). La Romana edges Maroma on beach (8.3 vs 8.2) and matches it on value context, but Maroma's 9.1 value rating versus La Romana's 8.8 suggests guests feel they get more for their money in Mexico. La Romana compensates with a broader activity set — casino, waterpark, lazy river, fishing, and diving — while Maroma leans into a more refined, pared-back luxury experience with a swim-up bar and consistently elite room and service scores. La Romana suits activity-seekers; Maroma suits those prioritising atmosphere and accommodation quality.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a Dominican Republic all-inclusive with a broader amenity spread — casino, waterpark, lazy river, fishing, and diving — and are happy to accept slightly lower scores on rooms and atmosphere in exchange for more to do on-property.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who prioritise an immaculate, high-atmosphere luxury experience above all else. Maroma's exceptional room (9.5), cleanliness (9.7), and service (9.5) ratings make it the stronger choice for couples or honeymooners who want a refined, polished stay on Mexico's Riviera Maya.","whenToVisit":"La Romana's Bayahibe setting in the Dominican Republic is best visited November through April when hurricane risk drops and trade winds keep temperatures comfortable. Secrets Maroma on Mexico's Riviera Maya also peaks December through April, avoiding both hurricane season and the summer heat. Both properties share a similar optimal travel window, so timing alone is unlikely to drive the decision between them.","activities":"At La Romana, guests can dive and snorkel the reefs around Bayahibe, visit the island of Saona on day trips, fish offshore, and use the on-site casino and waterpark. At Maroma, snorkelling and diving access the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef nearby, while the broader Riviera Maya offers cenote swimming, Tulum ruins, and Playa del Carmen day trips — giving Maroma a richer off-property excursion landscape."},"secrets-maroma-beach-vs-secrets-moxche-playa-del-carmen":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only, premium-priced Secrets properties in Mexico with near-identical service (9.5) and cleanliness (9.7) scores, but they diverge sharply on beach and pool. Secrets Maroma Beach sits on one of the Riviera Maya's most celebrated stretches of sand, earning an overall rating of 9.6 and a beach score of 8.2, while Moxche's beach scores a notably weak 5.7, suggesting limited or compromised beach access in Playa del Carmen. Moxche compensates with a standout pool score of 9.5 versus Maroma's 8.4, and edges ahead on food (9.2 vs 8.4) and room quality (9.6 vs 9.5). Maroma's location rating of 9.6 versus Moxche's 9.2 reflects its secluded, pristine setting, while Moxche benefits from Playa del Carmen's walkable town access. Maroma also adds diving and snorkelling to its activity list. If the beach is your priority, Maroma wins decisively. If exceptional pools, food, and proximity to Playa del Carmen's restaurants and nightlife matter more, Moxche is the stronger pick.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults and couples who want an exceptional natural beach experience as the centrepiece of their stay. Maroma's near-perfect overall rating of 9.6 and renowned white-sand setting make it ideal for those willing to pay a premium for seclusion, strong service, and access to diving and snorkelling.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults and couples who prioritise outstanding pools (9.5), excellent food without reservation hassles, and the option to walk into Playa del Carmen's shops, restaurants, and nightlife. A good fit for guests who are pool-first travellers and want a vibrant town at their doorstep.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Riviera Maya's dry season, December through April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity manageable. Peak weeks around Christmas, New Year, and spring break bring higher rates and fuller properties at both. May through November brings occasional rain and hurricane-season risk, but significantly lower prices and quieter conditions at both resorts.","activities":"At Maroma, guests can dive and snorkel the nearby Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, play tennis, use the spa, and enjoy evening entertainment on the beach. Moxche offers yoga classes, heated pools, spa treatments, tennis, and nightclub access, with the added advantage of Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue steps away for shopping, dining, and cenote day trips accessible from both locations."},"secrets-maroma-beach-vs-secrets-tides-punta-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only Secrets properties at the same price tier with matching room scores (9.5 each) and similar pools (both 8.4), but Maroma Beach pulls ahead decisively on overall rating (9.6 vs 9.1), beach (8.2 vs 6.5), atmosphere (8.7 vs 8.1), location (9.6 vs 8.8), food (8.4 vs 7.9), and value (9.1 vs 8.7). The beach gap is the starkest difference: Playa Maroma is consistently ranked among Mexico's finest stretches of Caribbean sand, while Secrets Tides sits on a more modest Punta Cana beach that lags nearly two full points behind. Maroma also edges out on service (9.5 vs 9.2) and cleanliness (9.7 vs 9.5). Secrets Tides counters with reservation-free dining across all restaurants, a marginally better sleep quality score (8.6 vs 9.0 favoring Maroma), and a slightly lower effective price point given its better value-adjusted ratings. If beach quality is your primary driver, Maroma is the clear winner. If flexible dining and a solid Dominican Republic adults-only base matter more than the sand itself, Tides is a reasonable alternative.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and adult travelers who want one of the Caribbean's best beaches as their backdrop, and are willing to pay a premium for it. Maroma's exceptional location, service, and cleanliness scores make it ideal for honeymoons, anniversaries, or anyone for whom beach quality is non-negotiable.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult travelers who prioritize room quality and flexible dining over beach prestige, and want a solid Secrets experience in the Dominican Republic at a slightly more forgiving price-to-value ratio. A good fit for those who spend more time at the pool and restaurants than on the sand.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April when rainfall is lowest and humidity is manageable. Mexico's Riviera Maya can see hurricane-season swells August through October, while Punta Cana sits in a similar Atlantic hurricane corridor with peak risk in September. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates with generally acceptable weather at both properties.","activities":"Both resorts share a strong core of watersports including diving, snorkelling, and swim-up bar access, plus spa facilities, gym, nightclub, and evening entertainment. Maroma adds tennis courts. Off-property, Maroma guests are well-positioned for cenote tours, Tulum ruins, and Playa del Carmen day trips, while Tides guests can access Bavaro's wider resort strip, Hoyo Azul, and Saona Island excursions."},"dreams-la-romana-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams La Romana is a family-focused Dominican Republic all-inclusive in Bayahibe with a waterpark, kids club, teen club, lazy river, pool slide, casino, babysitting, and adults-only pool, rated overall 9.2. Secrets Maroma Beach is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on the Riviera Cancun's famed Maroma Beach, rated overall 9.6 with a commanding lead across nearly every measurable category: food (8.4 vs 7.5), pool (8.4 vs 7.3), atmosphere (8.7 vs 7.1), room (9.5 vs 8.8), cleanliness (9.7 vs 9.0), and service (9.5 vs 9.0). Secrets Maroma's beach rating of 8.2 edges Dreams La Romana's 7.8, and its location score of 9.6 versus 9.0 reflects access to one of the Caribbean's most celebrated stretches of sand. Dreams La Romana offers more activity breadth for mixed-age groups, while Secrets Maroma delivers a markedly higher-quality experience in rooms, dining, and atmosphere for couples and adults seeking a refined, quieter setting. The gap in food and atmosphere ratings is particularly telling.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a lively Dominican Republic all-inclusive with a full waterpark, kids and teen clubs, a casino, babysitting, and broad activity coverage. A strong overall score at a competitive price point makes it a solid family value despite lower food and atmosphere ratings.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples and honeymooners seeking a high-performance adults-only all-inclusive on one of Mexico's finest beaches. With standout scores in rooms, cleanliness, service, atmosphere, and food, Secrets Maroma consistently outperforms in the categories that matter most to guests looking for a polished, romantic retreat.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations offer year-round sun. The Dominican Republic's Bayahibe area is driest from December through April, with hurricane risk peaking August through October. Mexico's Riviera Cancun shares a similar pattern, with peak dry season running November through April. Both resorts command higher prices over Christmas, New Year, and spring break, so shoulder months like May or November offer better value at either property.","activities":"At Dreams La Romana, guests can explore the UNESCO-listed Altos de Chavón village, dive Bayahibe's coral reefs, or visit the nearby Cotubanamá National Park and Saona Island. At Secrets Maroma, guests can snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, explore the Sian Ka'an Biosphere Reserve, take day trips to Tulum's clifftop ruins, or enjoy tennis and diving directly on property."},"secrets-maroma-beach-vs-secrets-the-vine-cancun":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun and Secrets The Vine Cancun are both adults-only Mexican all-inclusives at the same price tier, but they differ meaningfully across nearly every rating category. Maroma Beach holds a 9.6 overall versus The Vine's 9.2, with especially wide gaps in location (9.6 vs 9.0), room (9.5 vs 9.3), atmosphere (8.7 vs 8.0), pool (8.4 vs 7.8), and value (9.1 vs 8.7). Maroma Beach sits on one of the Riviera Maya's most celebrated stretches of white-sand coastline in a quieter, more secluded setting, with swim-up bar, snorkelling, tennis, and diving rounding out its beach-focused amenity set. The Vine is an urban high-rise in Cancun's Hotel Zone, better positioned for guests who want easy access to Cancun's nightlife and downtown scene, and it adds a heated pool and no-reservation dining policy. Maroma Beach wins on beach environment and overall atmosphere by a clear margin; The Vine trades those advantages for urban convenience and slightly better beach scores (8.3 vs 8.2), though the beach experience is a different character entirely.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults and couples who want a secluded, high-rated Riviera Maya beach escape with pristine white sand, swim-up bar, snorkelling, and tennis in a tranquil, resort-focused setting away from the bustle of Cancun city. Best for those prioritising natural beach quality and atmosphere over urban access.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who want a polished Cancun Hotel Zone all-inclusive with easy access to the city's restaurants, clubs, and shopping, plus the convenience of no-reservation dining and a heated pool. A better fit for guests who plan to explore beyond the resort or who prefer an urban high-rise setting.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the same Yucatán Peninsula climate. December through April offers the driest, most reliably sunny conditions at either property. Summer months bring heat and humidity. Hurricane season runs June through November, with peak risk in September and October. For Maroma Beach, shoulder months like May or early December offer strong value; The Vine's urban location makes it workable year-round for short stays.","activities":"At Maroma Beach, guests can snorkel directly off the beach, dive with onsite operators, play tennis, and use the swim-up bar. The Vine offers diving access and evening entertainment within the Hotel Zone. Both properties are within reach of Xcaret and Xel-Há eco-parks, Tulum ruins, Cenote Dos Ojos, and the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef. The Vine's Cancun location adds immediate proximity to the Hotel Zone's bars, clubs, and shopping malls."},"secrets-maroma-beach-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun is an adults-only luxury all-inclusive on the Riviera Maya, built around one of Mexico's most celebrated stretches of Caribbean coastline, with beach (8.2), pool (8.4), snorkelling, diving, and tennis anchoring its offering. Its overall rating of 9.6, room score of 9.5, and location rating of 9.6 reflect a property firing on nearly all cylinders. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only all-inclusive in San Jose del Cabo with a golf course, archery, fishing, yoga, and mini golf, but its beach rating of 3.5 is a critical gap — the Pacific surf at Los Cabos is typically too rough for swimming. Its overall (8.9), pool (7.8), and atmosphere (8.0) ratings all trail Maroma meaningfully. Los Cabos compensates with desert-meets-ocean scenery and a strong activity roster for land-based guests. If pristine Caribbean beach access and near-perfect scores across the board define your holiday, choose Maroma. If a golf course, fishing, and dramatic Baja scenery matter more than swimming off the sand, choose Los Cabos.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a beach-first luxury all-inclusive on one of Mexico's finest Caribbean shores, with strong ratings across food, rooms, service, and atmosphere, diving and snorkelling on the doorstep, and evening entertainment in a polished Riviera Maya setting.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who prioritise land-based pursuits — golf, fishing, archery, yoga — over beach swimming, and who are drawn to the rugged Baja Peninsula landscape around San Jose del Cabo. Best suited to those who won't be disappointed by an essentially non-swimmable Pacific beachfront.","whenToVisit":"Maroma on the Riviera Maya is best November through April, when humidity drops and hurricane risk is minimal; summer brings heat, rain, and occasional storms. Los Cabos suits year-round visits but is most comfortable October through June, avoiding the late-summer tropical storm window. Both resorts sit at the same premium price tier, so season primarily affects weather rather than value.","activities":"Maroma guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, one of the world's largest coral systems, or take excursions to Tulum ruins and Cobá. Los Cabos guests can arrange deep-sea fishing for marlin and dorado, play golf on a resort course, explore the iconic Land's End arch by boat, or visit the historic San Jose del Cabo art district. Both resorts offer spa, swim-up bar, nightclub, and evening entertainment on-site."},"breathless-cabo-san-lucas-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Breathless Cabo San Lucas is an adults-only party-focused resort on Mexico's Pacific coast in Cabo San Lucas, with a nightclub, heated pool, fishing, and a lively Xhale Club atmosphere built around energy and entertainment. Secrets Maroma Beach is an adults-only luxury all-inclusive on the Riviera Maya facing the Caribbean, with a swim-up bar, diving, snorkelling, tennis, and one of Mexico's most celebrated beaches. The rating gaps are significant: Secrets Maroma outscores Breathless Cabo across virtually every category, including food (8.4 vs 7.5), beach (8.2 vs 6.5), pool (8.4 vs 7.6), atmosphere (8.7 vs 7.7), room (9.5 vs 8.9), cleanliness (9.7 vs 9.2), sleep quality (9.0 vs 7.9), and overall (9.6 vs 9.1). Cabo's lower beach score reflects the Pacific's rougher surf conditions, which limit swimming. Breathless holds its own on location (9.2) and value (8.7), but Secrets Maroma's across-the-board excellence makes it the stronger luxury proposition at the same price tier.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want an energetic, nightlife-forward all-inclusive in Cabo San Lucas with Pacific Ocean scenery, fishing excursions, and a resort built around socializing and entertainment rather than quiet relaxation. Best for guests drawn to Cabo's rugged desert-meets-ocean landscape.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adults seeking a polished, high-performing luxury all-inclusive on a genuinely world-class Caribbean beach. Ideal for those prioritizing exceptional food, immaculate rooms, calm swimmable water, and a refined atmosphere with watersports including diving and snorkelling.","whenToVisit":"Cabo San Lucas is best November through May when Pacific weather is dry and stable; summer brings heat and occasional hurricane risk. Playa Maroma and the Riviera Maya peak December through April with calm seas and low humidity. Both destinations share a similar dry-season window, though Maroma's Caribbean side offers more reliable water clarity year-round for snorkelling and diving.","activities":"Breathless Cabo guests can explore Cabo San Lucas town, take sportfishing charters, visit El Arco rock formation, and ATV into the Baja desert. Secrets Maroma guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, explore the Riviera Maya's cenotes, visit Tulum ruins, and take excursions to Cobá. Both resorts offer on-site spa, gym, nightclub, and evening entertainment programs."},"secrets-maroma-beach-vs-secrets-royal-beach-punta-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only, luxury-tier all-inclusives in the same brand family, but the ratings tell a clear story: Secrets Maroma Beach outscores Secrets Royal Beach Punta Cana across nearly every dimension. Maroma leads in overall score (9.6 vs 9.1), location (9.6 vs 8.8), rooms (9.5 vs 8.9), atmosphere (8.7 vs 7.8), food (8.4 vs 7.9), beach (8.2 vs 8.0), and pool (8.4 vs 7.8). That atmosphere gap of nearly a full point is significant for an adults-only property. Maroma sits on one of Mexico's most celebrated stretches of Caribbean coastline, a differentiator reflected in its near-perfect location score. Royal Beach Punta Cana counters with a lazy river, a casino, and a no-reservations dining policy that adds flexibility, and its cleanliness and service ratings are strong at 9.2 each. At the same price tier, Maroma delivers a measurably superior experience on almost every metric, while Royal Beach offers a livelier Dominican setting with a casino and a more laid-back poolside vibe.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and adult travellers who want the best available beach and room quality at the luxury all-inclusive tier, and for whom atmosphere and location are non-negotiable. Those drawn to Mexico's Riviera Maya and willing to pay a premium for one of the Caribbean's most consistently top-rated resort experiences.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who want a luxury Dominican Republic all-inclusive with the added draw of a casino, a lazy river, and flexible no-reservation dining. A good fit for those already committed to Punta Cana or who prefer a livelier, game-friendly resort atmosphere without sacrificing strong service and cleanliness scores.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April in dry-season conditions. Mexico's Riviera Maya sees its calmest seas and lowest humidity in those months, making Maroma especially appealing for beach and snorkelling. Punta Cana shares a similar weather window but is more prone to brief tropical showers year-round. Both properties should be avoided during peak Atlantic hurricane season, roughly August through October.","activities":"At Maroma, guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, one of the world's largest barrier reef systems, or use the tennis courts, spa, gym, and evening entertainment program. Nearby cenotes and Tulum ruins are accessible day trips. At Royal Beach Punta Cana, guests enjoy the lazy river, casino, diving, tennis, spa, and evening entertainment, with Saona Island excursions and Indigenous Eyes Ecological Reserve within reach."},"dreams-cap-cana-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Cap Cana and Secrets Maroma Beach are both priced at the same premium tier, but they serve fundamentally different audiences and deliver different experiences. Dreams Cap Cana is a family-focused Dominican Republic resort in Cap Cana with a kids club for children under 4 and up, a swim-up bar, and no-reservation restaurants. It scores exceptionally on location (9.5), cleanliness (9.5), rooms (9.4), and service (9.4), but lags noticeably on food (7.7), pool (7.4), and atmosphere (7.6). Secrets Maroma Beach is an adults-only Mexican retreat on the Riviera Cancun with a broader amenity set including diving, snorkelling, a spa, tennis, nightclub, and evening entertainment. It outscores Dreams Cap Cana on nearly every measurable dimension: food (8.4 vs 7.7), pool (8.4 vs 7.4), atmosphere (8.7 vs 7.6), sleep quality (9.0 vs 8.5), and cleanliness (9.7 vs 9.5). Beach scores narrowly favour Dreams Cap Cana (8.5 vs 8.2). For families, Dreams Cap Cana is the clear choice; for couples or solo adults wanting a more polished, amenity-rich experience, Secrets Maroma Beach is meaningfully superior.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children, including infants and toddlers, who want a premium Dominican Republic all-inclusive with a kids club starting from under age 4, a great beach, outstanding rooms and service, and no need to wrestle with restaurant reservations.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adults seeking a refined, adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on one of the Riviera Cancun's most celebrated beaches, with superior food scores, a spa, diving, snorkelling, tennis, nightclub, and one of the cleanest and highest-rated atmospheres in the region.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak from December through April during dry season. The Dominican Republic's Cap Cana area sees its wettest months from May through November, with peak hurricane risk in September and October. Mexico's Riviera Cancun shares a similar pattern, with hurricane season running June through November. For either resort, January through March offers the most reliable weather and lowest humidity.","activities":"At Dreams Cap Cana, guests can explore Cap Cana's marina, championship golf courses, and nearby Hoyo Azul cenote lagoon. At Secrets Maroma Beach, on-site diving and snorkelling access to Mesoamerican Reef systems, tennis, and a spa round out the day, with Playa del Carmen's shops and cenote parks a short drive away. Both resorts offer swim-up bars and beach access as their social anchor."},"dreams-royal-beach-punta-cana-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Royal Beach Punta Cana is a large family all-inclusive in Bavaro with a waterpark, lazy river, kids club, teen club, casino, nightclub, and babysitting across a broad amenity set at a competitive price point. Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun is an adults-only luxury all-inclusive on one of Mexico's most celebrated stretches of Caribbean sand, rated significantly higher across nearly every measurable category. Secrets leads on overall score (9.6 vs 9.1), food (8.4 vs 7.5), pool (8.4 vs 7.3), atmosphere (8.7 vs 7.4), room quality (9.5 vs 8.8), cleanliness (9.7 vs 9.1), service (9.5 vs 9.1), and sleep quality (9.0 vs 8.4). Dreams edges ahead only in the breadth of family-specific amenities. The core trade-off is clear: Dreams delivers a full-featured Dominican family resort with infrastructure for children of all ages, while Secrets delivers a quieter, more refined adults-only experience on a world-class beach with markedly better food, rooms, and atmosphere. If you want child-friendly activities and a lively resort environment, choose Dreams. If you want elevated quality across the board without children, choose Secrets.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages, including under-4s, who want a lively Dominican all-inclusive with a waterpark, lazy river, kids and teen clubs, casino, and evening entertainment without needing restaurant reservations. A strong value proposition for larger groups needing rooms for five or more.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adults seeking a premium, child-free experience on one of the Riviera Maya's finest beaches. Those who prioritize exceptional room quality, cleaner facilities, superior food, and a refined atmosphere over a broad activity lineup will find Secrets Maroma hard to beat.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April. Punta Cana's Bavaro coast is drier and calmer during these months, with hurricane season running June through November. Playa Maroma enjoys similar dry-season conditions but sits closer to the Yucatán's more consistent Caribbean breezes. Both resorts are busiest over U.S. holidays and spring break; visiting January through early March avoids the largest crowds at either property.","activities":"At Dreams Royal Beach, guests can dive, snorkel, play tennis, visit the waterpark and lazy river, or access the casino and nightclub on-site. Punta Cana excels in offshore excursions including catamaran trips and dune buggy tours. At Secrets Maroma, diving and snorkelling along the Mesoamerican Reef are standout draws, with cenote tours, eco-park visits at Xcaret and Xel-Há, and Tulum ruins all within reach."},"dreams-flora-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Flora Resort & Spa is a large Dominican Republic family all-inclusive in Cabeza de Toro with a kids club, teen club, waterpark, babysitting, nightclub, and rooms sleeping 5 or more, aimed squarely at families at the same high price tier. Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on Playa Maroma, one of the Riviera Maya's most celebrated beaches, with diving, snorkelling, a swim-up bar, tennis, and spa in a more intimate, refined setting. The rating gaps are striking: Secrets leads on overall (9.6 vs 9.0), food (8.4 vs 7.6), beach (8.2 vs 6.8), pool (8.4 vs 7.3), atmosphere (8.7 vs 7.4), room (9.5 vs 8.9), cleanliness (9.7 vs 9.1), and service (9.5 vs 9.0). Dreams Flora holds its own on value (8.7 vs 9.1) and location (8.7 vs 9.6), but the breadth of those gaps makes Secrets the stronger performer across nearly every measurable category. The core split is family resort versus adults-only retreat.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a full-service Dominican Republic all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, waterpark, babysitting, and large-group rooms. The no-reservation restaurant policy and evening entertainment make it practical and accessible for parents who need flexibility.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adults seeking a premium, peaceful Riviera Maya escape on one of Mexico's top-rated beaches. Those who prioritize exceptional rooms, flawless cleanliness, strong food ratings, diving, and snorkelling in an adults-only atmosphere will find Secrets Maroma hard to beat at this price level.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April when rainfall is low and humidity manageable. The Dominican Republic's hurricane season runs June through November, with September the riskiest month. Mexico's Riviera Maya shares a similar risk window but typically sees less severe storms than the eastern Caribbean. Shoulder seasons of late November and early May offer better value with still-reliable weather at both properties.","activities":"Dreams Flora guests can use the on-site waterpark, kids and teen clubs, nightclub, and spa, with Punta Cana's golf courses, dune buggy excursions, and Hoyo Azul cenote nearby. Secrets Maroma guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, play tennis, visit the Tulum archaeological site, explore cenotes, and access the boutiques and restaurants of Playa del Carmen, all within easy reach of the resort."},"secrets-maroma-beach-vs-secrets-vallarta-bay-puerto-vallarta":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only Secrets properties in Mexico at the same price level, but their ratings tell meaningfully different stories. Secrets Maroma Beach edges Secrets Vallarta Bay on nearly every metric: overall (9.6 vs 9.0), beach (8.2 vs 6.0), pool (8.4 vs 7.4), atmosphere (8.7 vs 7.5), room (9.5 vs 9.0), and food (8.4 vs 7.9). The beach gap is the starkest difference — Maroma sits on one of the Riviera Maya's most celebrated stretches of white-sand Caribbean coastline, while Vallarta Bay's beach scores a notably low 6.0, typical of the rockier, darker-sand Pacific coast around Puerto Vallarta. Vallarta Bay adds a heated pool and no-reservation dining, useful practical touches, and holds its own on service (9.2 vs 9.5) and cleanliness (9.2 vs 9.7). Maroma commands a higher value score (9.1 vs 8.7) despite identical pricing, suggesting guests feel it delivers more for the money. Maroma also offers diving and snorkelling, absent at Vallarta Bay.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and adults who prioritize a world-class Caribbean beach — fine white sand, calm turquoise water — and want the full Secrets package with top-tier rooms, diving, snorkelling, and consistently high scores across food, atmosphere, and service on the Riviera Maya.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who prefer the Pacific Coast character of Puerto Vallarta — a more urban, culturally rich setting with easy access to the city — and are comfortable trading a lower beach score for proximity to Puerto Vallarta's restaurants, nightlife, and mountain-meets-ocean scenery.","whenToVisit":"Maroma's Riviera Maya location is best November through April when the Caribbean coast is dry, calm, and at its most inviting; hurricane season runs June through October. Puerto Vallarta's dry season also runs November through May, with the Pacific coast seeing heavier rainfall from July through October. Both resorts are at their best during the same core winter window, making late November through early April the sweet spot for either.","activities":"At Maroma, guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, the second-largest barrier reef in the world, directly from the resort, alongside tennis, spa, and swim-up bar. Vallarta Bay sits close to Puerto Vallarta's Malecón boardwalk, whale-watching excursions (humpbacks visit November through March), zip-lining in the Sierra Madre, and the cobblestone streets of the Romantic Zone, offering more off-resort cultural exploration than Maroma's more secluded Riviera Maya setting."},"secrets-maroma-beach-vs-secrets-papagayo-costa-rica":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only Secrets properties at the same price tier, but their ratings tell meaningfully different stories. Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun scores a near-perfect 9.6 overall and 9.6 for location, backed by one of the Riviera Maya's most celebrated stretches of white-sand beach — though its beach rating of 8.2 and food at 8.4 suggest even top-tier resorts have ceilings. Secrets Papagayo sits on the Gulf of Papagayo in Costa Rica and scores a solid 9.0 overall, but its beach rating of 6.0 and pool rating of 7.4 are the real differentiators — this is a rocky-cove Pacific destination, not a powder-sand Caribbean one. Papagayo's room score of 8.9 and sleep quality of 8.2 lag Maroma's 9.5 and 9.0 respectively. Maroma wins on atmosphere (8.7 vs 8.0), food (8.4 vs 7.7), and value (9.1 vs 8.6). Papagayo's appeal is its unique Costa Rican setting and access to nature, not its beach or pool infrastructure.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and adult travelers who want the definitive Caribbean all-inclusive experience — a world-class white-sand beach, high service scores, strong food and atmosphere ratings, and polished Riviera Maya infrastructure. If a pristine beach is non-negotiable, Maroma's reputation is well earned.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults drawn to Costa Rica's wildlife, rainforest, and adventure tourism who are willing to trade a great beach for an extraordinary natural setting. Best suited to couples who prioritize excursions and local experiences over lounging on sand, and who won't judge the resort by its shoreline.","whenToVisit":"Maroma's dry season runs December through April, when the Caribbean side delivers calm, clear water — peak months come with peak prices. Papagayo sits in Costa Rica's driest corridor; the Guanacaste dry season also runs December through April, making it one of the more reliably sunny destinations on the Pacific coast. Both resorts are priciest during North American winter holidays.","activities":"Maroma offers diving, snorkelling, tennis, a nightclub, evening entertainment, and a spa on a calm Caribbean beach, with Playa del Carmen, Tulum ruins, and cenote tours nearby. Papagayo adds fishing to a similar core list and benefits from proximity to Rincon de la Vieja volcano, zip-lining, wildlife watching, and Guanacaste's varied national parks — making it the stronger base for land-based adventure excursions."},"secrets-maroma-beach-vs-sunscape-cancun-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun is an adults-only luxury all-inclusive on the highly regarded Playa Maroma strip, rated 9.6 overall with standout scores for location (9.6), cleanliness (9.7), rooms (9.5), and service (9.5), at a premium price point. Sunscape Cancun Resort & Spa is a family all-inclusive in Cancun proper, rated 8.8 overall, with a kids club, teen club, waterpark, babysitting, and large-group rooms, but noticeably weaker scores in food (6.3 vs 8.4), pool (6.4 vs 8.4), and atmosphere (6.1 vs 8.7). The gap in food and atmosphere ratings is significant and hard to overlook. Secrets Maroma is the clearer choice for couples seeking a polished, beach-forward adults retreat, while Sunscape Cancun trades experiential quality for family infrastructure and convenience. If you want a top-rated adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on one of the Riviera Maya's best beaches with excellent rooms and service, choose Secrets Maroma. If you need a family-oriented Cancun resort with a waterpark, kids and teen clubs, babysitting, and rooms for five or more, choose Sunscape Cancun.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples or adult friends seeking a high-end, adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on a premier beach, where strong room quality, attentive service, and a refined atmosphere justify the premium price. Not suitable for families or guests travelling with children.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of varying ages who need a Cancun all-inclusive with a waterpark, dedicated kids and teen clubs, babysitting, and rooms that sleep five or more. Guests should temper expectations around food quality and pool atmosphere going in.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in Mexico's Yucatan coast corridor, where the driest and calmest weather runs from December through April. July and August bring peak family travel demand to Sunscape, so book early for the best rooms. Secrets Maroma is best visited outside Mexican holiday weeks in November through April to enjoy calmer beaches and quieter conditions at Playa Maroma.","activities":"Secrets Maroma offers diving, snorkelling, tennis, a spa, swim-up bar, and evening entertainment on a calm stretch of Riviera Maya beach, with cenotes and Tulum day trips nearby. Sunscape Cancun adds a waterpark for little kids, fishing excursions, and a teen club within Cancun's Hotel Zone, putting guests close to Isla Mujeres ferry trips, ATV tours, and the Cancun nightlife strip."},"secrets-maroma-beach-vs-secrets-playa-mujeres-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only Secrets properties in Mexico at the same price tier, but their ratings and settings diverge meaningfully. Secrets Maroma Beach outscores Playa Mujeres across nearly every category: overall (9.6 vs 8.8), beach (8.2 vs 7.5), pool (8.4 vs 8.0), atmosphere (8.7 vs 8.0), room (9.5 vs 9.0), and value (9.1 vs 8.6). Maroma's defining advantage is its location on one of Mexico's most celebrated stretches of Caribbean coastline, reflected in a near-perfect location score of 9.6 versus Playa Mujeres' 8.9. Playa Mujeres counters with a dedicated golf course and a heated pool, and edges Maroma slightly on sleep quality (9.1 vs 9.0). Maroma also offers diving and snorkelling, while Playa Mujeres features no-reservation dining across its restaurants. Cleanliness and service are strong at both, but Maroma holds the edge there too. In short, Maroma is the more complete beach-forward luxury escape; Playa Mujeres trades some beach prestige for golf and a quieter northern Cancun setting.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and adult travellers who want the best possible Caribbean beach experience in Mexico, with diving, snorkelling, and a vibrant atmosphere. Those who prioritise an exceptional location, immaculate rooms, and strong overall value at the luxury all-inclusive tier will find Maroma the harder property to beat.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult travellers, particularly golfers, who want a quieter all-inclusive setting away from the main Riviera Maya strip. The on-site golf course, heated pool, and no-reservation dining policy make Playa Mujeres a strong fit for those who prefer a more relaxed, low-friction luxury stay over a premium beach destination.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's Yucatán dry season, running roughly December through April, when rainfall is minimal and temperatures are warm without being oppressive. Peak holiday weeks drive up prices at both properties. The Atlantic hurricane season runs June through November, with September the riskiest month. Shoulder months like May and early December offer a balance of good weather and softer rates.","activities":"At Maroma, guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, among the world's largest coral systems, and use the full beach and watersports setup. Playa Mujeres guests can play the on-site championship golf course and access the quieter northern Cancun coastline. Both properties offer spa treatments, tennis, swim-up bars, evening entertainment, nightclubs, and gym facilities, with Cancun's broader excursion network accessible from either resort."},"dreams-onyx-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Onyx Resort & Spa is a large family all-inclusive in Punta Cana with a waterpark, kids club, teen club, lazy river, babysitting, and rooms for five or more guests, designed to accommodate families at every age. Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun is an adults-only luxury all-inclusive on Mexico's Playa Maroma, rated significantly higher across nearly every measurable category: beach (8.2 vs 6.5), food (8.4 vs 7.6), pool (8.4 vs 7.4), atmosphere (8.7 vs 7.4), room (9.5 vs 8.7), cleanliness (9.7 vs 9.1), and service (9.5 vs 9.0). The overall gap of 0.5 points (9.6 vs 9.1) understates how consistently Secrets outperforms on experiential quality. Dreams Onyx wins on family infrastructure and value for group travel, while Secrets Maroma delivers a quieter, more refined experience on one of Mexico's most celebrated beaches with diving, snorkelling, and tennis rounding out a polished adult program. These resorts serve fundamentally different guests.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a large Dominican Republic all-inclusive with a waterpark, lazy river, kids and teen clubs, babysitting, and spacious rooms for five or more guests. A strong overall rating at a competitive price point makes it a reliable family choice.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travelers who want a premium, adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on one of the Caribbean's top-rated beaches. Near-perfect scores across cleanliness, service, rooms, and location make Secrets Maroma a strong choice for honeymooners or anyone prioritizing an elevated, tranquil atmosphere.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak in winter and spring. Punta Cana's dry season runs December through April, with shoulder months offering good value before summer humidity builds. Playa Maroma similarly shines from November through May, when the Riviera Maya sees minimal rain and calm seas ideal for diving and snorkelling. Both carry some hurricane risk between June and October, though Punta Cana is generally more exposed.","activities":"Dreams Onyx centers on its family water amenities including a waterpark, lazy river, and swim-up bar, with evening entertainment rounding out each day. Secrets Maroma broadens the adult activity palette with diving, snorkelling, and tennis alongside its swim-up bar and nightclub. Both resorts offer spa facilities and gym access. Off-property, Playa Maroma sits near Tulum ruins, cenotes, and Playa del Carmen, while Punta Cana offers excursions to Saona Island and local cultural parks."},"secrets-huatulco-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only Secrets properties in Mexico at the same price tier, but their ratings tell meaningfully different stories. Secrets Maroma Beach outscores Secrets Huatulco across nearly every category: overall 9.6 vs 8.8, beach 8.2 vs 6.8, pool 8.4 vs 7.4, food 8.4 vs 7.9, atmosphere 8.7 vs 7.9, room 9.5 vs 8.9, cleanliness 9.7 vs 9.1, and service 9.5 vs 9.1. Huatulco's strongest suit is its location score (9.1) and relative seclusion on the Pacific coast, a UNESCO-protected bay area that keeps the surroundings quieter and less developed. Maroma counters with one of the Riviera Maya's most celebrated natural beaches and adds diving and tennis that Huatulco lacks. Huatulco scores slightly better on value at 8.7 vs 9.1 in Maroma's favor — meaning Maroma delivers more perceived value despite likely costing as much or more. For guests willing to pay the same rate, Maroma's performance advantage across food, beach, pool, rooms, and service is hard to argue against.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a quieter, less-trafficked Pacific Mexico escape in a UNESCO-protected bay setting. Huatulco's location and cleanliness scores are genuinely strong, and guests who prefer a more off-the-beaten-path atmosphere away from the Cancun corridor will find it rewarding despite lower beach and pool ratings.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who want the best all-around Secrets experience and are willing to pay for it. Maroma's combination of a world-class natural beach, top-tier rooms, near-flawless cleanliness, and exceptional service makes it one of the strongest-performing adults-only resorts on the Riviera Maya for guests who prioritize quality across every category.","whenToVisit":"Huatulco on the Pacific coast runs dry and sunny from October through May, with July and August bringing heavier rain and humidity. Maroma on the Caribbean side peaks November through April; September and October sit in hurricane season and bring risk of rough seas and storms. Both properties are at their best during the December to April window, though Maroma's shoulder months of May and June often offer strong value.","activities":"Both resorts cover snorkelling, swim-up bar, spa, gym, nightclub, and evening entertainment. Maroma adds diving and tennis that Huatulco does not list. Off-property, Huatulco offers bay boat tours, sea turtle watching, and the relatively undeveloped Sierra de Juárez foothills. Maroma sits closer to Tulum ruins, cenote swimming, Cobá, and the broader Riviera Maya activity corridor, giving it a significant edge for guests wanting excursion variety."},"secrets-bahia-mita-surf-and-spa-resort-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Bahia Mita Surf & Spa Resort sits on Mexico's Pacific coast in Punta de Mita, a quieter surf-influenced destination near Sayulita and the Riviera Nayarit, with strong room (9.1), service (9.2), and cleanliness (9.3) scores but a notably weak beach rating of 5.0 and modest food and pool scores of 7.8 each. Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun, on the Riviera Maya's celebrated Playa Maroma, outperforms it across virtually every category: overall 9.6 vs 8.9, beach 8.2 vs 5.0, food 8.4 vs 7.8, pool 8.4 vs 7.8, atmosphere 8.7 vs 7.7, and a near-perfect cleanliness score of 9.7. Maroma also adds diving, snorkelling, and tennis that Bahia Mita lacks, while Bahia Mita allows pets and skips reservation requirements at restaurants. The gap is decisive: Maroma delivers a premium Caribbean beach experience across the board, while Bahia Mita trades on Pacific coast character, surf proximity, and exceptional rooms and service despite a beach that clearly underdelivers.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a Pacific Mexico base near Punta de Mita's surf breaks and Sayulita's village atmosphere, prioritize immaculate rooms and attentive service, are comfortable with a weaker beach, and may be travelling with a pet.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults seeking one of the Mexican Caribbean's top-rated beach experiences, with consistently high scores across food, pool, service, cleanliness, and location, and who want diving and snorkelling on the renowned Playa Maroma.","whenToVisit":"Secrets Maroma is best November through April, when the Riviera Maya is dry and calm with minimal hurricane risk. Secrets Bahia Mita suits November through April as well, avoiding the Pacific rainy season that peaks June through October. Both share the same peak winter window, so book either early if travelling during the Mexican holiday weeks of late December or Semana Santa.","activities":"At Bahia Mita, guests are well-placed for surfing Punta de Mita's breaks, exploring Sayulita's bohemian village, whale-watching seasonally, and visiting the Marieta Islands. At Maroma, on-site diving and snorkelling on the Mesoamerican Reef are the headline draws, alongside cenote tours, Tulum day trips, and Mayan archaeological sites, all easily accessed from the Riviera Maya's well-developed excursion network."},"dreams-huatulco-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Huatulco Resort & Spa is a family all-inclusive on Mexico's Pacific coast in the quieter Tangolunda bay, with a kids club, babysitting, archery, windsurfing, yoga, and a relaxed atmosphere well removed from the Cancun resort corridor. Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun is an adults-only all-inclusive on the Riviera Maya facing the Caribbean, with a swim-up bar, diving, tennis, nightclub, and one of the region's most celebrated stretches of white-sand beach. The ratings tell a clear story: Secrets outscores Dreams across every single category, with especially wide gaps in overall score (9.6 vs 8.9), food (8.4 vs 7.5), beach (8.2 vs 7.3), pool (8.4 vs 6.9), atmosphere (8.7 vs 7.4), and room quality (9.5 vs 8.6). Dreams offers strong value and service in a secluded Pacific setting with family infrastructure; Secrets delivers a premium adults-only experience on a world-class Caribbean beach at a commensurately higher standard across the board. If you want a family-friendly Pacific Mexico all-inclusive in an uncrowded bay with excellent service and value, go to Dreams Huatulco. If you want a top-rated adults-only Caribbean all-inclusive on a stunning Riviera Maya beach, go to Secrets Maroma Beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who want a well-serviced, secluded Pacific Mexico all-inclusive with a kids club, babysitting, archery, windsurfing, and yoga in a quieter, less touristed setting at strong value for the price level.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travelers who want a premium adults-only Caribbean all-inclusive on one of the Riviera Maya's finest beaches, with top-tier rooms, exceptional food and service, a swim-up bar, nightclub, and diving on their doorstep.","whenToVisit":"Huatulco's Pacific coast is driest and calmest from November through April, with the rainy season running June through October. Maroma on the Riviera Maya is best from December through April when humidity drops and Caribbean seas are calm; hurricane season peaks September and October, though that period can bring lower rates at Secrets for travelers willing to accept some weather risk.","activities":"At Dreams Huatulco, guests can snorkel the bay, windsurf, fish offshore, take yoga classes, try archery on-site, or explore the nine bays of Huatulco's national park nearby. At Secrets Maroma, guests can dive the Mesoamerican Reef, snorkel, play tennis, or day-trip to Tulum ruins, Cobá, and the cenotes of the Riviera Maya, all within an hour or two of the resort."},"dreams-playa-mujeres-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Playa Mujeres is a large family all-inclusive on the quieter Playa Mujeres strip north of Cancun, built around an extensive amenity set including a waterpark, lazy river, kids club for under-4s, teen club, babysitting, mini golf, and a golf course. Secrets Maroma Beach is an adults-only all-inclusive on the celebrated Playa Maroma, one of the finest stretches of Caribbean sand in Mexico, with diving, snorkelling, tennis, and room service in a more intimate, couples-focused environment. The rating gap is significant: Secrets Maroma leads on nearly every metric, with an overall 9.6 versus Dreams' 8.9, beach 8.2 versus 7.5, atmosphere 8.7 versus 7.6, room 9.5 versus 9.0, and value 9.1 versus 8.4. Food also skews higher at Secrets (8.4 versus 7.9). Dreams holds its own on cleanliness (9.2) and location (8.9) and wins on family infrastructure, but Secrets Maroma is the stronger all-around resort for guests who don't need children's programming.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a large Mexican all-inclusive with a waterpark, lazy river, kids club from infancy, teen club, babysitting, and golf, all on a relatively uncrowded stretch north of Cancun where large family rooms and no-reservation dining make logistics easy.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups seeking a premium, adults-only Mexican retreat on one of the Caribbean's most acclaimed beaches, where high cleanliness scores (9.7), beautifully rated rooms (9.5), diving, snorkelling, and a refined atmosphere justify a stay at the same price tier as a family resort.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the same Yucatan Peninsula weather window: mid-November through late April delivers dry, sunny conditions with low humidity. Peak weeks around Christmas, New Year, and spring break bring higher rates and more crowded resorts at both properties. Shoulder months of November and late April offer the best balance of good weather and value across both.","activities":"At Dreams Playa Mujeres, the on-site golf course, waterpark, lazy river, and mini golf keep families occupied without leaving the property. Isla Mujeres is a short ferry ride away for snorkelling and exploring. Secrets Maroma guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef directly offshore, play tennis on-site, or arrange excursions to the Sian Ka'an Biosphere Reserve and Tulum ruins, both within roughly an hour's drive south."},"secrets-maroma-beach-vs-secrets-playa-esmeralda-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun is a premium adults-only all-inclusive on Mexico's Riviera Maya, rated 9.6 overall with standout scores for location (9.6), cleanliness (9.7), room quality (9.5), and service (9.5). It commands a $$$$ price point and backs it up with a full amenity set including diving, snorkelling, swim-up bar, tennis, spa, nightclub, and evening entertainment. Secrets Playa Esmeralda is a more affordable $$$ adults-only resort in Miches on the Dominican Republic's less-developed northeast coast, rated 8.2 overall, with notably lower scores across location (7.8), pool (7.8), and value (7.9), though it edges ahead on beach (8.5 vs 8.2) and sleep quality (9.1 vs 9.0). The amenity gap is significant: Playa Esmeralda lacks a swim-up bar, nightclub, diving, snorkelling, and tennis. Maroma Beach is the clear choice for guests who want a polished, activity-rich luxury experience; Playa Esmeralda suits those prioritising a quieter, more remote beach setting at a lower spend.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and adults who want a top-rated luxury Mexican all-inclusive with exceptional service, beautifully appointed rooms, and a full activity lineup including diving, snorkelling, tennis, and evening entertainment on one of the Riviera Maya's most celebrated stretches of beach.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults seeking a quieter, more secluded Dominican Republic escape at a lower price point, who value a pristine, less-crowded beach and solid sleep quality over a broad amenity set or lively nightlife, and don't mind a more remote, underdeveloped location in Miches.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Caribbean's dry season, roughly December through April, when rainfall is lowest and trade winds keep temperatures comfortable. Maroma Beach can see hurricane-season humidity from August through October but remains popular year-round. Miches on the Dominican Republic's northeast coast faces a wetter, more unpredictable pattern even in peak months, so December through March is the safest window for Playa Esmeralda.","activities":"At Maroma Beach guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, play tennis, use the swim-up bar, and access evening entertainment and a nightclub on-site, with Tulum ruins and Cenote Dos Ojos day trips nearby. Playa Esmeralda's on-site activity list is leaner, but guests can explore the undeveloped Miches coastline, arrange excursions to Laguna Limón, and visit Samana's whale-watching grounds seasonally."},"breathless-punta-cana-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Breathless Punta Cana is an adults-only Dominican Republic all-inclusive in Punta Cana with a casino, lazy river, nightclub, and swim-up bar at a lively, entertainment-forward property. Secrets Maroma Beach sits on one of the Riviera Maya's most celebrated stretches of sand in Playa Maroma, an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive with an exceptional beach, refined atmosphere, and across-the-board ratings that significantly outpace Breathless. The rating gaps are substantial: overall 9.6 vs 8.8, beach 8.2 vs 6.5, food 8.4 vs 7.6, rooms 9.5 vs 8.6, atmosphere 8.7 vs 7.4, cleanliness 9.7 vs 9.0, and service 9.5 vs 8.9. Breathless counters with a casino and lazy river that Secrets lacks, and appeals to guests who want a livelier, nightlife-driven scene. Secrets Maroma commands its price with a world-class beach and a quieter, more polished experience. If you want a lively Dominican adults-only resort with a casino and lazy river, choose Breathless. If you want consistently superior ratings, a stunning Mexican beach, and refined service, choose Secrets Maroma.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a lively, entertainment-heavy Dominican all-inclusive with a casino, lazy river, nightclub, and swim-up bar at the center of the experience, and are comfortable trading beach and food quality for more activity and energy.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults and couples who prioritize an exceptional beach, high-quality food, immaculate rooms, and polished service in a quieter, more refined Riviera Maya setting, and are willing to pay a premium for one of the best-rated all-inclusives in Mexico.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations are warm year-round. Punta Cana's peak season runs December through April, with hurricane season risk July through October. The Riviera Maya shares a similar pattern, with peak season November through April and hurricane exposure June through November. For Secrets Maroma specifically, avoiding late September and October minimizes storm risk while January through March delivers reliably dry, pleasant conditions at both resorts.","activities":"At Breathless Punta Cana guests can snorkel, dive, play tennis, use the lazy river, hit the casino, and enjoy nightly entertainment and a nightclub on a well-developed resort strip. Secrets Maroma offers diving, snorkelling, tennis, and evening entertainment steps from a world-renowned beach, with the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef accessible nearby. Both properties have full spas, gyms, and swim-up bars. The broader Riviera Maya gives Secrets guests access to cenotes, Tulum, and Cobá ruins."},"dreams-dominicus-la-romana-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Dominicus La Romana is a family all-inclusive on the Dominican Republic's Bayahibe coast, rated 8.7 overall, with a kids club, teen club, waterpark for little kids, babysitting, and rooms for five or more guests. Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun is an adults-only all-inclusive on Mexico's Playa Maroma, rated 9.6 overall, with a near-perfect cleanliness score of 9.7, a room rating of 9.5, and a beach score of 8.2 versus Dreams' 7.8. The rating gaps are substantial across nearly every category: food 8.4 vs 7.2, pool 8.4 vs 6.9, atmosphere 8.7 vs 7.4, and service 9.5 vs 8.8. Dreams holds its own on location (8.8) and value (8.6), and its family infrastructure is far broader. Secrets delivers a measurably more refined, quieter experience on one of the Yucatan Peninsula's finest beach stretches, but admits no children. If you want a full-family Dominican all-inclusive with kids programming and watersports at strong value, choose Dreams. If you want a premium adults-only Mexican retreat with exceptional rooms and one of the Caribbean's best beaches, choose Secrets Maroma.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a well-located Dominican all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, waterpark, babysitting, and large rooms, at a price point that delivers strong value for the category.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples and honeymooners who want an elite-tier Mexican all-inclusive with near-perfect cleanliness, exceptional rooms, a stunning Playa Maroma beach, and a polished, quiet atmosphere without families or children.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Dominicus benefits from the Dominican Republic's year-round warmth, with December through April being the driest and most popular window. Secrets Maroma sits on Mexico's Riviera Maya, where November through May offers the most reliable sunshine and calmest seas. Both destinations carry hurricane risk from July through October, though Bayahibe and Playa Maroma are less frequently impacted than other Caribbean areas.","activities":"Dreams Dominicus guests can dive and snorkel the reefs of Bayahibe, explore nearby Saona Island on excursions, and take advantage of on-site watersports rentals and evening entertainment. Secrets Maroma guests can dive and snorkel Mesoamerican Reef sites, explore the cenotes and ruins of the Yucatan Peninsula, shop and dine in Playa del Carmen, or simply enjoy tennis and spa days on one of Mexico's most celebrated stretches of beach."},"dreams-vista-cancun-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Vista Cancun is a large family all-inclusive in Cancun with a flowrider, waterpark for little kids, teen club, arcade, kids club for under-4s, golf course, and babysitting — built explicitly for multi-generational groups. Secrets Maroma Beach sits on one of the Riviera Maya's most celebrated stretches of sand in adults-only seclusion, and its ratings tell the real story: beach scores 8.2 versus Dreams Vista's 4, atmosphere 8.7 versus 7.1, food 8.4 versus 7.6, and an overall 9.6 versus 8.9. Secrets Maroma costs the same price tier but delivers measurably better execution across nearly every category — cleanliness 9.7, service 9.5, rooms 9.5. Dreams Vista counters with unmatched family infrastructure and respectable value at 8.7, plus rooms that score a solid 9 and an enviable overall cleanliness rating. The tradeoff is straightforward: Dreams Vista is a feature-rich family machine in a busier Cancun setting; Secrets Maroma is a refined, adults-only retreat on a world-class beach where the experience quality justifies every dollar.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a sprawling Cancun all-inclusive with a flowrider, waterpark, arcade, golf, teen club, and babysitting under one roof. The strong room and service scores mean parents are comfortable while kids are fully occupied.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adults seeking a premium, peaceful Riviera Maya escape on one of Mexico's finest beaches. Those who prioritise exceptional food, immaculate rooms, and a high-atmosphere environment over family amenities will find Secrets Maroma consistently over-delivers at its price point.","whenToVisit":"Both properties benefit from the same regional window: November through April brings dry, sunny weather and calmer seas ideal for diving and snorkelling. July and August are busy family peak periods that suit Dreams Vista's crowd-ready infrastructure. Secrets Maroma is best experienced outside school holidays when its adults-only calm is fully uninterrupted.","activities":"Dreams Vista offers flowriding, golf, windsurfing, diving, snorkelling, and watersports rentals alongside evening entertainment and a nightclub. Secrets Maroma covers diving, snorkelling, tennis, and evening entertainment in a more curated package. Both sit within reach of Playa del Carmen, Tulum, and cenote excursions, with the Riviera Maya's reef system accessible from either property."},"dreams-estrella-del-mar-mazatlan-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Estrella del Mar Mazatlán is a large family all-inclusive on Mexico's Pacific coast with a waterpark, lazy river, kids club for under-4s, babysitting, golf course, and evening entertainment. Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun is an adults-only resort on the Riviera Maya with one of the Caribbean's most celebrated beaches, diving, snorkelling, tennis, a nightclub, and consistently higher ratings across nearly every category. Secrets Maroma scores significantly above Dreams Mazatlán in food (8.4 vs 7.6), beach (8.2 vs 6.8), pool (8.4 vs 7.3), atmosphere (8.7 vs 7.5), cleanliness (9.7 vs 9.4), service (9.5 vs 9.2), and location (9.6 vs 8.5), with an overall rating of 9.6 versus 9.0. Dreams Mazatlán counters with a much stronger family infrastructure and meaningful extras like a golf course and waterpark. If you want a Pacific-coast Mexican family all-inclusive with a waterpark, golf, and kids programming at strong value, go to Dreams Mazatlán. If you want a refined adults-only Riviera Maya retreat with an exceptional beach, superior food, and top-tier service ratings, go to Secrets Maroma.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a Pacific-coast Mexico all-inclusive with a waterpark, lazy river, kids club from infants up, babysitting, and a golf course, particularly those who prioritize room quality and value at the $$$ tier.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want an elevated, adults-only Riviera Maya experience anchored by one of Mexico's finest beaches, outstanding food ratings, diving and snorkelling, a nightclub, and some of the highest cleanliness and service scores in the Caribbean.","whenToVisit":"Mazatlán is best visited November through April when Pacific humidity drops and conditions are dry and pleasant; the summer hurricane and rain season runs June through October. Playa Maroma on the Riviera Maya peaks December through April with calm seas and low humidity; hurricane season runs June through November, with September and October carrying the highest risk for both destinations.","activities":"At Dreams Mazatlán guests can golf an on-site course, use the waterpark and lazy river, take yoga classes, and explore Mazatlán's historic centro with its cathedral and Malecón. At Secrets Maroma guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, play tennis, and access nearby Playa del Carmen's boutiques and cenotes. Both resorts offer spa treatments, swim-up bars, and evening entertainment programs."},"dreams-jade-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Jade Resort & Spa is a large family all-inclusive in Puerto Morelos with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, babysitting, archery, fishing, nightclub, and rooms sleeping five or more, rated overall 8.8. Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun is an adults-only all-inclusive on Playa Maroma, rated a notably higher 9.6 overall, with standout scores across beach (8.2 vs 4.8), pool (8.4 vs 6.9), atmosphere (8.7 vs 6.8), room (9.5 vs 8.6), and food (8.4 vs 7.4). The beach gap is the starkest differentiator: Secrets sits on one of the Riviera Maya's most acclaimed stretches of sand, while Dreams Jade's 4.8 beach rating signals a meaningful shortcoming. Secrets also leads on cleanliness (9.7 vs 8.9) and service (9.5 vs 8.8). Dreams Jade wins on family infrastructure and value breadth; Secrets wins on nearly every quality metric for guests who don't need kids programming.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a full-service Mexican Caribbean all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, babysitting, archery, and large rooms sleeping five or more. Those willing to trade beach and food quality ratings for broad family amenities at a competitive price will find Dreams Jade well-suited.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adults seeking a premium adults-only experience on one of the Riviera Maya's finest beaches. Guests who prioritise exceptional rooms, near-flawless service, superior food, and a serene atmosphere over family programming will find Secrets Maroma's across-the-board high ratings consistently justify its price.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit on the Riviera Maya and share the same climate window. December through April delivers dry, sunny conditions with low humidity and the best beach weather. July and August are warm but wetter. Hurricane season runs June through November, with September the peak risk month. Shoulder months like May and early June offer lower rates with generally acceptable weather at both properties.","activities":"Both resorts offer diving, tennis, swim-up bars, spa treatments, nightclub access, and evening entertainment. Dreams Jade adds archery, fishing, a lazy river, and bicycles for guests wanting more daytime variety. Secrets Maroma includes snorkelling directly off its celebrated beach. The broader Puerto Morelos and Playa Maroma corridor provides access to cenote tours, Mesoamerican Barrier Reef snorkelling excursions, and day trips to Tulum and Chichen Itza."},"dreams-karibana-cartagena-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Karibana Cartagena is a family-friendly Colombian all-inclusive on the Caribbean coast with a golf course, kids club, babysitting, and pets allowed, but it struggles meaningfully on beach (4.5), pool (6.9), atmosphere (6.8), and food (7.0) ratings. Secrets Maroma Beach is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on the Riviera Cancun that outscores Dreams Karibana in every single rated category, with standout gaps in beach (8.2 vs 4.5), food (8.4 vs 7.0), atmosphere (8.7 vs 6.8), and an exceptional overall score of 9.6 versus 8.9. Secrets Maroma adds diving, snorkelling, a swim-up bar, and a nightclub to its lineup and sits on one of the Yucatan's most consistently praised beaches. Dreams Karibana's strongest cards are its golf course, family infrastructure, and room quality (9.0), plus the genuine novelty of a Cartagena all-inclusive. If you want a family all-inclusive in Colombia with golf and a kids club, choose Dreams Karibana. If you want a top-tier adults-only beachfront experience in Mexico, Secrets Maroma is clearly the stronger resort across nearly every measurable dimension.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children, golfers, and travelers specifically drawn to Colombia who want a well-appointed all-inclusive near historic Cartagena with babysitting, a kids club, pets allowed, and solid room quality and service scores, and who can accept a weaker beach and pool experience.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travelers who want a premium adults-only all-inclusive on one of Mexico's finest beaches, with top-rated food, service, rooms, and atmosphere, plus diving, snorkelling, a swim-up bar, and nightclub all in one of the Riviera Cancun's most celebrated settings.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Karibana is best visited December through March when Cartagena's dry season brings lower humidity and reliable sunshine; avoid October and November, the wettest months. Secrets Maroma is ideal from November through April during Mexico's dry season when the Caribbean is calm and visibility for diving and snorkelling is at its best; summer months bring heat and occasional hurricane risk.","activities":"At Dreams Karibana, guests can play golf on the on-site course, visit the historic walled city of Cartagena, take boat trips to the Rosario Islands, or explore the local colonial architecture. At Secrets Maroma, guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, visit Mayan ruins at Tulum or Cobá, explore Playa del Carmen, or enjoy the resort's tennis courts and evening nightclub program."},"dreams-macao-beach-punta-cana-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Macao Beach Punta Cana is a large Dominican Republic family all-inclusive on a quieter stretch of Punta Cana beach, loaded with family infrastructure: a kids club for under-4s, a teen club, a lazy river, waterparks for both age groups, babysitting, archery, and rooms that sleep five or more. Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun is an adults-only Mexican luxury resort on one of the Riviera Maya's most celebrated beaches, where the focus is on elevated food (8.4 vs 7.6), immaculate cleanliness (9.7 vs 9.2), and a refined atmosphere (8.7 vs 7.5). Secrets outscores Dreams across nearly every rated category, most notably overall (9.6 vs 9.0), rooms (9.5 vs 9.0), service (9.5 vs 9.0), and pool (8.4 vs 7.4). Dreams earns its place on value (8.7) and as a genuinely comprehensive family operation. If you want a high-amenity Dominican family all-inclusive with waterparks, babysitting, and rooms for large families, go to Dreams Macao. If you want a top-rated adults-only Mexican resort on a stunning beach with superior food, service, and atmosphere, go to Secrets Maroma.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a full-service Dominican all-inclusive with waterparks, a lazy river, kids and teen clubs, babysitting, archery, and large rooms that accommodate five or more guests without stretching the budget uncomfortably.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travelers who want one of the Riviera Maya's highest-rated adults-only resorts, with exceptional service, a world-class beach, superior food and beverage, and immaculate rooms on the famously beautiful Playa Maroma coastline.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations share broadly similar Caribbean climate patterns. Punta Cana and Playa Maroma are best visited from December through April, when rainfall is lowest and humidity manageable. Both carry Atlantic and Pacific storm risk from June through November, with August and September the highest-risk months. Maroma's protected location on Mexico's Caribbean coast offers slightly calmer waters in shoulder season.","activities":"Dreams Macao offers diving, snorkelling, watersports rentals, tennis, archery, yoga, evening entertainment, and a nightclub on-site, with Punta Cana's broader strip of excursions, dune buggies, and cenote trips nearby. Secrets Maroma provides diving, snorkelling, tennis, spa treatments, and evening entertainment, with easy access to Riviera Maya cenotes, Tulum ruins, and Playa del Carmen's dining and shopping scene a short drive away."},"breathless-riviera-cancun-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only all-inclusives on the Riviera Cancun at the same price tier, but their ratings tell very different stories. Secrets Maroma Beach outscores Breathless across every single category: overall 9.6 vs 8.8, food 8.4 vs 7.6, beach 8.2 vs 4.8, pool 8.4 vs 7.4, atmosphere 8.7 vs 7.4, rooms 9.5 vs 8.9, service 9.5 vs 8.9, and cleanliness 9.7 vs 9.1. The beach gap is the most striking: Secrets Maroma sits on one of the Riviera Maya's most celebrated stretches of white-sand beach, scoring 8.2 to Breathless's 4.8. Breathless, in the more developed Caracol area, leans into a livelier, entertainment-forward atmosphere with a nightclub, walk-up restaurants, and a party-oriented vibe. Secrets Maroma adds diving, snorkelling, tennis, and room service to its amenity list, suggesting a more well-rounded, polished offering. For the same price, Secrets Maroma delivers measurably better across food, beach, service, and atmosphere.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a high-energy, nightlife-oriented all-inclusive near Cancun's action, and who prioritize a lively atmosphere, easy restaurant access without reservations, and evening entertainment over beach quality or culinary refinement.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults and couples who want the full premium experience: one of the Riviera Maya's finest beaches, exceptional service scoring 9.5, refined dining, and a calmer, more romantic atmosphere with diving, snorkelling, and tennis rounding out a polished stay.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Riviera Maya's dry season, roughly December through April, when rainfall is minimal and temperatures stay in the low-to-mid 80s Fahrenheit. Peak season runs Christmas through Easter, with higher prices and more crowds. May through November brings heat, humidity, and hurricane risk, though shoulder months like May and November often offer lower rates with still-reasonable weather.","activities":"Both resorts offer spa treatments, swim-up bars, nightclubs, and evening entertainment on-site. Secrets Maroma adds diving, snorkelling, and tennis. Off-property, guests at either resort can reach the Tulum ruins, Cobá archaeological site, and several cenotes within an hour. The Xcaret and Xel-Há eco-parks are accessible day trips, and Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue shopping and dining district is a short drive from both."},"dreams-vallarta-bay-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Vallarta Bay is a family all-inclusive on Mexico's Pacific Coast in Puerto Vallarta, with a kids club for under-4s, teen club, pool slide, babysitting, adult pool, swim-up bar, fishing, diving, and no-reservation restaurants. Secrets Maroma Beach is an adults-only all-inclusive on the Riviera Maya facing the Caribbean, rated substantially higher across nearly every measurable category: overall 9.6 vs 8.9, beach 8.2 vs 6.0, pool 8.4 vs 6.9, food 8.4 vs 7.5, rooms 9.5 vs 8.8, and atmosphere 8.7 vs 7.1. Secrets Maroma sits on one of the most celebrated stretches of white-sand Caribbean beach in Mexico, while Dreams Vallarta Bay trades on its Pacific bay setting and family infrastructure rather than beach or pool quality. Both are priced at the same level, making Secrets Maroma's higher ratings across the board particularly compelling for non-family travelers. If you want a Pacific Coast family resort in Puerto Vallarta with kids programming and a full activity lineup, choose Dreams Vallarta Bay. If you want an adults-only Caribbean retreat with a world-class beach, superior rooms, and markedly better food and atmosphere, choose Secrets Maroma Beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a full-service Puerto Vallarta Pacific Coast all-inclusive with a kids club from infancy, teen programming, pool slide, babysitting, fishing, and no-reservation dining in a well-located bay setting.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples and solo travelers who want an adults-only Riviera Maya all-inclusive with one of the Caribbean's finest beaches, high-end rooms, strong food ratings, and a polished atmosphere, and who are willing to pay the same price for a measurably superior overall experience.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Vallarta Bay suits November through April when Puerto Vallarta's Pacific shoulder season brings dry, warm weather and calmer surf. Secrets Maroma Beach on the Caribbean side also peaks December through April, with clear turquoise water and low humidity. Both resorts see higher prices and availability pressure over US holiday weeks. Maroma's Caribbean coast faces hurricane risk July through October, while Vallarta's Pacific season runs June through October.","activities":"Dreams Vallarta Bay guests can dive, fish, play tennis, and explore Puerto Vallarta's Malecón, old town, and Sierra Madre excursions nearby. Secrets Maroma Beach guests can dive, snorkel Mesoamerican Reef sites, play tennis, and access Playa del Carmen's boutiques and restaurants or Tulum's cenotes and ruins within easy driving distance. Both resorts offer evening entertainment, spa facilities, and swim-up bar access on property."},"dreams-riviera-cancun-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Riviera Cancun and Secrets Maroma Beach are both four-dollar-sign Mexican Riviera Maya all-inclusives, but their ratings and guest profiles diverge sharply. Secrets Maroma leads on nearly every metric: overall 9.6 vs 8.8, beach 8.2 vs 4.8, food 8.4 vs 7.5, room 9.5 vs 8.7, atmosphere 8.7 vs 7.4, and cleanliness 9.7 vs 9.1. The beach gap is the starkest difference, with Maroma consistently ranked among the finest beaches in Mexico while Dreams scores a modest 4.8. Dreams counters with family infrastructure that Secrets entirely lacks: a kids club, teen club, lazy river, pool slide, heated pool, and babysitting service. Dreams also allows restaurant dining without reservations, adding casual flexibility for families. Secrets is adults-only, quieter, and more refined, with higher scores across the board reflecting a more focused, polished experience. At the same price tier, couples choosing between the two are essentially trading a world-class beach and elevated atmosphere at Secrets against the broader family amenity set and still-strong service scores at Dreams.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of any age who want a full-featured Mexican all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, pool slide, and babysitting in a well-rated, clean resort where strong service scores and flexible dining keep everyone comfortable without the pressure of reservations.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adults seeking a premium, quiet all-inclusive experience on one of Mexico's finest beaches, where high scores across food, rooms, atmosphere, and cleanliness combine with an adults-only policy to deliver a genuinely refined Riviera Maya escape at the same price point as family resorts.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Riviera Maya's dry season, running November through April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity is manageable. Peak weeks around Christmas, New Year, and spring break drive prices higher and crowds larger at Dreams in particular given its family orientation. Secrets Maroma warrants early booking year-round given its small size and consistently high demand from couples.","activities":"Both resorts offer diving, snorkelling, spa treatments, a swim-up bar, gym, nightclub, and evening entertainment. Secrets adds tennis courts. Dreams adds a lazy river, pool slide, and extensive kids and teen programming. The surrounding Puerto Morelos and Playa Maroma areas give guests access to the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef for world-class snorkelling, nearby cenotes, Mayan ruins at Cobá and Tulum, and day trips into Cancun's hotel zone."},"secrets-maroma-beach-vs-secrets-wild-orchid-montego-bay":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun and Secrets Wild Orchid Montego Bay are both adults-only luxury all-inclusives at the same price tier, but their ratings tell meaningfully different stories. Maroma Beach leads on nearly every metric: overall (9.6 vs 8.6), beach (8.2 vs 6.8), pool (8.4 vs 7.2), atmosphere (8.7 vs 7.7), room (9.5 vs 8.9), and value (9.1 vs 8.4). The beach gap is particularly striking — Maroma is consistently ranked among the finest beaches in Mexico, while Wild Orchid's Montego Bay waterfront scores notably lower. Wild Orchid edges ahead only on sleep quality (8.8 vs 9.0) and adds a casino and lazy river not found at Maroma, plus restaurants that don't require reservations. Maroma Beach includes snorkelling and free Wi-Fi; Wild Orchid charges for Wi-Fi. Both offer diving, spa, swim-up bar, and nightclub. Maroma is the stronger all-round performer; Wild Orchid suits those drawn specifically to Jamaica or the casino.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and adults who want a near-perfect beach holiday on one of Mexico's most celebrated stretches of sand. The combination of a 9.6 overall rating, spotless rooms, and exceptional service makes Maroma the right pick for guests who won't compromise on beach quality or resort polish.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who specifically want a Jamaican all-inclusive experience and can live with a modest beach. The casino, lazy river, no-reservation dining policy, and strong service scores make Wild Orchid a solid choice, especially for guests who prefer Jamaica's energy and culture over Mexico's beach supremacy.","whenToVisit":"Maroma Beach is best visited November through April, when the Mexican Caribbean is dry, calm, and consistently sunny; hurricane season peaks August to October. Wild Orchid in Montego Bay shares a similar risk window, with Jamaica's peak season running December through April. Both resorts command higher rates in peak winter months, so shoulder season — May or November — offers better value at each property.","activities":"At Maroma Beach, guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, the second-largest barrier reef in the world, and explore nearby Tulum ruins or the cenotes of the Riviera Maya. Wild Orchid guests can take excursions to Dunn's River Falls, try the Hip Strip dining scene in Montego Bay, or head inland for Blue Mountain tours. Both resorts offer on-site tennis, spa treatments, diving, and evening entertainment."},"secrets-maroma-beach-vs-secrets-riviera-cancun-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only, upper-luxury all-inclusives from the Secrets brand on Mexico's Riviera Maya, but their ratings tell very different stories. Secrets Maroma Beach outscores Secrets Riviera Cancun by a full point overall (9.6 vs 8.6), and the gap is most dramatic on beach (8.2 vs 4.8) and pool (8.4 vs 7.1), reflecting Maroma's reputation as one of the finest stretches of Caribbean sand in Mexico. Atmosphere (8.7 vs 7.5), food (8.4 vs 7.7), and location (9.6 vs 8.2) all favor Maroma meaningfully. Room quality is close (9.5 vs 9.0) and service is similarly strong at both (9.5 vs 9.1). Maroma carries a higher price premium that its ratings largely justify, while Riviera Cancun offers a slightly better value score (8.4 vs 9.1 in reverse — Maroma still wins at 9.1). Secrets Riviera Cancun adds no-reservation dining as a practical convenience Maroma lacks. If beach quality is your priority, the gap here is not marginal — it is decisive.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults and couples who place the beach at the center of their holiday and want one of the Riviera Maya's most celebrated stretches of sand, combined with top-tier rooms, atmosphere, and service. Best for those willing to pay a premium for ratings that back up the price across nearly every category.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who want a polished Secrets all-inclusive experience at a somewhat lower price point and value the flexibility of no-reservation dining. Best suited to guests who spend more time at the bar, spa, or in their room than on the beach, and for whom a lower-rated beach is an acceptable trade-off.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit on Mexico's Riviera Maya, where the driest and calmest weather runs November through April. December through March brings the most reliably clear skies and lowest humidity. Hurricane season peaks August through October, carrying higher risk of rain and rough surf — a particular concern at Secrets Riviera Cancun given its already lower beach rating during calmer months.","activities":"Both resorts offer spa treatments, swim-up bars, gyms, evening entertainment, and nightclubs on-site. Secrets Maroma adds diving, snorkelling, and tennis not listed at Riviera Cancun. Off-property, both sit within reach of Tulum's ruins, Xcaret and Xel-Há eco-parks, cenote swimming, and Playa del Carmen's shops and restaurants, all accessible by taxi or organized excursion from the Riviera Maya corridor."},"dreams-aventuras-riviera-maya-vs-secrets-maroma-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Aventuras Riviera Maya is a family-focused all-inclusive in Puerto Aventuras with a waterpark, kids clubs for all ages, babysitting, arcade, and rooms for five or more guests. Secrets Maroma Beach Riviera Cancun is an adults-only all-inclusive on one of the Riviera Maya's most acclaimed beaches, where every major rating category outpaces Dreams Aventuras by a meaningful margin. The beach gap is stark: Secrets scores 8.2 versus Dreams Aventuras's 5.3, reflecting Maroma's world-class stretch of sand against Puerto Aventuras's more modest shoreline. Food (8.4 vs 7.0), pool (8.4 vs 6.6), atmosphere (8.7 vs 6.9), and room quality (9.5 vs 8.6) all follow the same pattern. Overall, Secrets scores 9.6 against Dreams Aventuras's 8.9. Dreams Aventuras trades those gaps for family infrastructure the adults-only Secrets simply cannot offer. If you want a family-oriented Mexican all-inclusive with waterparks, kids clubs, and babysitting at a strong value, go to Dreams Aventuras. If you want one of the Riviera Maya's top-rated adults-only experiences on a genuinely exceptional beach, go to Secrets Maroma Beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who need kids clubs, babysitting, a waterpark, an arcade, and large-capacity rooms. The strong service score of 9.0 and no-reservation restaurant policy make logistics easier when travelling with young children.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travellers who want a high-end, adults-only Riviera Maya experience on one of the Caribbean's standout beaches. Near-perfect ratings across cleanliness, rooms, location, and service make this a strong choice for honeymoons and milestone trips.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Riviera Maya's dry season from December through April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity is lower. July and August bring family travel peaks to Dreams Aventuras. Secrets Maroma is worth considering in May or early June for lower rates before hurricane season intensifies, while still catching reliable beach weather.","activities":"At Dreams Aventuras, guests can dive, snorkel, and use the waterparks on site, with Puerto Aventuras marina nearby for fishing and the Aktun Chen nature park a short drive away. Secrets Maroma offers diving, snorkelling, and tennis, with Playa Maroma itself a draw, and Tulum's ruins, cenotes, and Sian Ka'an biosphere reserve all accessible within an hour's drive from either property."}}
